<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rally / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-term bond prices jumped Tuesday on hopes  
that interest rates might stay at their low levels for the time 
being. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 15/16  
point, or $9.38 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, fell to 5.52 percent from 5.59 percent 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations that Federal Reserve policy-makers did not adopt a  
bias toward tightening rates at their meeting last week helped 
bolster bond prices. Higher rates would hurt the value of bonds, 
which pay a fixed rate of return. Hopes that the European Central 
Bank and the Bank of England may cut rates this week also helped 
lift bond prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the gains were concentrated in the long-term bond. In  
the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities were 
up between 1/32 point and 5/32 point, and intermediate maturities 
were up 7/32 point to 15/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.39 percent as the  
discount rose 0.01 percentage point from the auction Monday to 4.28 
percent. Six-month yields were 4.51 percent, as the discount was 
unchanged from the weekly auction at 4.35 percent. One-year yields 
were 4.64 percent as the discount fell by 0.01 percentage point 
from late Monday to 4.42 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.50 percent from 4.75 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose to 124 3/8 from 124 1/8. The average yield to 
maturity fell to 5.22 percent from 5.24 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
