<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Junior' Gotti Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Like father, like son -- John A.  
``Junior'' Gotti is headed for jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti, the 35-year-old son of America's best-known Mafioso,  
pleaded guilty Monday night to racketeering, bribery and other 
charges and will spend five to seven years in prison. Jury 
selection in his trial was to have begun today in federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors proudly declared victory against the Gambino crime  
family. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of us are naive enough to think you don't have to remain  
vigilant because there are obviously other Gambino members and 
associates out there,'' U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said. ``But in 
terms of what it does to the leadership and the power, I think it 
can't be overstated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti also was fined $1 million and must forfeit $1 million in  
cash and property that prosecutors say are proceeds from his 
criminal ventures. He could have been sentenced to 15 years in 
prison and fined millions. 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti, who remains free on $10 million bail, said nothing as he  
exited the courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing was scheduled for July 8. Prosecutors said the term  
will range between five years and ten months, and seven years and 
two months. Defense attorneys said they will not challenge the 
judge's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti was accused of succeeding his father, John J. Gotti, at  
the top of the Gambino family after the elder Gotti was sent to 
prison for life in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the charges -- robbery, loansharking, gambling and  
bribery -- stemmed from an alleged extortion scheme at the Manhattan 
topless club Scores. Thirty-nine other people have pleaded guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Gotti admitted to bribing a union official,  
conspiring with others to commit extortion, supervising illegal 
gambling activities and filing a false income tax return. 
</P>
<P>
	``I conspired with a group of individuals forming an  
association,'' Gotti told Judge Barrington Parker, though he did 
not mention the Gambino family. 
</P>
<P>
	He entered the plea after learning that federal prosecutors had  
planned to indict him on income tax and loansharking charges, 
defense attorney Gerald Shargel said. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Gotti) found himself in a no-win situation,'' Shargel said.  
``If he was convicted, he would be sentenced to time in jail. If he 
was acquitted, it would be like the Old West: Every prosecutor in 
the area would be gunning for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Gotti, known as the Teflon Don for avoiding conviction  
in three trials, was found guilty in 1992 in a racketeering case 
that alleged five murders -- including that of his predecessor, Paul 
Castellano -- and featured the Mafia's highest-ranking turncoat, 
Salvatore ``Sammy the Bull'' Gravano. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the entire indictment against ``Junior,'' there was no  
mention of murder. No cement shoes, no sleeping with the fishes, no 
kiss on the lips followed by a bullet to the head. There wasn't 
even any leg-breaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that kind of mob case,'' said Ronald Goldstock,  
former director of the state Organized Crime Task Force. ``You 
might not get those much anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So many Mafia leaders are in prison and so many mobsters are  
willing to cooperate that it's difficult now to carry out ``the 
kind of blatant criminal activity people associate with organized 
crime,'' Goldstock said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the younger Gotti's case is less glamorous, so is the  
defendant himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Junior,'' whose father also was called the Dapper Don for his  
fine suits and silvery hair, has gone to court in sneakers and 
jeans. Unlike his swaggering father, he rushes past the cameras and 
talks to reporters in half-sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Gotti asked to be jailed during the trial so he  
wouldn't have to pay the $24,000 monthly cost of round-the-clock 
security guards that were a condition of his release on bail. He 
withdrew that request Monday because the judge ruled that he didn't 
have to pay for guards during the trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
