<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Portals Slow in Future Online Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Online retailers may be using Internet gateways now  
to increase their exposure on the Web, but they won't be able to 
rely on these relationships for huge sales growth in coming years, 
a new study has found. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, released today by Internet research firm Jupiter  
Communications Co., said that retailers should expect electronic 
commerce from these entry points to the Internet, known as portals, 
to account for only 20 percent of online retail revenues by 2002, 
up slightly from a projected 18 percent in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the New York-based Jupiter estimates that online  
retail sales generated by portal sites will represent $2.4 billion 
out of the $13 billion in total sales, and $8.7 billion out of 
$43.7 billion in revenues in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Through portals such as Yahoo!, Excite and Lycos, consumers can  
search the Internet as well as find a wealth of online services 
such as free e-mail, news, chat and personalized functions like 
stock quotes, local weather and sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Since they have become such popular destination sites on the  
Web, portals have cut expensive, multiyear ``tenancy'' deals with a 
wide array of online merchants to market and refer shoppers to 
their sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Portals have also been fueling much of the Internet merger mania  
on Wall Street in recent months as online companies have been eager 
to align themselves with the powerful portals. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Jupiter questions the role these Internet entry points  
will play for online merchants in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``While they offer an effective means to drive traffic, primary  
portals do not help commerce players retain customers,'' said Marc 
Johnson, director of Jupiter's Digital Commerce Strategies research 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet retailers are locked in a fierce battle to obtain  
customers who will return to their site when they are shopping 
online. 
</P>
<P>
	To achieve this goal, Jupiter is encouraging retailers to expand  
their distribution and marketing efforts, including more 
advertising off-line and aligning with sites representing specific 
customers and consumer interests. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was based on interviews with 36 Internet retailing  
executives with portal agreements, along with Jupiter's own 
consumer research. It was released at the Jupiter Online Shopping 
Forum in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Of those online merchants surveyed, about 92 percent said portal  
deals help expose their sites to a wide audience, but more than 60 
percent noted that only one-third of the sales that result can be 
attributed to the portal deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than 5 percent of the merchants surveyed said they were  
likely to renew their current portal agreements. That does not mean 
they will abandon the portals, but they will reevaluate their 
deals, Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the study's findings, portal executives still believe  
that retailers won't be able to find a better way to market 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``Virtually anyone who has built a successful retail site has  
done it through a portal one way or another,'' said Bob Davis, 
president and chief executive of Lycos. ``I don't think there is an 
effective way or an affordable way to build visibility to your site 
without that portal relationship.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
