<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MLS Bans Enhancement Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Major League Soccer banned anabolic steroids and  
human growth hormone today and expects to begin testing players by 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Doug Logan said the league added six categories to  
its list of banned substances, including erythropoietin (EPO), an 
endurance-boosting hormone that increases the blood's ability to 
carry oxygen. 
</P>
<P>
	EPO is a favorite of some cyclists and was at the center of the  
Tour de France drug scandal last year. 
</P>
<P>
	However, scientifically reliable tests have not been perfected  
for some substances, such as EPO, but are expected to be available 
by next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because we cannot test for them, doesn't mean shouldn't  
be making statement that these substances should be banned,'' Logan 
said during a conference call. ``They violate the ethics of 
competitive sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MLS already tests every league and team employee, including  
players, once a year by urinalysis for 10 kinds of illegal drugs, 
including cocaine, marijuana, amphetamines and barbiturates. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's policy change added steroids, stimulants (other than  
caffeine or medications approved by the league), EPO, human growth 
hormone, chorionic gonadotrophin (another human growth hormone), 
and diuretics (used to mask drugs). 
</P>
<P>
	MLS operations manager William Ordower said the 3-year-old  
league has been considering adding such substances for a few years. 
However, the league decided to go forward after a recommendation of 
Dr. Ian Macdonald, who also advises the International Olympic 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making the announcement now to give our players a full  
season to change their habits if any did rely on it,'' Ordower 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
