<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                             *John Bibb    	
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- John Bibb, retired sports editor for The  
Tennessean, who once was nominated for Pulitzer Prize and covered 
36 straight Masters golf tournaments, died Sunday of cancer. He was 
72. 
</P>
<P>
	Bibb, a member of the Tennessee Sports Hall of Fame and a  
two-time president of the Golf Writers Association of America, 
worked for The Tennessean from 1942 until his retirement in 1993. 
He was sports editor for the last 23 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Bibb covered numerous U.S. Opens and PGA Championships, the  
British Open and Ryder Cup matches. He covered his first Masters in 
1949. 
</P>
<P>
	Bibb later crossed over into radio. He was a sports commentator  
on WSM's ``Waking Crew'' program and later joined the 
``Roundtable'' program, where he offered views on politics and 
other topics. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife of nearly 50 years, Betty Jean; a son  
and a granddaughter. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Gary Blonston    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gary Blonston, chief of the Knight Ridder  
Washington bureau, whose journalism career spanned more than three 
decades, died Sunday of cancer. He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston served as reporter, editor and writing coach in his  
nearly 36 years in the field. He worked at The Miami Herald, the 
Detroit Free Press and the San Jose Mercury News before coming to 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston was a principal writer on two Pulitzer Prize-winning  
projects. One was during his time at the Free Press, where he came 
under gunfire while covering Detroit's 1967 riots. Blonston also 
worked on the Mercury News' reporting of the 1989 Loma Prieta 
earthquake in the San Francisco Bay area. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1968, Blonston found himself in the middle of rioting  
protesters and police officers outside the Democratic National 
Convention. Coughing from tear gas, he dictated his story to an 
editor on deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston also freelanced for newspapers and magazines, on topics  
ranging from politics to prehistoric art. During a 1967 strike at 
the Free Press -- when Blonston was working at Chrysler Corp. -- he 
wrote a book on the history of the Plymouth. In 1996, he published 
``William Morris,'' a book about a famed glass blower. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston began his newspaper career with The Miami Herald in  
1964, moving to the Free Press two years later. He moved to San 
Jose in 1987, then to Knight Ridder's Washington bureau. He became 
bureau chief in August 1995, supervising a staff of 60 reporters 
and editors. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston is survived by his wife, Susan Goldberg, a deputy  
managing editor at USA Today; two children from a previous 
marriage; and a sister. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Corwin Dwight Denney    	
</P>
<P>
	PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Corwin Dwight Denney, an aerospace  
engineer who initially flight-tested his own products, died April 1 
of pneumonia, following a battle with cancer. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Denney began manufacturing aerospace components and flight-test  
equipment in 1947 when he founded American Helicopter Co. He was 
the company's lone test pilot until he was joined by several World 
War II veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, renamed Mid-Continent Manufacturing, was soon  
commissioned by the federal government to create complex aircraft 
structures and nondestructive test materials. That money enabled 
Denney to merge with tiny Pasadena-based Automation Instruments in 
1952 to form Automation Industries Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	He orchestrated a score of mergers during his three decades as  
president, chairman of the board and chief executive officer of 
Automation Industries, which he sold to General Cable in 1978 for 
$106 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1962, he branched off into oil drilling, forming the  
independent San Antonio-based Venus Oil Co. He later invested in 
the Beverly Wilshire Hotel in Beverly Hills, helping to restore it 
to profitability before selling his share in 1985 for $33 million. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Giulio Einaudi    	
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Giulio Einaudi, an Italian publisher, died Monday of  
a heart attack. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	A doctor, Einaudi founded the liberal publishing firm that bears  
his name in 1933 and made it into an important force in Italy's 
intellectual life. 
</P>
<P>
	Einaudi wrote books on literature, history, philosophy, art and  
science. He was also a collector of rare books and prints. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Deil Gustafson    	
</P>
<P>
	CANNON FALLS, Minn. (AP) -- Deil Gustafson, a former owner of  
Summit Banks in the Twin Cities and the Tropicana Hotel and Casino, 
a Las Vegas complex with a history of ties to organized crime, died 
Friday. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death was not available.  
</P>
<P>
	The former businessman and real estate magnate spent 40 months  
in federal prison in the mid-1980s after being convicted of 
participating in a financial scam involving the Tropicana and his 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gustafson sold the Tropicana in 1979, but was under  
investigation as recently as the mid-1990s for allegedly trying to 
hide millions of dollars in proceeds from the sale of the casino. 
He pleaded guilty to bankruptcy fraud in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He was deputy director of Hubert Humphrey's 1960 presidential  
campaign. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Peter Pellegrino    	
</P>
<P>
	NEWTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- Peter Pellegrino, a pilot and ballooning  
enthusiast who trained military air traffic controllers during 
World War II, died March 26 at age 82. 
</P>
<P>
	He played a key role in creating an early national ballooning  
organization, the Balloon Federation of America. Today, the group 
is made up of 100 local clubs with more than 4,000 individual 
members. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Ambroise Roux    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Ambroise Roux, an influential business leader who  
was a close adviser to President Georges Pompidou, died Sunday of a 
heart attack. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Roux was the chief executive officer of one of France's largest  
companies, the Compagnie Generale d'Electricite, for 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting in 1963, Roux wielded considerable power in French  
business and political circles as head of CGE, an industrial group 
now known as Alcatel. 
</P>
<P>
	Roux was close to a number of French politicians, most notably  
Pompidou, whom he advised during a time of enormous growth in 
France's industrial sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Roux worked for a series of government ministries during the  
1950s and then moved to private business, where he fought for lower 
corporate taxes and greater independence for France's corporate 
sector. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Early Wynn    	
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Hall of Fame baseball pitcher Early Wynn, a  
300-game winner and one of the fiercest competitors of his time, 
died Sunday from complications related to a stroke. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynn pitched from 1939 to 1963, winning 20 games or more for the  
Cleveland Indians four times and once for the Chicago White Sox in 
the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 23-11 in 1954, when the Indians won the American League  
pennant with 111 wins in a 154-game season. In 1959, he won the Cy 
Young Award for the pennant-winning White Sox, posting a 22-10 
record at age 39. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynn returned to the Indians at age 43 and won his 300th game on  
July 13, 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	After he retired, Wynn was a pitching coach for the Indians and  
Minnesota Twins. He was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1972. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Lucille Lortel    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lucille Lortel, who earned the title ``Queen of  
off-Broadway'' for bringing innovative new actors, playwrights and 
productions to the American stage, died Sunday. She was 98. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lortel, whose career in theater spanned more than 70 years,  
produced or co-produced about 500 plays, five of which were 
nominated for Tony Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lortel, born Louise Wadler, began her own acting career in  
the 1920s and made her Broadway debut in 1925 with a small role in 
George Bernard Shaw's ``Caesar and Cleopatra,'' starring Helen 
Hayes and Lionel Atwill. 
</P>
<P>
	She quit performing in 1939 to please her husband, Louis  
Schweitzer, a chemical engineer who made a fortune manufacturing 
cigarette papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Out of boredom, she began staging readings in a barn at their  
estate in Westport, Conn. In 1947, she was asked by the actor 
Canada Lee and playwright Philip Huston to help find a place and 
audience for a staged reading of a new play, ``The Painted Wagon,'' 
and the still-thriving White Barn Theater was born. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1955, her husband gave her the Theatre de Lys -- now called  
the Lucille Lortel Theater -- in Greenwich Village as a 24th 
anniversary gift. Its first production was a hugely popular 
adaptation of Bertolt Brecht's and Kurt Weill's ``Threepenny 
Opera'' that made off-Broadway famous. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lortel's eye for and confidence in young talent boosted the  
careers of countless actors, composers, designers, directors and 
playwrights in international theater. She established numerous 
funds and fellowships to further the arts. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
