<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Tombstone' Fund Takes Grave Turn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The next time you are tempted to invest in a  
mutual fund with a clever-sounding gimmick, visualize a tombstone. 
</P>
<P>
	That scary association may serve in a general way to remind you  
of the perils inherent in any fund that sacrifices diversification 
for a portfolio organized around a single theme. More specifically, 
it may call to mind a real-life fund that was far and away the 
worst-performing stock fund in the first quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	In the January-March period, the Houston-based Pauze Tombstone  
Fund, which describes itself as ``the first-of-its kind death care 
industry mutual fund,'' posted a negative return of 50.65 percent, 
according to the research firm of Lipper Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Its loss outstripped by more than 20 percentage points the next  
worst performer, the ProFunds Ultra Short OTC Fund, whose specialty 
of betting against the market suffered as market indicators were 
reaching new highs. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past 12 months, the Tombstone Fund dropped 54.30  
percent, according to Lipper, to rank as the third-worst performer 
in the fund universe -- behind the Lexington Troika Russia Fund, 
which felt the full weight of the economic collapse in Russia, and 
the maverick American Heritage Fund, which has been amassing a 
horrendous record for years now. American Heritage's five-year 
return, according to Lipper, is minus 72.28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The premise behind the Pauze Tombstone Fund may strike you as a  
decent-sounding idea. Launched in May 1997 by Pauze Swanson Capital 
Management Co. in Houston, the fund is built around the firm's 
index of stocks in the businesses of funeral services, cemetery 
services and funeral and cemetery support goods and services. 
</P>
<P>
	The firm's promotional materials made a persuasive-sounding  
case: ``Death-care stocks'' had posted years of strong performance 
since the '80s; industry consolidation, still in its early stages, 
held out the promise of a continuing brisk pace of mergers and 
takeovers; foreign growth prospects seemed bright, and the U.S. 
population continued to age. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the heading of ``Compelling Demographic Factors,'' the  
fund's literature cited projections that the number of deaths in 
this country would rise from 2.2 million in 1990 to 4.1 million by 
2040. 
</P>
<P>
	So what has gone wrong lately? Well, shares of the biggest  
funeral services company, Service Corp. International, have tumbled 
in response to an unexpected earnings decline, and other companies 
in this relatively small field have sounded echoes of the same kind 
of problems. From a 12-month high of about $47, SCI shares recently 
hovered just above $13, and the company's president has resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently, deaths are not occurring at quite the expected rate.  
And when people do die, survivors seem to have become more choosy 
and price-conscious than they used to be about death services. 
</P>
<P>
	All this may prove to be just a temporary spell of trouble in  
the business. Quite a few analysts argue that Wall Street has 
overreacted to the recent negative news, and it's entirely possible 
that death-service stocks are bargain-priced now. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, it's not as though legions of investors suffered  
from the Tombstone Fund's woes. According to Lipper, the fund's 
total assets at last word were only about $500,000. That's tiny by 
any standard, in a world where stock fund assets in the aggregate 
exceed $3 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
	But none of those points overshadows the big problem with a fund  
like Pauze Tombstone. It is just one of a growing breed of niche 
funds organized in recent years, focusing on fields ranging from 
golf and auto racing to the Internet and other technology 
specialties. 
</P>
<P>
	These funds naturally appeal to people who like investments that  
come with a story. But unlike most general purpose stock funds, 
they lack the cushion of diversification. If the script around 
which they are organized takes an unexpected plot twist of any 
kind, as happened to Pauze Tombstone, they can find themselves with 
no place to hide. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
