<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollars Sold Off in Money Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Traders sold off the dollar and bought major  
European currencies Tuesday as Yugoslavia announced a unilateral 
cease-fire in its battle against Kosovo rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also fell against the yen, dragged along as traders  
bought the currencies of important economies near Yugoslavia. The 
British pound was at 18-month lows against the dollar until the 
announcement helped it recoup most of its loss. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0848, up  
from $1.0708 late Monday. The dollar also was quoted at 120.62 
Japanese yen, down from 121.83 yen. The British pound was quoted at 
$1.5911, down from $1.6000 late Monday but higher than its low 
Tuesday of $1.5851. 
</P>
<P>
	The cease-fire was announced hours after the most intensive  
night of NATO air raids across Yugoslavia. The Yugoslav government 
called the cease-fire a ``gesture of goodwill'' in advance of 
Sunday's Orthodox Easter. However, the action was rejected as a 
sham by Western leaders and the bombings were to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, considered a safe-haven currency during times of  
turmoil, had been rising against the euro since the bombings began 
on March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a pretty quiet day until we got those reports from  
Yugoslavia announcing the cease-fire,'' said Henry Willmore, a 
senior economist at Barclays Capital. ``It's definitely an 
indication that the foreign exchange market has taken the euro down 
on concerns about conflicts in Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Willmore said the euro also rose because of a late afternoon  
news report that France's central banker, who also sits on the 
European Central Bank's board, was warning against a weaker euro. 
The new currency, representing 11 countries tethered by the 
European Central Bank, has mostly fallen since its January launch. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank's policy-making committee meets this week and  
the French warning could make it reluctant to lower interest rates 
to spur the lagging European economies. Typically, lower interest 
rates make returns on a country's or a region's currency and assets 
less appealing to foreign investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4729 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4895, and 1.5016 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5020. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro no  
longer are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed 
rate. Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8031 
German marks, down from 1.8265; 6.0459 French francs, down from 
6.1275; and 1,785.71 Italian lire, down from 1,808.32. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
