<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kazak Currency Plummets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALMATY, Kazakstan (AP) -- The Kazak currency nosedived Monday in  
the wake of the government's decision to allow it to trade freely, 
and residents of the former Soviet republic rushed to buy foreign 
currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The tenge, which had long held steady at about 88 to the dollar,  
fell to 100 on the state-controlled currency market Monday. The 
government and the central bank decided Sunday to stop supporting 
the currency because it was depleting the Central Asian nation's 
foreign currency reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	Currency exchange offices quickly closed their doors Monday  
after a wave of panic dollar buying, and the black market rate 
plunged to 200 tenge to the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people rushed to the banks, trying to withdraw their tenge  
deposits and convert them to hard currency. There were long lines 
at many bank offices, but all of them were giving cash without 
restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The government tried to quell the panic by promising to convert  
all bank savings into hard currency if depositors agree to freeze 
their accounts for nine months. The state-controlled media have run 
reports about black market dealers trading in fake dollar bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail prices on most staples remained virtually unchanged, but  
many vendors suspended wholesale operations, waiting for the 
currency to stabilize. 
</P>
<P>
	The government hopes the tenge will recover quickly thanks to a  
new rule obliging exporters to sell 50 percent of their hard 
currency earnings on the currency market. 
</P>
<P>
	Exporters hailed the government's decision to stop supporting  
the currency, saying the artificially high tenge rate was hurting 
their business. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazakstan's economy has suffered since the global financial  
crisis hit Russia, its northern neighbor and largest trade partner, 
last August. About 40 percent of Kazakstan's trade is with Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 7 million of Kazakstan's 16 million people live in  
poverty, and unemployment is widespread. Increasing numbers of 
businesses are going bankrupt. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazakstan is heavily dependent on the sale of oil for much of  
its state revenue. With world oil prices low, the government has 
already had to revise budget projections for 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:29:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Inflation Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian inflation was down to 2.8 percent last  
month, the lowest level since a financial crisis hit last August, 
but other indicators released today painted a gloomy economic 
picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is looking to the International Monetary Fund to help  
revive its economy, and an IMF team was to arrive today to assess 
the country's suitability for a new loan. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides have agreed in principle on a loan, but the amount  
is unclear. Russian officials have said they are hoping for $8 
billion, but the IMF has refrained from giving any figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Statistics Committee said the 2.8 percent inflation  
last month was the best performance since prices began jumping in 
the wake of an economic upheaval eight months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has not printed large sums of money to pay its  
debts, as some economists feared, and this has helped limit 
inflation in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, prices have gone up 16 percent in the first three months  
of this year after soaring 84 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also is having difficulties collecting taxes for  
the budget, a chronic problem that has left the state unable to pay 
salaries, pensions and other debts on time. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's budget revenues were $1.3 billion in March,  
while expenditures were $1.5 billion, the Ministry of Finance said. 
Both numbers were well below the target figures and were extremely 
small for a country of Russia's size. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Russian currency hit a new low of 25.11 rubles to  
the U.S. dollar, managing a tiny improvement today to 25.10, as set 
by the Central Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruble has resumed its slide in recent weeks, and the  
government has been running low on the hard currency reserves it 
traditionally uses to defend the Russian currency. 
</P>
<P>
	With its hard currency supply dwindling, Russia has acknowledged  
it won't be able to pay back more than half of the $17.5 billion in 
foreign loans that fall due this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
