<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 23:13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Sale To Be Decided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- After months of juggling finances and weeks of  
intense lobbying, Howard Milstein was to find out today whether he 
would achieve his goal of owning the Washington Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	Or whether he would become the first prospective buyer rejected  
by NFL owners in a bid for an established franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	While it's been notoriously difficult to project the votes of  
the 31 owners on anything from instant replay to expansion, it 
appeared Tuesday night that Milstein and bid partner Daniel Snyder 
did not have the support of the 24 owners needed to purchase the 
Redskins for a record $800 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's special meeting was arranged after Milstein requested a  
postponement during last month's sessions in Phoenix. In Arizona, 
it become apparent he did not have enough votes and would need to 
spend more time lobbying individual owners. 
</P>
<P>
	One league source, speaking on condition of anonymity, told The  
Associated Press that Milstein had no more than seven to 10 votes 
in Phoenix and is still ``far short'' of the three-fourths 
required. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote could hinge on a recommendation from commissioner Paul  
Tagliabue and the league's financial committee, which will meet 
before the vote. The eight-member committee was split 3-3 with two 
abstentions in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee chairman Bob Kraft, owner of the New England Patriots,  
has been one of the bid's few solid supporters. But committee 
members Tom Benson of New Orleans and Pat Bowlen of Denver are 
adamantly opposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Some owners, such as Baltimore's Art Modell, expressed concern  
that the Redskins would be left in limbo if the bid is rejected. It 
could take several months to come up with a new prospective buyer 
if the league asks for another round of bidding, and possibly 
several years to resolve a court battle if Milstein sues. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the objections by some owners:  
</P>
<P>
	--While Milstein is worth an estimated $500 million, most of it  
is tied up in real estate, making his part of the bid heavily 
leveraged without the ready cash to back it up. His father recently 
agreed to supply $125 million to support the bid, but some league 
officials reportedly consider that money a loan that helps the 
financing arrangement only marginally. 
</P>
<P>
	--Milstein's part-ownership of the NHL's Islanders, which he  
bought with a partner just 14 months ago, has been ugly and 
litigious. Milstein wanted a new arena and threatened to cancel 
games because he felt the old one was unsafe. There are lawsuits 
pending between Milstein and New York's Nassau County. 
</P>
<P>
	--Milstein, according to several sources, solicited politicians  
in the nation's capital to lobby owners on his behalf. Sources say 
several owners considered it a high-handed impropriety when they 
received calls from congressmen from other parts of the country 
asking about the Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	--Several owners have expressed a preference for Cooke's son,  
team president John Kent Cooke, to own the team. John Kent Cooke 
was outbid by Milstein and Snyder in an auction conducted by the 
trustees of his father's estate -- in accordance with his father's 
will after his death on April 6, 1997 -- but sources say some owners 
are eager to make the point they alone can choose who joins their 
exclusive club. 
</P>
<P>
	If Milstein is rejected and the trustees reopen the bidding, the  
favorite to win the second round would be Snyder. The 
Washington-area communications executive has the money in the bank 
and has come through the NFL process unscathed. Snyder could team 
with a losing bidder from the first round, such as Phoenix 
developer Sam Grossman, to mount a formidable bid. 
</P>
<P>
	But all that becomes moot if a defeated Milstein goes to court  
and ties up the process, although Milstein told the owners in 
Phoenix he would not sue. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless the sale is approved, John Kent Cooke will continue to  
run the team, retaining coach Norv Turner and general manager 
Charley Casserly. 
</P>
<P>
	Several free agents said they were wary of signing with the  
Redskins because of the uncertainty, and the players under contract 
want the matter resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those things that has gone on too long,'' center  
Cory Raymer said Tuesday. ``And it's become a pain in the butt.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
