<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racing Dad, Daughter in Wheelchairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Race car driver Al Unser Jr. knows the  
wheelchair he's in is temporary. He's hoping that will be the case 
for his 12-year-old daughter, Cody. 
</P>
<P>
	While Unser recovers from injuries suffered in a race in Florida  
last month, his daughter is battling transverse-myelitis, a 
disorder that has left her paralyzed from the chest down. The 
problem occurs when nerve impulse transmission up and down the 
spinal cord is blocked. 
</P>
<P>
	Dad and daughter are both using wheelchairs these days to get  
around the Unser household and also getting in some quality time 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's teaching me wheelies,'' Cody said. ``I'm teaching him how  
to get around in the house better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cody, a sixth-grader, was stricken while playing basketball in  
February. She spent more than three weeks at the Barrow 
Neurological Institute in Phoenix before returning home. 
</P>
<P>
	Unser fractured both bones in his right ankle and sprained his  
left knee in the accident March 21 at Homestead, Fla., in the first 
race of the season. He expects to be back in a race car by the end 
of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	The outlook for his daughter, who is undergoing treatment at  
Carrie Tingley Hospital in Albuquerque, is more uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's looking really healthy,'' Unser said. ``She's really  
upbeat about everything and that's great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Basketball remains a passion for Cody and the family has set up  
a miniature goal in the driveway of their Albuquerque home. Cody, 
her dad and 16-year-old brother, Albert, have been playing 
wheelchair basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the same,'' Cody said. ``What I miss the most is  
playing basketball with my sixth-grade friends.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
