<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Della Reese Helps CBS Win the Week / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The next time actress Della Reese seeks a raise  
from CBS, she may want to keep a copy of last week's Nielsen Media 
Research ratings for ammunition. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Secret Path,'' a CBS Sunday night movie that starred Reese  
and Ossie Davis, was the second most-watched show of the week, 
Nielsen said Tuesday. Tied for third place was ``Touched By an 
Angel,'' also starring Reese. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS, involved in a tight race with NBC for season dominance, had  
a 9.0 rating and 16 share to win the week. NBC was second with an 
8.4 rating and 15 share, though it led among 18- to 49-year-olds, 
the audience advertisers covet. ABC had a 7.1 rating and 12 share 
and Fox had a 5.5 rating and 9 share. 
</P>
<P>
	The men's NCAA basketball championship game between Connecticut  
and Duke was the week's most-watched program. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a lackluster week, ABC was pleased that its two newest  
comedies, ``The Norm Show'' and ``It's Like, You Know,'' managed 
the unusual feat of getting higher ratings during their second 
showings than on their premieres a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox's new comedy, ``Futurama,'' also did well, though it dropped  
off from its premiere. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's first major television interview since his  
impeachment trial, with Dan Rather on ``60 Minutes II,'' had an 
average audience of 12 million people. That was approximately one 
quarter the audience for Monica Lewinsky's interview with Barbara 
Walters nearly a month earlier. However, CBS had less than 24 hours 
notice that Clinton would give the interview, so there was little 
time to promote it, and most of the talk was about matters other 
than the sex scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the emerging networks, the WB had a 2.7 rating and 5  
share, UPN had a 1.9 rating and 3 share and Pax TV had a 0.8 rating 
and 1 share. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Nightly News'' eked out a victory in the evening news  
race with an 8.1 rating and 17 share. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' 
had an 8.0 rating and 17 share and the ``CBS Evening News'' was at 
6.8 and 15. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of March 29-April 4, the top 10 shows, their  
networks and ratings were the ``NCAA Basketball Championship: 
Connecticut vs. Duke,'' CBS, 17.2; ``CBS Sunday Movie: The Secret 
Path,'' CBS, 14.7; ``Frasier,'' NBC, 12.6; ``Friends,'' NBC, 12.6; 
``Touched By an Angel,'' CBS, 12.6, ``Jesse,'' NBC, 12.0; ``ER,'' 
NBC, 11.8; ``The Drew Carey Show,'' ABC, 11.6; ``Dateline 
NBC-Tuesday,'' NBC, 11.4; ``Prelude to a Championship,'' CBS, 11.2; 
''Veronica's Closet,'' NBC, 11.2. 

</P>
</TEXT>
