<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 43.84 at 9,963.49 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Gillette Corp. provided the latest sobering  
influence for a giddy stock market Tuesday, sending prices lower 
with a warning that it will fall short of analysts' expectations 
for first-quarter earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette's announcement deflated the rally that sent the Dow  
Jones industrial average to a new record Monday. The Dow fell 43.84 
points Tuesday to close at 9,963.49. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader market indicators were mostly lower, although the Dow  
sustained the sharpest losses. Barry Hyman, senior equity analyst 
at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum, said Gillette's bad news illustrated 
the recent split between the fortunes of the blue-chip companies 
and the Internet upstarts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a two-tiered market,'' he said. ``It has been for  
quite some time, and as long as the Gillettes, the Cokes, keep 
coming out with warnings, it will remain so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the blue chips propelled the Dow past 10,000 for the first  
time in recent weeks, the market has appeared extremely vulnerable 
at the first sign of weakness from the corporate giants. Tuesday, 
after Gillette said weakness in its Latin American business will 
cause it to miss analysts' expectations by 1 cent per share, its 
stock fell 7 3/4 to 50. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology companies that lifted the market Monday appeared  
ready to hold on to their gains Tuesday, as the Nasdaq composite 
index, dominated by high-tech issues, outperformed the rest of the 
market for most of the session. By late afternoon, though, the 
Nasdaq slipped back to close just 3.11 higher at 2,563.17, a new 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Microsystems rose 10 9/16 to 140 9/16 after the company told  
investors of new efforts to improve its compatibility with 
Microsoft Corp.'s Windows NT operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! traded higher for much of the day as investors continued  
to anticipate its earnings report, due Wednesday after the close of 
trading. The Internet company's stock rose 39 3/16 Monday, and 
gained as much as 25 Tuesday until profit-takers sold it back down. 
Yahoo! fell 5 1/16 to 214 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications companies were mixed. MCI WorldCom fell 2 7/8 to  
89 5/8 amid reports it is negotiating to buy Nextel Communications in 
an attempt to break into the $33 billion U.S. wireless telephone 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Lucent Technologies soared 5 9/16 to 64 1/2 in very heavy  
trading. Analysts cited the company's strong foundation and a sound 
outlook for the telecom industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Market watchers continued to fret about the narrow range of  
companies that have flourished in the current market. Declining 
issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the New York 
Stock Exchange, with 1,789 down, 1,193 up and 594 unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	``The advance/decline line is seriously negative today, and  
that's disturbing,'' said Hyman. ``If this market doesn't broaden 
out, we'll be in line for a much more serious correction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 969.40 million shares, well ahead of  
Monday's pace. The NYSE composite index fell 2.31 to 612.32, and 
the American Stock Exchange composite index fell 6.03 to 715.21. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, which also set a record Monday,  
slipped 3.23 to 1,317.89. The Russell 2000 index of smaller 
companies fell 1.21 to 401.08. 
</P>
<P>
	The market appeared unaffected by the Conference Board's report  
that its Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose for the fifth 
straight month in February. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
