<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 10:43:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Allied Planes Target Yugoslav Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Allied warplanes blasted fuel  
depots, oil refineries, roads and bridges in the most intensive 
night of air raids across Yugoslavia, and Serb officials said today 
that a NATO attack on a coal mining town killed five civilians and 
injured dozens. 
</P>
<P>
	A NATO spokesman said there was evidence one of its weapons  
accidentally struck short of its target in this central Serbian 
town -- a military facility housing an artillery brigade. 
</P>
<P>
	The refugee airlift has begun, meanwhile, for the first of at  
least 110,000 ethnic Albanians who have fled Yugoslav forces in 
Kosovo and taken shelter in cold, primitive conditions in northern 
Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400,000 ethnic Albanians have now left Kosovo, where  
at least 2,000 people have been killed over the past 13 months. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials say 1.1 million of the 1.8 million ethnic  
Albanians in prewar Kosovo are now displaced -- made refugees, lost 
their homes and possessions to marauding Serb forces and fled to 
neighboring Balkan countries. 
</P>
<P>
	A tent city for refugees has sprung up in Kukes, northern  
Albania, and bread was trucked in from Tirana, Albania's capital. 
Television footage showed crowds, including children, fighting over 
loaves of bread. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials reported about 65,000 refugees trapped for days  
without shelter in the no man's land near Blace, Macedonia, on the 
frontier with Yugoslavia. Thousands more were anxiously waiting 
over the border in Kosovo to get out. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest airstrikes in the NATO air campaign that began March  
24 were aimed at cutting the Yugoslav military's lines of supply 
and transport -- roads, bridges, airports and command centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Targets in a heavy wave of attacks late Monday and early today  
included military barracks, fuel dumps and a power station. The 
bombings included a midmorning strike today in the Kosovo capital, 
Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	But it appeared that NATO's airstrike on Aleksinac went awry.  
</P>
<P>
	NATO said today during an allied briefing that its weapons had  
targeted a nearby military post but there was ``evidence of damage 
600 meters just short of the target.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO Air Commodore David Wilby said it was ``possible'' one of  
the weapons ``fell short'' due to a guidance system fault, incoming 
fire or another cause and that ``any unintended damage'' is ``very 
much regretted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	British Defense Secretary George Robertson said accidents happen  
in war and that ``despite all our efforts such casualties will 
inevitably occur in a campaign of this size and complexity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav government harshly condemned the NATO strike on  
Aleksinac, a mining town of about 17,000 people 100 miles southeast 
of Belgrade, comparing it to Nazi atrocities. 
</P>
<P>
	In Aleksinac, two bodies, along with pools of blood and human  
body parts, could be seen in the wreckage of the apartment 
building. Bricks and roof tiles were strewn about, some hundreds of 
feet from the blast. Local officials feared some people were 
trapped in the rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	The allies signaled that the air campaign, stepped up sharply in  
the past several days with better weather conditions, was about to 
become even more intense. 
</P>
<P>
	Brig. Gen. Xavier Delcourt, deputy operations chiefs for the  
French armed forces, said NATO would carry out ``massive strikes'' 
on Yugoslavia today and Wednesday, ``greater than anything done so 
far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, meanwhile, voiced new  
defiance in the face of the NATO campaign to dislodge his forces 
from the separatist ethnic Albanian province in southern Serbia and 
to get him to agree to a peace deal offering autonomy to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavs are ``ready to defend their country,'' his office said  
in a statement today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo crisis has sparked the largest refugee exodus Europe  
has seen in a half-century. 
</P>
<P>
	An airlift of refugees to NATO nations and other countries began  
late Monday to Turkey and Norway, but so far it has made only a 
tiny dent in mass of refugees, some living in desperate conditions 
in crude encampments. 
</P>
<P>
	In Geneva, U.N. refugee chief Sadako Ogata said today that the  
forced deportation of Kosovar Albanians represents ``unprecedented 
violations of the most elementary rights of an entire civilian 
population.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. Security Council on Monday expressed ``deepest concern  
at the grave humanitarian situation'' created by the mass exodus 
from Kosovo, but steered clear of blaming any party for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbia has blamed the NATO campaign for the refugee exodus, and  
bitterly denounced the allied attacks on its heartland. Fresh 
criticism also came today from China, which accused NATO of causing 
``major civilian casualties'' by bombing nonmilitary targets. 
</P>
<P>
	In Aleksinac, the state-run Tanjug news agency quoted civil  
defense commander Jovan Zlatic as saying rescue squads were trying 
to retrieve survivors from beneath the rubble of the wrecked 
apartment building. In a nearby neighborhood, wrecked cars were 
still smoldering hours later. 
</P>
<P>
	The total number of casualties from the NATO attack in central  
Serbia couldn't be independently confirmed, but an Associated Press 
photographer at the scene saw two victims who had died in a 
residential area where several homes were flattened. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian state-run TV showed a local clinic badly damaged and  
shop windows shattered in the center of the town. A local Red Cross 
worker, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that of the 30 
wounded, five were in serious condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb television said NATO also struck a fuel depot south of the  
Hungarian border and a railway bridge over the Danube River. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanjug said several missiles blasted a barracks today in  
Prizren, Kosovo's second-largest city. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO missiles hit a communications relay station near Pristina,  
and blasted targets on the main road from Kosovo to the Serb 
heartland, Tanjug reported. The runway at Pristina's airport was 
also hit, the independent Beta news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong detonations late Monday in the northern city of Novi Sad  
sent an orange fireball into the sky, Serbian television showed. 
Tanjug said the power station at the city oil refinery had been 
hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Beta said missiles had struck the airport at Nis, headquarters  
of the army corps responsible for military operations in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
