<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Xerox Names Thoman As CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- G. Richard Thoman, a former IBM executive  
credited with tough cost-cutting moves during the computer maker's 
turnaround, was named chief executive officer at Xerox Corp. today. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoman, 54, who joined Xerox in 1997 as president and chief  
operating officer, replaces Paul A. Allaire, 60, who will stay on 
as chairman for another year. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoman's election by the Xerox board of directors was not a  
surprise. He had been the heir apparent since being hired as the 
No. 2 executive at Xerox in June 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoman started at IBM in 1994, running its personal computer  
business, and was promoted to finance chief in 1995. His 
cost-slashing measures eliminated thousands of jobs and helped 
revive the company. 
</P>
<P>
	At Xerox, Thoman has been instrumental in the company's push to  
sell its digital products in low-end retail outlets such as Staples 
and Office Max. He has also promoted a more aggressive marketing 
strategy. In the past year, the company's advertising budget has 
doubled from about $100 million to $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the right guy to take Xerox into the next stage,'' said  
Keith Kmetz, an industry analyst with International Data Corp. of 
Framingham, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``His legacy will be maintaining and driving Xerox into more of  
an organization in the digital document world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allaire, who became CEO in 1990 and chairman the following year,  
is credited with transforming Xerox from a copier company into a 
high-tech digital company. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox has struggled to reduce costs as it shifts from old-style  
copiers that operate with lenses and light bulbs to multipurpose 
digital models that can be upgraded to print, scan and fax 
documents when connected to personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is in the midst of cutting 9,000 jobs, or just under  
10 percent of its worldwide work force, as it tries to step up its 
presence in the rapidly growing market for lower-priced digital 
copiers and printers used in the home and small office markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the company unveiled 90 new products, including a  
family of digital copiers. Digital products made up 53 percent of 
the company's $5.05 billion revenue in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to CEO, Thoman will retain the title of president.  
</P>
<P>
	Before joining IBM, Thoman worked at Nabisco International,  
American Express, the consulting firm McKinsey and Co., and Exxon 
Corp. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
