<HEADLINE> Prodigy Offers New Spanish Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Prodigy Communications Corp. will  
offer a Spanish-language Internet access service to 
Spanish-speaking households in the United States, the company 
announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The service offers the same features available through Prodigy  
Internet, but also provides both customer service and technical 
support for Spanish-speaking customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Prodigy, based in White Plains, hopes to ``break down the  
language barriers that have kept many Spanish-speaking Americans 
away from the Internet,'' said David C. Trachtenberg, president and 
chief operating officer of Prodigy. 
</P>
<P>
	The service will be supported with Spanish-language advertising,  
news and links to other Hispanic Web sites and services. Visitors 
can also search the Internet with Spanish language search engines. 
</P>
<P>
	The service, costing $19.95 monthly, will be promoted in  
commercials beginning today on Spanish-language television stations 
in Miami and Chicago, The Wall Street Journal reported today. The 
marketing campaign will be expanded to eight other U.S. cities, the 
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other companies offer Spanish-language content online, but focus  
mainly on subscribers outside the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online Inc., based in Dulles, Va., announced in December  
a joint venture with a Venezuelan company to develop local online 
services written in Spanish and Portuguese and geared to residents 
of Argentina, Brazil and Mexico. AOL said it would also be able to 
provide the online content to its subscribers in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Star Media, a New York-based Internet company, is also a  
provider of Spanish and Portuguese-language content to 
Spanish-speaking subscribers in Latin America as well to online 
subscribers in the United States. 

</P>
</TEXT>
