<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hockey Champs Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORONO, Maine (AP) -- The University of Maine hockey team returned  
home today with the NCAA championship, completing a three-year 
turnaround in which the program rebounded from scandal and 
disgrace. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of fans turned out at Alfond Arena for a 90-minute  
rally to honor the Black Bears, who flew home late Sunday night 
from Anaheim, Calif., after two overtime victories in the Frozen 
Four. 
</P>
<P>
	Maine advanced to the final with a 2-1 win over Boston College,  
then beat New Hampshire 3-2 Saturday night in the championship 
game. Marcus Gustafsson scored the winning goal off his own rebound 
at 10:50 of overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was especially sweet for Gustafsson and fellow  
seniors Steve Kariya, David Cullen, Bobby Stewart and Jason 
Vitorino, all of whom remained at Maine even after sanctions for 
NCAA rules violations led some teammates to transfer elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	The team was barred from the NCAA tournament for two years,  
scholarships were cut and coach Shawn Walsh was suspended for a 
year, casting doubt on the future of a program that had brought 
home its first national championship in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Speakers at the rally praised the five seniors for hanging in  
and providing the leadership that led to the national title. 
</P>
<P>
	``They worked hard, they took care of business, and now they're  
number one,'' university president Peter Hoff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletic director Suzanne Tyler singled out Walsh for turning  
adversity into success. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a guy who takes chicken parts and makes chicken  
salad,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the preliminary remarks, Walsh introduced his players,  
each of whom addressed the crowd. The biggest cheers were reserved 
for the seniors and goalie Alfie Michaud, who made 46 saves in the 
final game and was the last to speak. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh said the team will visit the White House, as it did after  
its 1993 national title. The championship banner will be hung at 
Alfond Arena in October, when Maine plays host to Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh displayed his optimism for the coming season as he  
introduced some of the transfer students and current reserves who 
will be called upon to play big roles next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh noted that no team has won consecutive NCAA championships  
in more than 25 years, but added, ``I'll be honest with you. I like 
our chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Black Bears were led to their 1993 championship by freshman  
Paul Kariya, the Hobey Baker Award winner who went on to star with 
the Anaheim Mighty Ducks. This year, playing on the home ice of 
Kariya's NHL team, Maine was led by his younger brother Steve, a 
Hobey Baker finalist. 
</P>
<P>
	A third Kariya, Martin, has made a verbal commitment to enroll  
at Maine in the fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
