<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Church Learns About Investing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) -- The Rev. Larry O'Dell sowed $1,281 and  
reaped five times as much. 
</P>
<P>
	At the start of Lent, O'Dell handed out cash to members of his  
congregation and, citing a parable in the Bible, asked them to use 
their talents to invest the money and then donate their earnings to 
the church. 
</P>
<P>
	On Easter Sunday, the collection plates at Christ United  
Methodist Church contained $5,610.63, with more money still coming 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dell had dispensed the seed money in crisp, new bills -- fives  
for adults and twos for children -- and gave the congregation 40 
days to invest it. It came back as a combination of cash and 
checks, with a note explaining how each member of the congregation 
used his or her talents. 
</P>
<P>
	``One man makes duck calls. He used his money to make a handmade  
duck call. I think it brought in $50. A lot of people made pies and 
peanut brittle,'' O'Dell said. 
</P>
<P>
	The students in an adult Sunday school class pooled their $5s  
and put together a cookbook. Children held car washes or raked 
lawns. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the whole point -- to find out what they could do,''  
O'Dell said. ``Some people said this helped find out who they 
are.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:33:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Charging $3 Minimum Fee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. is extending a $3 minimum monthly  
charge to all of its long-distance customers, even if they don't 
make any long-distance calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The minimum charge starts in July for AT&AMP;T customers not  
currently signed up for one of the company's calling plans. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, which has 70 million long-distance customers, introduced  
the policy last August, charging the $3 to plan subscribers and new 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	About 10 million AT&AMP;T customers make less than $3 a month in  
calls. AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest telecommunications company, said 
it needs the money to cover the $300 million a year it costs to 
service infrequent callers. 
</P>
<P>
	Minimum charges, until now, had been more limited.  
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom, the second largest long-distance company, also has  
a $3 monthly minimum for customers who don't use its promotional 
calling plans, but doesn't charge the fee to its remaining 
customers, a spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 3 Sprint, conversely, only charges a minimum fee to those  
who sign up for promotions. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T said it would waive the fee for some low-income customers.  
But consumer groups said charges are hurting those customers least 
able to afford it. 
</P>
<P>
	``AT&AMP;T's new minimum charge is the latest example of  
telecommunications deregulation run amok, driving up prices for 
millions of consumers,'' said Gene Kimmelman, of the 
Washington-based Consumers Union, in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Kimmelman noted that other fees, ranging from $2-3 a month,  
already were instituted in the wake of telecommunications 
deregulation in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T stock rose more than 3 percent, advancing $2.68 3/4 to  
$80.12 1/2, in Tuesday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 14:35:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seles, Davenport on US Fed Cup Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Removing the Fed Cup series between the  
United States and Croatia from Eastern Europe took the participants 
out of possible danger. It also allowed U.S. captain Billie Jean 
King to choose Monica Seles. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterfinal originally was scheduled for Zagreb, Croatia.  
But NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia raised questions about 
safety. For a time, there was talk of switching the site to 
Hamburg, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't even consider her if we were in one of those two  
places,'' King said during a conference call Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The matches were moved to Raleigh, N.C., and that allowed King  
to have Seles join Lindsay Davenport, Chanda Rubin and Lisa Raymond 
for the matches at Raleigh Racquet Club on April 17-18. 
</P>
<P>
	Seles was born in Novi Sad, Yugoslavia, where explosions were  
heard during Monday's round of air strikes and which was without 
water after weekend raids. King has talked with Seles about the 
conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has been very upset,'' King said. ``It is just very  
difficult for her and I am sure for the Croatians as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was six years ago this month that Seles was stabbed in the  
back during a match in Hamburg, Germany, by an obsessed fan of 
Steffi Graf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told her if we are going to play in Croatia or they are  
going to move it to Germany, I don't expect you to go at all,'' 
King said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of made the decision for her so she didn't have to get  
uptight about it because I know deep down she always wants to play 
Fed Cup when she can,'' King said. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Tennis Federation's Fed Cup committee said it  
considered neutral sites for the series, then decided on the United 
States for the Croatia match. It narrowed its choice to the 
southeastern United States because a number of players will be in a 
tournament at Amelia Island, Fla., the preceding week. 
</P>
<P>
	A nine-time Grand Slam winner, Seles is ranked fourth in the  
world after reaching the semifinals of the 1999 Australian Open and 
the doubles finals in the Lipton Championship with Mary Joe 
Fernandez. 
</P>
<P>
	Seles played in the 1998 Fed Cup semifinals against Spain and  
was a member of the 1996 Fed Cup championship team. 
</P>
<P>
	King said she expects the Raleigh crowd to act less like a staid  
tennis crowd and more like fans who pack college basketball and 
stock car racing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just too bad that we do have to play in the United States  
because of what is going on over there,'' King said. ``At least we 
are going to feel safe here. That is very important for both teams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
