<HEADLINE> Missing Kentucky Derby Trophy Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- More than two decades after his 1961  
Kentucky Derby trophy was stolen from his home, jockey John Sellers 
may soon get his treasure back. 
</P>
<P>
	The engraved sterling silver trophy that Sellers won aboard  
Carry Back was among a dozen trophies stolen when his Monrovia, 
Calif., home was burglarized in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Sellers, 62, now living in Hallandale, Fla., was stunned to  
learn from a friend last week that his cherished trophy was up for 
sale on the Internet auction site eBay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought I'd see any of them again,'' Sellers said in  
The Trentonian newspaper Tuesday. ``I was absolutely shocked. I 
couldn't believe it. I had just assumed that all my trophies were 
melted down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trophy was offered for sale with a $4,500 reserve by Sue and  
Lou Novello of Sudbury, Mass. Novello told the newspaper she 
obtained the trophy legally at a California auction, but planned to 
return it to Sellers after she notified her brother and business 
partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the most unbelievable story I have ever heard,'' she  
wrote in an e-mail quoted by The Trentonian. 
</P>
<P>
	Sellers said if he gets his Derby trophy back, he plans to give  
it to his son, John Jr. Sellers also won the 1961 Preakness aboard 
Carry Back and the 1965 Belmont Stakes on Hail to All. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
