<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cabela Catalog Firm Goes Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Dick Cabela started a small business from his  
kitchen table 38 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, that business has grown into one of the nation's largest  
catalog retailers, with an estimated $420 million in mail-order and 
Internet sales of outdoor sporting goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabela's, based in the western Nebraska town of Sidney, ships  
more than 60 million seasonal and specialty catalogs annually to 
all 50 states and 120 countries. It even has its own 30-minute fall 
outdoor show on Saturday mornings on ESPN, ``Cabela's Sportsman's 
Quest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It started out to be just a hobby,'' said Cabela's wife, Mary,  
who helped get the business started from the family kitchen in 
1961. ``I remember Dick went to Chicago to buy furniture with his 
dad. When he came home we celebrated with 25 orders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The son of a hardware and furniture store owner, Cabela had  
traveled to a trade show in Chicago to buy furniture for his 
family's store in Chappell. He spotted some Japanese fishing lures 
-- and he got hooked on the idea of starting his own business. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were awfully cheap -- 1 1/2 cents apiece,'' recalled the  
62-year-old Cabela, who is chairman of Cabela's. ``We bought 20 
gross, about 120 bucks. We got to selling 'em. It was just one of 
those kind of dumb things you do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One classified ad in a Casper, Wyo., newspaper promising 12  
hand-tied flies for $1 got only one bite. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he began offering five hand-tied flies free -- with 25 cents  
for postage and handling. First-class stamps then cost 6 cents, so 
the Cabelas made 11 cents on every sale. 
</P>
<P>
	``That ad really clicked,'' Cabela said. ``We ran the ads in  
Field and Stream, those kind of magazines. Some would tape 25 
pennies in their replies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pouring those pennies back into the enterprise, the Cabelas  
began collecting more Japanese imported fishing gear, primarily 
fishing rods and tackle. By 1962, a small shed in their backyard in 
Chappell became Cabela's first warehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1963, mimeographed sheets mailed to customers became small  
catalogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Owned by the family, Cabela's declines to release financial  
data. But trade magazine Catalog Age of Stamford, Conn., put 
Cabela's catalog and Internet sales at about $420 million in 1997, 
ranking it 29th in the country for companies that make print 
catalogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabela's was one of just 46 U.S. companies that had $250 million  
or more in revenue from catalog and Internet transactions out of 
more than 8,000 companies issuing print catalogs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're pretty big,'' Catalog Age editorial director Laura  
Beaudry said of Cabela's. 
</P>
<P>
	The company sells a wide variety of clothing and gear for  
outdoor sports such as fishing, hunting, camping and boating. Some 
of the items are designed and manufactured to Cabela's 
specifications; others are made by brand-name companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabela says running his own business came naturally to him.  
</P>
<P>
	``You grow up in a family like that, a family of merchants, that  
is what you do,'' he said. ``I never thought I would do anything 
else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cabela grew up in a close-knit family of two girls and four boys  
in the high plains of western Nebraska. He and his brothers and 
sisters hunted rabbits in the backyard on the edge of Chappell. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabela still enjoys that hobby. He and his wife have hunted  
around the world and stock their stores with full-mounted 
elephants, lions, leopards and varieties of antelope. 
</P>
<P>
	During the early days of his business, Cabela worked at the  
furniture store during the day, while his wife, who grew up in 
Casper, Wyo., cared for their growing family. They have nine 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	At night, the couple packed merchandise and prepared ads at the  
kitchen table until 3 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were very, very busy years, but they also were a lot of  
fun,'' said Mrs. Cabela, 61. ``Building a company is fun, 
especially when you work together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cabela's younger brother, Jim, joined the enterprise in 1963. He  
is now the company president and works with the merchants, while 
Dick works with marketing and finance. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years after those mimeographed sheets first turned into a  
small catalog, Dick Cabela began working full-time at his 
mail-order company. He moved the business to an old American Legion 
Hall in Chappell and included a small retail display. In 1968, he 
moved the business and his family 25 miles west to the larger town 
of Sidney, where it was easier to find employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabela's is now a major employer in Sidney, a town of 6,000,  
with more than 700 people working at its headquarters and store. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a visible force here in Sidney,'' said Mayor Suzanne  
Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1 million visitors come each year to the Sidney flagship  
store, making it one of Nebraska's top attractions -- complete with 
a 27-foot-tall replica mountain covered with 40 lifelike game 
trophies and a waterfall. 
</P>
<P>
	People from all over the country camp overnight in the parking  
lot -- which has a special area for recreational vehicles and 
trailers with water-service hookups -- to shop the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabela's four retail stores in Nebraska, Minnesota and Wisconsin  
are extravagant tributes to the great outdoors. 
</P>
<P>
	The 150,000-square-foot store in Owatonna, Minn., includes  
mounted African wildlife, a 35-foot-high mountain with North 
American game trophies and huge aquariums stocked with native 
Minnesota fish. 
</P>
<P>
	``We try to make our stores sort of like a natural history  
museum,'' Cabela said. ``It makes us more like a tourist attraction 
than just a plain store.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
