<HEADLINE> Stocks Sharply Higher / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues propelled the stock market  
sharply higher Tuesday, lifting the Dow Jones industrial average 
back above 10,000, as the outlook for interest rates improved. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally also sent the Nasdaq composite index into record  
territory. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was up 178.16 at 10,010.67,  
trading above its high close of 10,006.78, set last Monday. The 
markets were closed on Good Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq index was up 49.41 at 2,542.78, beating its record  
close of 2,510.09 reached Feb. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher.  
</P>
<P>
	Traders had their first chance to react to Friday's Labor  
Department report that just 46,000 new jobs were created in 
February, the smallest increase in three years. The news calmed 
investor fears that the economy was growing too fast and that the 
Federal Reserve might raise interest rates to slow it down. The 
report also said the unemployment rate fell to a 29-year low of 4.2 
percent as wages rose less than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks once again set the tone for trading.  
</P>
<P>
	Among Dow stocks, IBM was up 5 1/8 to 182 1/8 and Hewlett-Packard rose  
4 to 71 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! shot up 28 1/4 to 208 as traders anticipated a strong  
earnings report from the Internet company on Wednesday. Computer 
maker Dell was up 2 3/4 at 43 15/16, Sun Microsystems gained 4 1/16 to 
130 1/4, and Microsoft was up 2 3/16 at 94 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Online trading companies also traded higher after a Credit  
Suisse First Boston analyst issued positive comments about the 
sector. E-Trade Group rose 8 1/4 to 69 1/8. Charles Schwab rose 5 3/4 to 
100. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 24.01 at 1,317.73.  
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 472.2 million shares, 
down from Thursday's 480.9 million. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
