<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kissinger Asked To Be on IOC Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and  
former Los Angeles Olympics chief Peter Ueberroth have been picked 
for a panel to restructure the IOC in the wake of its worst 
scandal, Olympic sources said today. 
</P>
<P>
	International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch  
chose Kissinger and Ueberroth among four Americans for IOC 2000, 
created to help clean up after the Salt Lake City bribery case, the 
sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also tapped by Samaranch was IOC vice president Anita DeFrantz,  
said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment of U.S. Olympic Committee president Bill Hybl to  
the commission was announced last month. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not known if Kissinger, Ueberroth or DeFrantz had  
accepted their appointments. All were traveling Tuesday and 
unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Such prominent individuals could help convince critics from  
corporate suites to Capitol Hill that the IOC is serious about 
changing its privileged ways. 
</P>
<P>
	Kissinger's appointment brought immediate praise from the IOC's  
harshest congressional critic, Sen. John McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is pleased to see the appointment of someone of Dr.  
Kissinger's stature,'' said Pia Pialorsi, a spokeswoman for the 
Arizona Republican whose Commerce Committee has scheduled hearings 
on the Olympic scandal next week. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland, were closed for the  
day and spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber was unavailable. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000 was set up last month as the committee's primary engine  
for change after the Salt Lake scandal, in which six members were 
expelled in a million-dollar gifts-for-votes scheme involving the 
Utah capital's successful quest for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission will have 20 to 24 members, half from the IOC and  
half ``leading personalities who understand sport.'' The panel 
essentially form a new version of the Olympic Charter, the IOC's 
century-old bylaws. 
</P>
<P>
	It will make recommendations on selection of Olympic host  
cities, election and term limits of IOC members, the structure of 
the IOC and executive board and further roles for Olympic athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also will look at revenue sharing and the evolution of  
the games themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources said Samaranch wanted the commission to have its  
first meeting in early June, with an interim report presented to 
the IOC general assembly later that month in Seoul, South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch will head the commission and appoint its members, two  
points attacked last month by critics, including McCain, who felt 
the panel needed more independence. 
</P>
<P>
	But with Kissinger a member, the IOC reform panel gains instant  
credibility because of his long record of statesmanship and 
diplomacy. Samaranch had mentioned Kissinger as the kind of 
heavyweight he wanted on the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Ueberroth also brings weight -- and an educated outsider's view --  
to the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	After leading the Los Angeles Games to athletic success and a  
$225 million surplus that convinced cities and sponsors that the 
Olympics were a good investment, Ueberroth served as baseball 
commission and now heads a venture capital company in Southern 
California. He has been critical of the IOC and its leader. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz was a bronze-medal rower at the 1976 Games who sued  
over the White House-led boycott of the 1980 Games in Moscow. She 
worked with Ueberroth in 1984, was appointed to the IOC in 1986 and 
now runs the foundation of amateur sports in Los Angeles financed 
by seed money from the '84 surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Hybl is a former Colorado prosecutor and head of one of the  
nation's largest charitable foundations. USOC president since 1996, 
he has led the ethics investigation into the 1994 attack on figure 
skater Nancy Kerrigan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
