<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Hire Law Firm for Tobacco Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department is getting some outside  
help in preparing a federal tobacco lawsuit from a Minneapolis law 
firm that helped Minnesota obtain a $6.6 billion settlement from 
the industry last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The firm of Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi will advise and  
assist Justice Department lawyers through June 30 at the 
substantially reduced rate of $75 per hour plus travel costs and 
expenses, Acting Assistant Attorney General David W. Ogden, head of 
the department's tobacco litigation task force, announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In this year's State of the Union speech, President Clinton  
announced that the government had decided to sue the industry to 
recover money paid by federal health-insurance programs for 
treatment of tobacco-related illnesses. The Justice Department has 
requested $20 million from Congress in the fiscal year beginning 
next Oct. 1 to pay for 40 government lawyers to work on the case 
and for $5 million for expert witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract with the Minneapolis law firm runs through June 30  
and sets a maximum payment of $81,760 through that date. The 
government said it could be extended if both parties agree. 
</P>
<P>
	The department emphasized the contract specifies only consulting  
services and does not contemplate any contingent fee payment to the 
law firm based on potential payments the industry might either 
agree or be ordered to make. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least for the foreseeable future, the litigation team  
itself will consist exclusively of Justice Department attorneys,'' 
Ogden said. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for the law firm was not immediately able to say  
how many lawyers the firm intends to devote to advising the 
government and what the firm's normal hourly rate for such business 
would be. Large firms often charge business clients several hundred 
dollars an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi represented the state of  
Minnesota and Blue Cross-Blue Shield of Minnesota in their lawsuit 
against the tobacco industry. As a result of the lawsuit and near 
the end of the trial, the tobacco industry agreed May 8, 1998, to 
pay $6.6 billion to Minnesota's citizens and to submit to cigarette 
marketing and advertising curbs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi is widely recognized for its  
success in the Minnesota litigation against the tobacco industry 
and for its expertise in this area of litigation,'' Ogden said. 
``They have devoted thousands of hours to uncovering and learning 
the facts relating to tobacco litigation. Their extraordinary 
experience in this area will be very valuable to the department's 
tobacco litigation team as we prepare a plan to recover federal 
health care expenditures from the tobacco industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Department officials said they were particularly interested in  
tapping the law firm's knowledge of the 200,000 pages of industry 
documents that were disclosed during the discovery process of the 
Minnesota lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior department official, requesting anonymity, has said the  
government's lawsuit or lawsuits will be tort claims against the 
tobacco companies, possibly alleging fraud, negligence or breach of 
a special duty to provide the government all information on health 
effects of their product. Torts is the legal name for injuries 
against people or properties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
