<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Patriots' Stadium Cost Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- State officials have tacked on another $6  
million to the estimated cost of the New England Patriots football 
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	They claim the expenses were expected and have been worked into  
the project's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody understood all along that the cost was going  
to be about the $380 million figure, not the $374 million,'' said 
Marc Ryan, the governor's budget chief. ``This project is not going 
up in cost by any means. This is just recognizing those last few 
costs that were out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state's Finance Advisory Committee, composed of Gov. John G.  
Rowland, the state comptroller, state treasurer and legislative 
leaders, agreed Friday to take an additional $2 million in state 
surplus money for the stadium project. 
</P>
<P>
	About $600,000 of that money will be used for the stadium's  
environmental impact study, a state-mandated comprehensive 
investigation that began in February to determine the stadium's 
potential social, economic and environmental effect on Hartford. 
The balance, about $1.4 million, will pay legal fees incurred by 
the state in drafting the stadium legislation and negotiating the 
stadium development and relocation agreement with the Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending is in addition to the $374 million the legislature  
authorized in December to pay for a stadium on Hartford's 
riverfront. It joins another $5.5 million in state budget surplus 
that has been set aside through the next two years to pay for 
stadium ``soft costs,'' such as legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	No one will know the value of the final bill until the  
68,000-seat stadium opens in 2002. Ryan said the state has 
earmarked $107.5 million in surplus, to go along with $274 million 
in state bonds, to finance the project. 
</P>
<P>
	The state will be protected from construction-specific cost  
increases, he said, because the Patriots must pay any cost overruns 
past $280 million in the actual construction of the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Other costs associated with the project include $55 million for  
environmental cleanup work and infrastructure improvements such as 
relocation of sewer and water lines; $24 million for inflation; and 
$15 million for a new training facility for the Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	Between mid-November and early February, the state incurred more  
than $800,000 in legal fees from two law firms working on those 
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
