<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 23:41:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal Trial Coming To Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The federal judge presiding over the  
trial of Whitewater figure Susan McDougal is poised to instruct the 
jury that she, not special prosecutor Kenneth Starr, is the only 
one on trial. 
</P>
<P>
	That reminder, drafted on Tuesday, may come as a surprise to  
jurors who have listened to a full month of attacks on Starr by 
Mrs. McDougal and her lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office, the jury has been told time and time again, was  
out to ``get'' President Clinton and his wife and wanted Mrs. 
McDougal to falsely implicate them in wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. said Tuesday, however,  
that in deciding the criminal contempt charges, jurors cannot 
consider evidence that prosecutors wanted something other than Mrs. 
McDougal's truthful testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury may consider her accusations against Starr only on the  
companion obstruction of justice charge, the judge added. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury instructions, which the judge reduced to writing on  
Tuesday, were to be delivered after closing arguments, which were 
beginning today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were pleased overall'' with the instructions, Associate  
Independent Counsel Mark Barrett said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, the Clintons' former business partner in the  
Whitewater real estate venture, was indicted after she refused on 
two occasions to answer grand jury questions about the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett said the prosecution was able to block a defense request  
for an instruction that jurors could acquit Mrs. McDougal of 
criminal contempt if she proved she had ``just cause'' to refuse to 
answer the grand jury questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Harris, Mrs. McDougal's fiance and co-counsel for the  
defense, had a matter-of-fact response. ``Some of them we got. Some 
of them we didn't,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris pointed out that, according to the jury instructions,  
jurors will have to find that Mrs. McDougal ``willfully'' refused 
to answer the questions to find her guilty of criminal contempt. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have heard evidence that the defendant believed that  
certain prosecutors wanted something other than her truthful 
testimony,'' Howard wrote in his instructions. 
</P>
<P>
	``This evidence should be considered by you only when  
considering ... the obstruction of justice charge,'' the judge 
wrote. ``You are not to consider this evidence when considering'' 
the contempt charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Another instruction says ``the law does not recognize as a  
defense to these charges that the defendant was motivated to commit 
her acts by sincere moral, political or religious convictions.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
