<HEADLINE> Safety Panel May Fine Navy Builder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Federal safety regulators are accusing a  
major shipbuilder for the Navy of hundreds of workplace safety 
violations, the most serious involving inadequate measures to 
protect workers from falls. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale Industries Inc. could face $537,000 in fines for the  
437 violations alleged Monday by the Occupational Safety and Health 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans to contest the citations, saying it was the  
target of a biased investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	OSHA acted after complaints by the Metal Trades Council of the  
AFL-CIO. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past six years, Avondale has refused to recognize a  
collective bargaining election held by the Metal Trades Council. 
The company is challenging the results of that election in federal 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	The citations were issued by OSHA following a six-month  
investigation at Avondale's yard, one of Louisiana's largest 
employers with about 6,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The most serious allegations involved federal standards for  
scaffolding, guard rails, inadequate fall protection devices, 
openings in the decks of ships and inadequate training for 
employees in the use of fall protection equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant Labor Secretary Charles Jeffress said that of the  
seven deaths at Avondale since 1990, three involved falls. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale attorney Horace A. ``Topper'' Thompson said OSHA's team  
leader on the inspection ``had the same agenda'' as the union. 
</P>
<P>
	Union spokeswoman Lane Windham said Avondale ``will duck and  
dodge and drag their feet whenever they are held accountable for 
how they treat their workers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They need to pay this fine immediately and make their yard  
safer today,'' Windham said. 
</P>
<P>
	Windham called on the Navy to put pressure on Avondale to  
upgrade its safety. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
