<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Isaac Stern Gives Violin Classes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- Violinist Isaac Stern, making his first  
visit to Germany, opened a seminar Tuesday for young musicians at 
the Cologne music school. 
</P>
<P>
	Stern, who is Jewish, had vowed never to visit Germany out of  
respect to the 6 million Jews killed in the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he changed his mind because he felt it was time to see  
the country of Bach, Beethoven and Mendelssohn, which he's been 
doing by traveling around Germany since he arrived a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The virtuoso also wanted to see and hear how young German  
musicians are absorbing their musical heritage, as well as to pass 
on his own experience by teaching a nine-day seminar for 28 
students. 
</P>
<P>
	Prominent in Stern's thoughts was the connection between art and  
politics, not only because of his feelings about Germany's history 
but also because of the war in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to teach them that they, as musicians, must live and  
play at the same time,'' he said of his seminar. ``Our 
responsibility is to continue the search for beauty and humanity. 
That is what survives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stern, the president of Carnegie Hall, was born in Russia but  
moved to the United States with his parents when he was 10 months 
old. Many of his relatives were killed in the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	After arriving in Germany, Stern visited Berlin, Dresden and  
Leipzig before returning to the southern city of Cologne for 
teaching. 
</P>
<P>
	``I learned,'' he said of his decision to visit Germany. ``The  
time came when I wanted to hear, search and think. With my visit, I 
forgive nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he said, he did not want to blame, attack or  
speak of guilt. 
</P>
<P>
	``It isn't very human not to give people a chance to change,''  
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
