<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> News Corp. Expands Cable Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Adding to a burgeoning U.S. media empire, Rupert  
Murdoch's News Corp. is paying $1.4 billion to take full control of 
two cable television channels, Fox Sports Net and the entertainment 
channel FX. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian magnate's deal with Liberty Media Group, a  
company controlled by AT&AMP;T Corp. and headed by cable magnate John 
Malone, will also increase News Corp.'s indirect ownership of two 
New York sports teams, basketball's Knicks and hockey's Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of the accord announced late Monday, News Corp.  
will pay $1.4 billion in stock to buy out nearly all of Liberty's 
50 percent interest in Fox/Liberty Networks, a joint venture the 
two companies formed three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would give Liberty an 8 percent stake in News Corp.,  
making it the company's second-largest shareholder. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fox Sports Net was created as a challenger to Walt Disney  
Co.'s ESPN channel and reaches more than 62 million households 
across the United States. FX is seen in 39 million U.S. homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This deal will enable us to leverage more fully the Fox brand  
across our cable and broadcast properties while giving us added 
flexibility over our sports and entertainment channels,'' Murdoch 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	News Corp. will also take over the joint venture's 40 percent  
interest in Rainbow Programming, a unit of Cablevision that 
controls the New York Knicks, the New York Rangers and part of the 
Madison Square Garden arena where they play. News Corp. is also the 
owner of baseball's Los Angeles Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Media, based in Englewood, Colo., will retain its 50  
percent interest in International Sports Programming Partners, the 
international sports programming venture it formed with Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street saw the deal, which had been rumored for several  
days, as positive for both companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``They couldn't grow it under a two-headed ownership,'' said  
David Goldsmith, an analyst at Buckingham Research Group. ``News 
Corp. wants the programming to grow, sometimes at the expense of 
earnings, while Liberty wants the value of the assets to grow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch analyst Jessica Reif Cohen said it was an added  
plus for News Corp. to bring in John Malone as an investor. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tuesday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Liberty  
Media shares jumped $3.12 1/2, or 5.6 percent, to $59. News Corp.'s 
U.S.-listed shares rose 18 3/4 cents to $34. 
</P>
<P>
	News Corp., based in Sydney, Australia, is one of the world's  
largest media companies. Its U.S. holdings also include the Fox 
Television Network, the Twentieth Century Fox movie studio, and the 
book publisher HarperCollins. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Media is one of nation's biggest providers of cable  
television programming, with interests in BET, CNN and Court TV. 
Liberty chairman Malone is the former head of Tele-Communications 
Inc., the cable giant recently acquired by AT&AMP;T. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
