<DOCNO> APW19990406.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:42:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rain showers stretched from Michigan to Georgia on Tuesday while  
a storm hit Nevada with heavy snow. 
</P>
<P>
	A storm system from the Great Lakes to the Tennessee Valley  
moved east through the day. The storm brought snow to northeastern 
Minnesota and rain showers in a band running from northern Michigan 
through Georgia. Wind gusts of up to 45 mph were reported in 
Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Precipitation amounts with the system were generally light, with  
heavier amounts reported in northern Mississippi and Alabama, where 
some areas reported up to two inches of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure was building in the central part of the country,  
bringing mostly fair skies to the region. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, a storm system moving out of California into the  
central and southern Rockies produced rain in Southern California, 
with snow showers at higher elevations. 
</P>
<P>
	In Nevada, more than two feet of snow fell around Lake Tahoe,  
while the valleys of western Nevada saw accumulations ranging from 
three to six inches. Snow showers in association with the storm 
were also reported in southern Idaho and northern Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	By midafternoon, temperatures around the continental United  
States ranged from 86 in Punta Gorda, Fla., to 10 in Flagstaff, 
Ariz. The highest heat index was 90 in Key West, Fla., and the 
lowest wind chill was zero in Worthington, Minn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
