<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yahoo Stock Jumps 22 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Internet exuberance hit the stock market again  
today as shares of the popular Web site Yahoo! Inc. -- and two 
Internet companies it plans to buy -- all soared more than 20 
percent on rumors that Yahoo! would beat predictions for its 
quarterly profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like this week, Internet stocks are everybody's  
favorite again,'' said Jim Balderston, industry analyst for Zona 
Research Inc., Redwood City, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo!'s stock rose $39.37 1/2, or nearly 22 percent, to close at  
$219.12 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. GeoCities Inc. gained $26.43 3/4, 
or almost 23 percent, to close at $143.56 1/4. Broadcast.com Inc., 
rose $27, or 21 percent, to $157. GeoCities provides Internet pages 
where individuals can post material. Broadcast.com is the biggest 
provider of radio and television programming on the Web. Both 
companies will soon become part of Yahoo!'s expanding empire. 
</P>
<P>
	Their rise was part of a broader market surge by technology  
stocks that pushed the Dow Jones industrial average to a new high 
of 10,007.33 and boosted the Nasdaq by 66.69 points to 2,560.06. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said those numbers may have been buoyed by excitement  
over Yahoo!, one of the few Internet companies that actually makes 
a profit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that they're generating black ink instead of red ink  
has got to make some of these investors feel less queasy'' about 
the sky-high prices for Internet stocks, Balderston said. 
</P>
<P>
	Santa Clara, Calif.-based Yahoo! is scheduled to report results  
after the market closes Wednesday for the quarter ended March 31. 
The company earned $4.3 million, or 8 cents per share, in the same 
quarter a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The consensus among analysts surveyed by the research firm First  
Call Corp. is for the company to earn 8 cents per share. However, 
the ``whisper'' number -- the rumored predictions that circulate 
shortly before earnings announcements -- was at 10 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman Brothers analyst Brian Oakes said Yahoo!'s revenue,  
expected to be $80 million, could beat that figure by $10 million -- 
or 12.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! has consistently beaten analysts expectations in recent  
quarters, said Chuck Hill, director of research for First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakes said that has more to do with the company than the  
analysts covering it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of what companies do now is set expectations so they can  
be sure they beat expectations,'' Oakes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Monday, Yahoo! announced a deal to deliver its content and  
services to hand-held computers and devices for viewing the Web on 
TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal with Online Anywhere, Yahoo! will provide e-mail,  
personal calendars, weather and stock quotes. Online Anywhere's 
technology automatically formats the information to fit whatever 
device the subscriber is using, be it a large-screen television or 
a pocket-size, hand-held computer. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year ended Dec. 31, Yahoo! earned $25.6 million, or 23  
cents per share, reversing a loss of $25.5 million, or 29 cents per 
share, in 1997. Revenue jumped to $203.3 million from $70.5 
million. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
