<HEADLINE> Nets' Williams Out of Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- All-Star center Jayson Williams of  
the New Jersey Nets was released from a hospital Tuesday after 
surgery for a season-ending broken leg. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams has already started rehabilitation work, but is wearing  
a brace and will not be able to put weight on his right leg for 
eight to 10 weeks, Nets spokesman John Mertz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams had been expected to leave the Hospital for Special  
Surgery in New York City on Monday, three days after he had an 
operation to insert a plate and five screws in his leg. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dr. Russell Warren, the surgeon, said there was too much  
swelling, according to Sal DiFazio, Williams' agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Team doctors had X-rays taken Tuesday to check on the stability  
of bone taken from Williams's hip that was grafted onto the leg and 
held in place with the plate and screws, DiFazio said. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams broke the leg in a collision with teammate Stephon  
Marbury late in the fourth quarter of the Nets' 90-85 win over the 
Atlanta Hawks on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets officially put Williams on the injured list Tuesday and  
activated forward Scott Burrell, who went on the injured list with 
a sprained right ankle on March 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
