<HEADLINE> Wheat Mixed; Corn, Soybeans Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures finished mixed Tuesday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while corn and soybean futures moved lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans fell sharply on reports three American pork producers  
planned to import cheaper Brazilian soybean meal as animal feed in 
coming months. Analysts derided the reports as economically 
unfeasible, but the widespread talk shook the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans have been pressured for the past few weeks amid fears a  
bumper Brazilian crop, offered at prices more attractive to 
importers, would take business away from American exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures fell amid signs that the recent rains and mild  
temperatures across Midwestern planting regions had aided early 
planting and increased the likelihood of a bumper crop. On Monday, 
the U.S. Agriculture Department said spring planting was slightly 
ahead of normal. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures remained under pressure amid expectations  
inventories will rise sharply later this year with the harvest of a 
winter wheat crop that's currently in excellent condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1/4 cent to $2.89 a bushel; May corn  
fell 2 1/2 cents to $2.16 1/4 a bushel; May oats fell 6 cents to $1.05 a 
bushel; May soybeans fell 4 1/4 cents to $4.77 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mostly lower on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while lean hogs finished mixed and pork bellies advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose 0.08 cent to 65.30 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle fell 0.03 cent to 73.97 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose 0.80 cent to 54.90 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose 1.02 
cents to 53.32 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
