<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Business Briefs    	
</P>
<P>
	HOME-BASED WORKERS: The image that many people have of  
home-based workers is that of women who manage to fit their 
occupation around raising their children and doing the housework. 
But Ohio State University found in a study of 899 home-based 
workers in nine states that nearly 59 percent were men involved in 
traditional fields such as sales or construction. Three-quarters of 
the respondents were self-employed, and the average age of all the 
home-based workers was 44. Kathryn Stafford, a professor at Ohio 
State's College of Human Ecology, said the home-based workers made 
a big contribution to local economies, buying from local suppliers 
and selling most of their products or services to local customers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	INTERNET STOCKS: While Internet company stocks including Yahoo!,  
America Online and Amazon.com have surged higher lately, they're 
appealing mostly to a narrow segment of the investing public, finds 
PaineWebber and the Gallup Organization in a survey of more than 
1,000 investors. The survey found that just 15 percent of the 
investors queried own or have owned Internet stocks. PaineWebber 
also reported that Internet stock investors tended to be younger 
than the general investing population. Mark Sutton, president of 
PaineWebber's private client business, said Internet stocks may 
appeal to younger investors ``because they are most likely to be 
using those companies' services.'' Moreover, younger investors, who 
don't need their money for imminent retirement or children's 
college tuition, are more likely to buy stocks like Internet issues 
that are considered somewhat risky. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HOW SOON DO I HAVE TO GO THROUGH THIS AGAIN?: The spring means  
the start of home-repair season, and millions of do-it-yourselfers 
will be wondering as they paint and hammer away how long the fruits 
of their labors will last. HouseMaster, a home inspection company, 
put together a list of a home's common features and their life 
spans. For instance, the paint job should last four to seven years. 
The bathroom sink you installed should make it for 10 years or 
more. If you're replacing your own roof, asphalt shingles will last 
15 to 18 years, about the same as a wood roof. But if you install a 
tile roof, chances are you'll be off the hook for replacements once 
the new one's on -- tiles are expected to last 40 years or more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:46:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Susan McDougal Trial Winding Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- In her month-long trial, Susan McDougal  
got what she wanted: a judge, a jury and her lawyer in the room 
while she answered questions in Kenneth Starr's Whitewater 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	They were questions that she refused to answer in 1996 and again  
last year when Starr, the independent counsel, hauled her before 
grand juries to no avail. Instead she spent 18 months in jail for 
civil contempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, after closing arguments on Wednesday, jurors will consider  
Mrs. McDougal's defense that she feared being charged with perjury 
unless she gave Starr a story that she says he wanted to hear -- 
that the Clintons engaged in wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, who with her late husband was a partner with Bill  
and Hillary Clinton in the Whitewater land deal, is charged with 
criminal contempt and obstruction of justice. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final round of testimony Monday, Starr's office tried to  
show that it did everything possible to address her fears about 
giving grand jury testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray Jahn, a former Starr prosecutor, said Mrs. McDougal was told  
in 1996 that if there came a point where there was a question about 
whether she'd committed perjury, the matter would be turned over to 
an independent prosecutor -- and not pursued by the Starr team. 
</P>
<P>
	Jahn denied prosecutors ever promised her relief from other  
legal problems if she cooperated or told her ex-husband -- as she 
claimed -- that she could ``write her own ticket'' if she said she 
had a sexual affair with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Jahn acknowledged, however, that a state prosecutor in  
California had indicated an embezzlement case against Mrs. McDougal 
might be settled by plea bargain. She still refused to cooperate 
with Starr and Mrs. McDougal later was acquitted on the 
embezzlement charge. 
</P>
<P>
	During the trial, Mrs. McDougal's defense got a boost when Judge  
George Howard Jr., allowed, despite strong protests from 
prosecutors, testimony from a Virginia woman who also claimed she 
had been mistreated by Starr prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Susan and I have been relentlessly pursued by the Office of  
Independent Counsel,'' testified Julie Hiatt Steele, who claimed 
she had been indicted because she refused to give false testimony 
against Clinton. Steele faces a trial next month on an indictment 
obtained by Starr's staff that she obstructed justice and lied to a 
grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal used her trial to dramatically press her attack on  
Starr whom she accused of waging a ``personal vendetta'' against 
her. ``It will be an all-out fight,'' she predicted as the trial 
opened March 8. 
</P>
<P>
	When she took the stand two weeks into the trial, McDougal said  
she never discussed a fraudulent $300,000 loan with Bill Clinton -- 
that has been the center of the Whitewater investigation -- and that 
she did not believe Clinton had said ``anything untruthful'' when 
he testified at her 1996 trial involving the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing he said was untrue to me,'' said McDougal from the  
stand, for the first time addressing questions she for 2 1/2 years had 
refused to address for Starr's prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	The criminal contempt and obstruction case centers on Mrs.  
McDougal's state of mind when she refused to cooperate with Starr, 
her defense lawyers argued, because she believed her own words 
would be used against her by Starr's prosecutors even if she told 
the truth. 
</P>
<P>
	A career federal prosecutor, Jahn insisted Monday that the Starr  
prosecutors only wanted Mrs. McDougal to tell the ``total and 
complete truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No matter what Mrs. McDougal claims, added Associate Independent  
Counsel Mark Barrett, the government has only to show that she 
disobeyed a court order to answer the grand jury questions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 10:05:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Few Law Govern Use of Videotape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q. Everywhere I go in public these days, it seems I see a camera  
perched somewhere above, filming my every move. What happens to 
this videotape? 

</P>
<P>
	A. You're not imagining it.  
</P>
<P>
	From banks and ATMs to grocery stores and mini-marts to  
elevators and toll booths, video monitoring is everywhere. And the 
people and organizations who initiate such taping rarely warn you 
that it's happening. 
</P>
<P>
	Few laws explicitly govern the use or abuse of videotape,  
according to Robert Ellis Smith, publisher of the monthly 
newsletter Privacy Journal, based in Providence, R.I. 
</P>
<P>
	He says videotape with sound can occasionally fall under illegal  
wiretapping laws, and some jurisdictions have anti-eavesdropping 
laws. But much of what's filmed is simply silent security video. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early days of taping, security videos were simply endless  
loops that recorded over themselves automatically, Smith says. Now, 
many machines preserve their footage, and its fate varies. 
</P>
<P>
	``What becomes of those tapes? It's not known,'' Smith says.  
``Whether a divorce lawyer or someone else can get hold of those 
tapes, it's unclear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	These days, much filming is done as a matter of routine. And, as  
the cameras reach beyond security, audiences are growing wider. 
Some cameras even allow Internet users to see what people are doing 
someplace else. 
</P>
<P>
	``People go about their business now without thinking twice  
about it, and I think that's regrettable,'' Smith says. ``They 
don't seem concerned about the videotaping of themselves in various 
public places. I don't think they even focus at all on what's 
happening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He believes the people responsible for the taping ``ought to  
articulate their reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You're entitled to privacy protection -- who you're holding  
hands with, what newspaper you may be reading,'' Smith says. 
``Articulating in advance the reason for surveillance should force 
you to stop the surveillance when the reason has disappeared.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:53:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Allied Planes Target Yugoslav Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Allied planes targeted  
transportation links and communication sites today across 
Yugoslavia, and local officials said a NATO attack on a coal mining 
town in central Serbia killed five civilians and injured at least 
30 others. 
</P>
<P>
	The total number of casualties couldn't be independently  
confirmed, but an Associated Press photographer at the scene saw 
two victims who had died in a residential area where several homes 
were flattened. 
</P>
<P>
	Police and army officials blamed the casualties on a series of  
missile attacks in Aleksinac, a town of 17,000 that is 100 miles 
southeast of Belgrade. More bodies were believed to be buried in 
the rubble, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two bodies, along with pools of blood and body parts, were  
in the wreckage of a block of apartments. Bricks, wooden boards and 
roof tiles were strewn about, some thrown up to 200 yards from the 
blast. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, NATO said the strike had apparently been aimed at a  
military target in the area but had no details. A spokesman at NATO 
headquarters, Maj. Dan Baggio, stressed that military planners did 
their best to ``minimize the possibility of collateral damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the incident was being investigated.  
</P>
<P>
	The state-run Tanjug news agency quoted local civil defense  
commander Jovan Zlatic as saying rescue squads were trying to 
retrieve survivors from beneath the rubble. In another 
neighborhood, wrecked cars smoldered hours after the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian state-run TV showed a local clinic badly damaged and an  
emergency unit smashed. Shop windows were shattered in the center 
of the town. A local Red Cross worker, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said that of the 30 wounded, five were in serious 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The airstrikes late Monday and early today aimed to cut the  
Yugoslav military's lines of supply and transport -- roads, bridges, 
airports, fuel depots and command centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb television said NATO struck a fuel depot south of the  
Hungarian border and a railway bridge over the Danube River. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanjug news agency said several missiles blasted a barracks  
today in Prizren, Kosovo's second-largest city. It was the fourth 
attack there since NATO launched the air campaign on March 24 to 
dislodge government forces from the province in southern Serbia, 
where majority ethnic Albanians have been fighting for 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO missiles hit a communications relay station near Kosovo's  
provincial capital, Pristina, and blasted targets on the main road 
from Kosovo to the Serb heartland, Tanjug reported. The runway at 
Pristina's airport was also hit, the independent Beta news agency 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong detonations late Monday in the northern city of Novi Sad  
sent an orange fireball into the night sky, Serbian state 
television showed. Tanjug said the power station at the city oil 
refinery had been hit, causing ``enormous damage'' to oil 
installations, depots and a major pipeline in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire also caused the emission of poisonous fumes, forcing  
about 300 from a nearby settlement to flee, Tanjug said. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian TV said two NATO planes were shot down during their  
attack on the Novi Sad area Monday night. But NATO spokesman Lt. 
Col. Michael Kaemmerer denied the report, saying all planes had 
returned to their bases. 
</P>
<P>
	Beta also said missiles had struck the airport at Nis,  
headquarters of the army corps responsible for military operations 
in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Three powerful explosions were also heard northeast of Belgrade  
near Pancevo early today, Tanjug said. 
</P>
<P>
	In central Serbia, Tanjug said a TV relay tower was downed near  
Kragujevac, interrupting the reception of TV and radio programs. 
Two powerful explosions were also heard near the central city of 
Kraljevo, Beta reported. The town crisis center said a nearby 
barracks was targeted. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, President Clinton promised an ``undiminished,  
unceasing and unrelenting'' air campaign, saying it would no longer 
be enough for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to just stop 
the killing in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our plan is to persist until we prevail,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Milder weather was little comfort for the tens of thousands of  
refugees who continued to pour out of Kosovo. The U.N. refugee 
agency said the number of ethnic Albanians reaching neighboring 
countries had risen to nearly 400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	More than half have taken shelter in Albania, one of Europe's  
poorest countries. Albania offered Monday to take more refugees 
from Macedonia to prevent Western nations from dispersing them to 
countries far from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	In Macedonia, conditions remained dire at a makeshift refugee  
camp at the border town of Blace, where thousands were living in 
shelters of plastic and blankets in a muddy, fetid border area. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are too many people in that small concentrated area for  
safety and also for sanitation and health concerns,'' said Chris 
Thomas of the American Red Cross. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Monday, 239,000 refugees had arrived in Albania, 120,000  
in Macedonia and 35,000 in Montenegro, the U.N. High Commissioner 
for Refugees said. 
</P>
<P>
	Relief flights carrying 200 tons of food and other emergency  
supplies were scheduled to fly into Albania and Macedonia, NATO 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It announced plans by many member-states to temporarily take in  
110,000 refugees to ease the pressure on Yugoslavia's neighbors. 
Airlifts began Monday to Turkey and Norway. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, Belgium, NATO Air Commodore David Wilby said Monday  
the alliance would take advantage of better weather over Kosovo to 
accelerate its attacks on Serb and Yugoslav forces accused of 
systematically expelling ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will focus our attention on fielded forces in Kosovo,''  
Wilby said. ``We will disrupt Serbian military operations on the 
ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Washington has agreed to send 24 Apache helicopters, 2,600  
troops and a missile launching system to Albania to give NATO the 
ability to directly attack Serb troops and tanks in Kosovo, where 
more than 2,000 people have died over the past 13 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Deploying low-flying attack helicopters and support troops in  
Albania would mark a substantial escalation of the NATO campaign to 
try to force Milosevic to agree to a U.S.-backed peace deal and an 
autonomy pact with the Kosovo Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Human Rights Watch reported Monday that Baton Haxhiu, editor in  
chief of Koha Ditore, the Albanian-language newspaper in Pristina, 
was alive and well. NATO officials earlier said he had been 
reported executed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:53:10 </DATE_TIME>
