<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'The Matrix' Scores at Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Graphic BOXOFFICE    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Matrix'' became the highest-earning  
film to open during an Easter weekend, helping jump-start Keanu 
Reeves' career as an action star and yanking the industry out of 
its post-''Titanic'' funk. 
</P>
<P>
	The surreal sci-fi film snapped the record for an April debut by  
earning $27.8 million at North American theaters, industry figures 
showed Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Matrix'' easily beat the two closest movies. The  
teen-oriented ``10 Things I Hate About You'' finished second with 
$8.3 million and the Steve Martin-Goldie Hawn comedy ``The 
Out-Of-Towners'' finishing third with $8.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Matrix'' helped propel the box office to only its second  
weekend this year with a higher overall gross than the year before, 
when ``Titanic'' was sailing strong. 
</P>
<P>
	It also provided a lift to Reeves, whose career had been  
foundering since he appeared opposite Sandra Bullock in the popular 
action movie ``Speed'' in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Once considered for summer release, ``The Matrix'' was slotted  
for April by Warner Bros., putting it safely away from the ``Star 
Wars'' juggernaut on May 19. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we approached the opening, we were strongly skewed toward  
males,'' said Warner Bros. distribution head Dan Fellman. ``As the 
weekend progressed, more and more females came to the movie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the romantic comedy ``Forces of Nature'' with Ben  
Affleck and Ms. Bullock, finished in fifth place with $6.2 million, 
while Ron Howard's ``EDtv'' plummeted 47 percent in its second week 
to finish sixth with $4.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Still enjoying a warm Oscar glow, best-picture winner  
``Shakespeare in Love'' had $3.1 million for seventh, and 
foreign-language winner ``Life is Beautiful'' had $2.7 million for 
ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandwiched between the Oscar winners was the low-budget animated  
kid's movie ``Doug's 1st Movie'' in eighth with $3.1 million. ``The 
Mod Squad'' tumbled 58 percent in the second week to 10th place 
with $2.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 20 movies at North American theaters Friday through  
Sunday, followed by studio, gross, number of theater locations, 
average receipts per location, total gross and number of weeks in 
release, as compiled by Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. and ACNielsen 
EDI Inc.: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``The Matrix,'' Warner Bros., $27.8 million, 2,849 locations,  
$9,754 average, $37.4 million, one week. 
</P>
<P>
	2. ``10 Things I Hate About You,'' Disney, $8.3 million, 2,271  
locations, $3,668 average, $11.5 million, one week. 
</P>
<P>
	3. ``The Out-of-Towners,'' Paramount, $8.2 million, 2,102  
locations, $3,913 average, $8.2 million, one week. 
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Analyze This,'' Warner Bros., $6.3 million, 2,335  
locations, $2,712 average, $78.5 million, five weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	5. ``Forces of Nature,'' DreamWorks, $6.2 million, 2,278  
locations, $2,722 average, $36.5 million, three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	6. ``EDtv,'' Universal, $4.4 million, 2,631 locations, $1,690  
average, $15.4 million, two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	7. ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Miramax, $3.1 million, 1,735  
locations, $1,795 average, $84.1 million, 17 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Doug's 1st Movie,'' Disney, $3.07 million, 2,268 locations,  
$1,354 average, $9.3 million, two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Life is Beautiful,'' Miramax, $2.7 million, 1,130  
locations, $2,362 average, $44.7 million, 24 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	10. ``The Mod Squad,'' MGM/UA, $2.6 million, 2,290 locations,  
$1,122 average, $10.4 million, two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	11. ``Baby Geniuses,'' Sony, $2 million, 1,702 locations, $1,188  
average, $18.5 million, four weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	12. ``True Crime,'' Warner Bros., $1.9 million, 1,801 locations,  
$1,029 average, $13.4 million, three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	13. ``Cruel Intentions,'' Sony, $1.2 million, 1,405 locations,  
$827 average, $35.4 million, five weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	14. ``The King and I,'' Warner Bros., $1 million, 1,932  
locations, $527 average, $8.8 million, three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	15. ``October Sky,'' Universal, $836,995, 731 locations, $1,145  
average, $26.7 million, seven weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	16. ``Saving Private Ryan,'' DreamWorks, $705,892, 542  
locations, $1,302 average, $212.8 million, 37 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	17. ``The Rage: Carrie 2,'' MGM/UA, $646,609, 872 locations,  
$742 average, $16.4 million, four weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	18. ``A Bug's Life,'' Disney, $423,476, 649 locations, $653  
average, $161.2 million, 20 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	19. ``The Corruptor,'' New Line, $412,191, 766 locations, $538  
average, $14.3 million, four weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	20. ``The Prince of Egypt,'' DreamWorks, $393,530, 708  
locations, $556 average, $99.5 million, 16 weeks. 
</P>
