<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iverson Returns from Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Answer is back.  
</P>
<P>
	Allen Iverson, trying to shake a bruised thigh and a feud with  
76ers coach Larry Brown, scored 27 points in 46 minutes tonight as 
Philadelphia beat the Milwaukee Bucks 95-87. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson, the NBA's leading scorer, had not played since  
exchanging words with Brown on the sideline Friday night against 
Cleveland. He had played with a severely bruised right thigh since 
a collision with the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal on March 19 before 
getting benched against the Cavaliers. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson did not play the opening 2:03 of the second quarter of  
an 85-80 loss to Cleveland after going 0-for-7 in the first 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	When Brown told Iverson to go back into the game, Iverson,  
according to courtside reporters, muttered, ``It's about time you 
put me back in,'' and used an obscenity. Brown sent him back to the 
bench. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Iverson denied he cursed Brown, but the coach  
disagreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``You all heard it,'' Brown said. ``My team heard it. The guy I  
substituted for heard it. But again, it was over. It was one little 
thing, and it was over at halftime. Now we've got to get him back 
healthy playing as well as he was playing before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown and Iverson came out of their latest spat agreeing on two  
things: They will have more disagreements, and Iverson sat out the 
second half against the Cavs and Sunday's game in Toronto because 
he was injured -- not because of their feud. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said he intended to play Iverson in the second half Friday  
night, but Iverson told him his leg stiffened and he couldn't play. 
</P>
<P>
	To anyone who questioned whether he was sitting out to get back  
at his coach, Iverson said, ``They're out of their mind I don't 
even worry about those people, because they probably don't know a 
damn thing about basketball anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute with Brown was the latest in a long list for  
Iverson, nicknamed ``The Answer'' for a shoe that is named after 
him. The two quarreled last season over playing time, coaching 
style, missed practices and lateness. 
</P>
<P>
	They renewed their feud on March 11, when Iverson missed  
practice without an excuse. Brown let the team decide how to handle 
it, and followed their recommendation not to fine Iverson. 
</P>
<P>
	On another front, Brown and Iverson's bodyguard, Terry Royster,  
made up after Brown had kicked Royster out of the locker room 
following the Cleveland game. The two talked after practice Monday 
and settled their differences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 00:23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> E. Coli Blamed in Minn. Beef Recall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Authorities are investigating an outbreak of  
illness from E. coli-contaminated ground beef after at least six 
guests became ill at a Maine ski resort. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking into whether or not other states may be involved  
as well,'' said Tom Skinner, a spokesman for the federal Centers 
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The outbreak has been linked to meat recalled from Rochester  
Meats Inc. in Rochester, Minn., the Agriculture Department said 
Monday. Beth Gaston, spokeswoman for the food safety and inspection 
office, said scientists found ``genetic fingerprints'' linking a 
strain of E. coli ``in samples of the meat from Rochester Meats to 
the patients in Maine who have become ill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On USDA orders, Rochester Meats Inc., of Rochester, Minn., which  
supplies meat for restaurants and institutions, recalled 170,780 
pounds of product last week. That's the equivalent of one day's 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said Monday they were unaware of any link  
between their product and illnesses. ``USDA has not confirmed that 
with us,'' said Rochester Meats spokeswoman Joanne Randen. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled products include frozen ground-beef patties, ground  
chuck patties, chopped beefsteak, beef patties, meat for chili, 
beef patty mix and pure beef bulk. 
</P>
<P>
	The meat was produced Dec. 1 and sold in 10-, 15- and 20-pound  
packages. They are marked with the Julian code 8335 and 
Establishment 8999 in the inspection mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Maine officials had a tally of seven E. coli illnesses, but USDA  
has not confirmed the seventh was a genetic match to the Rochester 
Meats outbreak, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The people became ill while visiting the Sunday River Ski Resort  
in Bethel, Maine, said Dr. Kathleen Gensheimer, state 
epidemiologist for the Maine Department of Human Services. 
</P>
<P>
	The first illness was reported Feb. 11, and three people were  
hospitalized, Gensheimer said. Everybody in the group, which 
included four children, has recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	It is possible that other people became ill but treated  
themselves instead of seeking medical attention, Gensheimer said. 
</P>
<P>
	There are an estimated 10,000 to 20,000 cases in the United  
States every year of infections attributed to E. coli 0157:H7, the 
strain in the Maine case, according to the CDC. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingested by humans, E. coli bacteria can cause serious illness  
and sometimes death, especially in children and the elderly. 
Symptoms include chills and bloody diarrhea. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident is the second outbreak in the country related to  
contaminated meat in recent months. Bil Mar Foods in Zeeland, 
Mich., recalled 15 million pounds of hot dogs and deli meats in 
December because of possible contamination with listeria. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen deaths and six miscarriages and stillbirths have been  
linked to the Bil Mar recall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 12:15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Wings Hot Since Deadline Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Since picking up four players hours before the  
March 23 trading deadline, Detroit has been unbeatable. 
</P>
<P>
	That can only mean trouble for the rest of the NHL -- the Red  
Wings were pretty good to begin with. 
</P>
<P>
	Good, but not great.  
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings, winners of the last two Stanley Cup  
championships, had losing streaks of three, four and five games. 
But since acquiring Chris Chelios, Wendell Clark, Ulf Samuelsson 
and goalie Bill Ranford at the trade deadline, the team has won 
seven straight games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has really revived everybody,'' said goalie Chris Osgood,  
who has won five of those seven games, one of them his third 
shutout of the season. ``We're a totally different team the last 
two weeks. We're excited again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What the newcomers appear to have added was a bit of nastiness.  
That was on display early in Monday night's 3-2 win over the 
Anaheim Mighty Ducks when Darren McCarty drew two minutes for 
roughing just 35 seconds into the game. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty, who had missed the 10 previous games with an injury,  
has never been a wallflower. But until the new guys showed up, the 
Red Wings couldn't afford to use him as an enforcer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've proved in the past that you have to use the regular  
season to set things up for the playoffs,'' McCarty said. ``Right 
now, we're gearing ourselves up for the postseason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings are attempting to become the first team to win  
three consecutive Stanley Cups since the New York Islanders won 
four straight (1980-83) 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit (41-30-6) is the No. 3 team in the Western Conference  
with almost no chance of overhauling first-place Dallas. That means 
the Red Wings probably will draw Anaheim or St. Louis in the first 
round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Mighty Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg wouldn't mind if it was his  
team. He respects Detroit, but Hartsburg thinks maybe too much is 
being made of the Red Wings' recent acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's a bit of a slap at the other guys who were  
here,'' Hartsburg said. ``They were a pretty good hockey team 
before the trades. 
</P>
<P>
	``But, if we come back here for the playoffs, maybe we'll have  
learned something about how it's going to be. They've been on a 
roll, no question about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It has been almost storybook stuff since the new players  
arrived. Clark has scored four goals, including the winner against 
Philadelphia on March 28. Chelios, who has been paired on defense 
with Nicklas Lidstrom, has played almost 25 minutes a game. And he 
added a goal in the Red Wings' 6-1 victory over Tampa Bay on March 
26. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranford, 5-18-3 for the season, has won both his starts since  
coming to Detroit as Osgood's backup. Samuelsson, recovering from a 
broken foot, is expected to be ready for the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can never tell, but the guys have helped out,'' said  
Detroit coach Scotty Bowman, who is shooting for an NHL-best ninth 
Stanley Cup. ``It's given us a chance to play different guys, where 
we might not have had that luxury before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Big trades don't always work. Sometimes the new guys don't fit  
in. Yet Detroit's four newcomers were made welcome at once. 
</P>
<P>
	``These guys are not just average guys,'' Detroit forward Martin  
Lapointe said. ``They are world-class players. They adapt to 
pressure well. They would fit in well on any team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lapointe noted that Clark, Chelios and Ranford all earned the  
respect of the others on the very first day by working hard in 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``You should see Billy in practice,'' Lapointe said. ``You can't  
measure that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 06:35:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gotti Plea Is Latest Mob Mess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Gotti family's reign atop the Gambino crime  
family provides an apt metaphor for the mob's past and future: It 
started with a bang on a city street and finished with a whimper in 
a suburban courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	John ``Junior'' Gotti's surprise guilty plea Monday in  
Westchester County was another big blow to New York's five Mafia 
families, where age and incessant prosecution are taking a 
devastating toll against the once-mighty mob. 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti, who pleaded guilty to racketeering, bribery, extortion  
and other charges, is the highest-profile mobster to take a fall 
lately. But the son of the jailed-for-life ``Dapper Don'' is hardly 
the only one. 
</P>
<P>
	Another top Gambino family leader, John ``Jackie Nose'' D'Amico,  
also pleaded guilty in the case. In January 1998, top Gambino aide 
Nicholas ``Little Nick'' Corozzo -- once considered next in line for 
family leadership -- was sentenced to nearly six years in jail for 
running a Florida loansharking operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe DeFede, the acting boss of the Luchese family, pleaded  
guilty in December to an extortion scheme in New York City's 
Garment District. Colombo boss Andrew Russo was found guilty of 
obstruction of justice three months ago. And Dominic ``Quiet Dom'' 
Cirillo, who succeeded Vincent ``Chin'' Gigante atop the Genovese 
family, had his reign cut short by a heart attack last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want to be the boss of a family, you have to pay the  
price,'' ex-FBI mob investigator Bruce Mouw said earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gottis represent much of what's gone wrong with the mob,  
experts say. Even if John Sr. runs the family from prison, much of 
its lucrative business is gone forever. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Gotti ascended to power after the Dec. 16, 1985, hit  
on his predecessor, ``Big Paul'' Castellano, outside the Sparks 
Steak House in Manhattan. Castellano mixed mob business with 
legitimate interests, signaling a change in the traditional mob 
methodology. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gotti was a stone gangster, and a charismatic one. His  
ascension signaled a return to the old, violent ways. His public 
persona -- $2,000 suits, hand-painted ties, expensive tastes -- made 
him America's best-known gangster since Al Capone. 
</P>
<P>
	It also ensured his downfall, as he quickly became the FBI's No.  
1 target. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Gotti's 1992 murder and racketeering conviction, he  
installed his son as head of the family, with veteran Gambino 
leaders assigned to assist him. But the family's influence dwindled 
under Junior. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gotti case was typical of today's mob prosecution, with made  
men once sworn to omerta -- the oath of silence -- lining up as 
government witnesses. The elder Gotti had his Sammy Gravano; the 
younger Gotti faced implication from ex-Luchese acting boss 
Alphonse ``Little Al'' D'Arco and mobsters Dominic ``Fat Dom'' 
Borghese and Willie Marshall. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the mob's veteran leadership lifers -- men like the elder  
Gotti, Gigante, Gravano, Carmine ``The Snake'' Persico, Cirillo -- 
are aging, imprisoned or working for the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Its generation of replacements, mobsters and mob experts have  
agreed, is inexperienced, unskilled and undisciplined -- more 
interested in making mayhem than money. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best and the brightest are not taking leadership roles,''  
says Ronald Goldstock, former head of the state Organized Crime 
Task Force. 
</P>
<P>
	The bosses aren't getting any younger, either. The reputed head  
of the Bonanno family, Joseph Massino, is 55, making him the 
youngest of the alleged bosses of the five families. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the mob's younger generation other than young Gotti have  
attracted much government attention -- another sign of its 
diminished capacity. One, Genovese family street boss Liborio 
``Barney'' Bellomo, 40, is currently in the second year of a 
10-year sentence for extortion and murder conspiracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
