<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sears Settles Battery Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. will pay $985,000  
and extend free replacement warranties on some of its car batteries 
to settle allegations it passed off used batteries as new. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears, which did not admit fault, also agreed to add five months  
to the free-replacement warrantees it offered on Exide batteries it 
sold before April 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``In many instances, customers who thought they were buying new  
batteries were in fact buying batteries Sears had previously used 
to test care electrical systems or batteries that had been returned 
to Sears by other customers,'' Attorney General Robert Butterworth 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears denies the allegations. The store had problems with the  
quality of Exide batteries a few years ago that were resolved, said 
Sears spokesman David Albritton. 
</P>
<P>
	Exide Corp. is the target of an investigation by the attorney  
general for allegedly selling defective, used and mislabeled auto 
batteries in Florida, as well as misleading investors and 
improperly crediting customer accounts. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
