<DOCNO> APW19990406.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 14:54:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kazak Currency Continues Nosedive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALMATY, Kazakstan (AP) -- The Kazak currency dipped to nearly  
half of last week's value in hectic trading Tuesday, although 
ordinary citizens seemed to heed the government's appeals and 
refrain from rushing to convert their savings into dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazakstan's government decided Sunday to stop buying up the  
national currency, the tenge, to bolster its price, because the 
policy was depleting the Central Asian nation's hard currency 
reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was seen as signaling that damage in Kazakstan was  
beginning to mount from the economic crisis in neighboring Russia, 
its largest trading partner. 
</P>
<P>
	The tenge, which had held steady at about 88 to the dollar for  
months, has been dropping since the announcement. It dipped to 150 
to the dollar when trading opened Tuesday, but the government 
announced at the end of the day that the average rate in Tuesday's 
trading was 138 to the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazakstan's Central Bank chairman Kadyrzhan Damitov said even  
that rate was unrealistically low and that the drop was driven by 
traders' nervousness and panic selling. 
</P>
<P>
	Ordinary Kazaks seemed calmer, and a rush of withdrawals from  
the nation's main bank ebbed Tuesday, National Savings Bank chief 
Karim Masimov said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people in this former Soviet republic had rushed to the  
bank Monday to take out their tenge deposits and convert them to 
dollars. Panic dollar buying on Monday drove the tenge's black 
market rate to 200 to the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The government tried to quell the panic by promising to convert  
all bank savings into hard currency at a highly favorable rate if 
depositors agreed to freeze their accounts for nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	But the International Monetary Fund envoy to Kazakstan, Paul  
Ross, urged the government to renege on that promise Tuesday, and 
said Kazak depositors should pay the price for their misplaced 
trust in the national currency. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference in Almaty, Ross also urged the government  
not to freeze consumer energy prices as many impoverished Kazaks 
have demanded, saying that would hurt producers and the overall 
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
