<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Surgery Sidelines Marlins' Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Florida Marlins outfielder Cliff Floyd will be  
sidelined a little longer than expected with his latest injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd underwent surgery today to repair torn cartilage in his  
left knee, and is expected to miss another 2-4 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd, 26, went on the disabled list for the fourth time in his  
career March 30 because of the knee injury, which was initially 
diagnosed as a sprain. Swelling persisted, and the tear was 
discovered Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins are counting on Floyd to anchor their lineup. He  
avoided injuries last year, hitting .282 with 22 home runs and 90 
RBIs, and was rewarded in January with a four-year, $19 million 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Preston Wilson will fill in for Floyd in left field.  
</P>
<P>
	``He put up big numbers last year,'' Wilson said. ``No one  
person can fill what he can do. Everybody who's out there is going 
to have to pull together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, 24, spent most of last season at Triple-A Charlotte  
after being acquired in a trade with the New York Mets. Manager 
John Boles said Wilson has the potential to eventually hit 30 
homers and steal 30 bases. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can cry and moan about Cliff not being in the lineup, but  
there's always a bright side,'' Boles said. ``We had been trying to 
trade for Preston, and now we've got him, so let's play him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd will be on crutches for two or three days before he begins  
rehabilitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
