<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MCI Wants To Enter Wireless Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom Inc. is in negotiations to buy  
Nextel Communications Inc. in another attempt to break into the $33 
billion U.S. wireless telephone business, according to a person 
familiar with the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The discussions are still in the early stages and no deal is  
expected for at least a week, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom is the nation's No. 2 provider of long-distance  
calling service, but the only major telephone company without a 
stake in the lucrative and rapidly growing market for wireless 
communication. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, MCI WorldCom backed out of a bidding war for  
AirTouch Communications, much to the relief of shareholders who 
were concerned about paying a hefty price -- Vodafone's winning bid 
was worth $56 billion -- so soon after WorldCom's costly purchase of 
MCI Communications last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, however, many of MCI WorldCom's major investors  
support a deal with Nextel even though that would mean taking on 
Nextel's hefty $7 billion debt burden. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can keep (the debt) in mind, but I don't think that  
should prevent them from acquiring Nextel,'' said Max Katcher, 
portfolio manager of the Ameritor Funds, which own 21,000 shares of 
MCI Worldcom. ``They cannot afford to stay out of'' the wireless 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Ebbers, chief executive of MCI WorldCom, has said he  
doesn't want to issue a lot of new stock to acquire another company 
because it would reduce MCI WorldCom's earnings per share -- a key 
measure of a company's value for investors. 
</P>
<P>
	But while that was a big factor in MCI WorldCom's decision to  
withdraw a reported $55 billion bid for AirTouch, it wouldn't be as 
big a consideration in making an offer for Nextel, which has a 
market value of $11.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation about a MCI WorldCom-Nextel deal has swirled around  
Wall Street since the AirTouch bidding war ended. News that the 
companies were in ``substantive discussions'' was first reported 
Tuesday in The Wall Street Journal, which said people involved in 
the talks put the odds of a deal at no more than 50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But the pressure on MCI WorldCom is mounting. The number of  
wireless customers in the United States jumped 25 percent last year 
to 69.2 million, according to the Cellular Telecommunications 
Industry Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Nextel, which controls 4 percent of that market, is the last  
major independent wireless phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a great deal of room for expansion there,'' said  
Katcher of Ameritor. Any earnings dilution ``will be overcome with 
improved earnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom's stock fell $2.93 3/4 a share to $89.56 1/4 in Tuesday's  
trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market as some investors bailed out, 
but the decline was nothing like the two-day 10 percent drop in 
January that accompanied the bidding war for AirTouch. 
</P>
<P>
	Nextel's stock, which has risen 20 percent over the last two  
weeks on takeover rumors, fell 43 3/4 cents to $39.18 3/4 on Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	As CEO, Ebbers has built a telecom giant in just three years and  
earned a reputation as a savvy dealmaker. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to see him over paying, and I don't think he  
will,'' said Catherine Jackson, a managing director for Trainer 
Wortham Co., a money management firm that owns 600,000 shares of 
MCI WorldCom. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, who also owns shares of AT&AMP;T and Qwest, said that of  
those three companies, ``I like MCI WorldCom the best -- but there's 
a hole and the hole is wireless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom could try to build its own wireless network, buying  
companies like Omnipoint Corp. and a handful of other technology 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T has taken that route. The No. 1 long-distance company,  
which spent $11.5 billion to acquire McCaw Cellular Communications 
in 1994, spent $1 billion last year and plans to shell out another 
$2 billion this year to expand its network and entice customers 
with its nationwide one-rate wireless plan. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom could also buy one of the Baby Bells, which all  
have extensive wireless operations. But a deal like that would 
likely take years to clear regulatory hurdles -- precious time in a 
fast-growing industry like wireless. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever MCI WorldCom does, investors know they have to do  
something. 
</P>
<P>
	In the future, Jackson said, ``we are all going to be walking  
around New York City or Montana with these wireless devices, and 
MCI WorldCom has got to be there.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
