<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Group Claims Lab Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- An animal rights group claimed responsibility  
for ransacking 12 University of Minnesota labs, taking dozens of 
research animals and causing an estimated $1 million in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the Animal Liberation Front said the group  
smashed computers, tipped over lab equipment and wrecked 
microscopes early Monday to protest the use of animals in 
scientific research. 
</P>
<P>
	The group said in a communique that 27 pigeons, 48 mice, 36 rats  
and five salamanders were taken out of the labs. The university 
initially estimated that about 75 animals were taken. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ALF is taking action immediately to free these animals  
from their exploitation,'' group spokesman Kevin Kjonaas said. He 
said the group had found homes for the animals. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials said the damage will seriously impede  
research on Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, cancer and other diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	Researcher Dr. Walter Low said the damage set back the  
Alzheimer's research alone by two years. One of the pieces of 
equipment damaged was an incubator containing brain cells from a 
patients participating in a research project. 
</P>
<P>
	``You begin to have an impact on a patient who's donated their  
cells for us to develop a vaccine, and we no longer have that 
vaccine to offer to that patient,'' Low said. ``That patient has no 
other hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	University Police Chief Joy Rikala said investigators are not  
ruling out the possibility that the vandals had inside help. Rikala 
said none of the freed animals are infectious or pose a health 
threat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
