<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Rally / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A late surge in telecommunications shares sent  
Japan's main stock index to its highest close in more than eight 
months today. The U.S. dollar retreated against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 144.93  
points, or 0.89 percent, to end the day at 16,479.71 -- its highest 
close since July 21. On Monday, the average finished up 44.59 
points, or 0.27 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.06 yen in late trading, down 0.30 yen from  
late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
121.83 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo stock exchange, shares recovered from morning  
losses triggered by profit-taking, as buying of telecoms issues by 
foreign investors in the last half-hour of trading boosted the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was heavy buying in the information technology sector''  
such as Sony and NTT, said Yoshio Watanabe, a manager at the 
futures section of Toyo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors that the ruling Liberal Democratic Party might be  
considering an $83 billion supplementary budget this fiscal year 
also fueled the last-minute rally. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 15.44 points, or 1.18 percent, to 1,322.61. 
The TOPIX closed up 3.00 points, or 0.23 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 568.10 million shares changed hands on the First  
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 558.74 million on 
Monday. Advancing issues outnumbered declines 725 to 474, while 129 
issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar tumbled as Japanese exporters,  
hedging against future weakness in the dollar, sold the U.S. 
currency to repatriate funds quickly and avoid losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite today's dip, the dollar is expected to be supported by  
the continuing turmoil in Yugoslavia, where NATO forces have 
intensified their bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. currency is often seen as a haven for investors during  
times of international crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.75 yen and 121.82 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.19 yen, down  
from 130.61 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.795 percent from Monday's finish of 1.740 percent, 
driving its price down to 100.04 yen from 100.51 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
