<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslav Sites Targeted by NATO  
</P>
<P>
	ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Allied warplanes blasted fuel  
depots, oil refineries, roads and bridges in the most intensive 
night of air raids across Yugoslavia. The refugee airlift has 
begun, meanwhile, for the first of at least 110,000 ethnic 
Albanians who have fled Yugoslav forces in Kosovo for Albania, 
Macedonia and Montenegro. More than 400,000 ethnic Albanians have 
left the embattled Serbian province since the NATO air campaign 
began nearly two weeks ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Town Bathed in Blood  
</P>
<P>
	ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Pools of blood, two corpses and  
parts of dismembered bodies lay in the wreckage of a large 
apartment building today in this central Serbian town after an 
overnight air strike. Yugoslav authorities said five people were 
killed and at least 30 injured when NATO missiles hit a residential 
neighborhood last night in this coal mining community of 17,000 
people about 100 miles southeast of Belgrade. Journalists permitted 
to visit the area today saw a destroyed apartment building. Some 
bricks, wooden boards and roof tiles were tossed more than 500 feet 
from the site. Three two-story homes were also flattened. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockerbie Suspects in Dutch Court  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- Two Libyan suspects in the 1988  
Pan Am jet bombing listened today while the names of all 270 
victims were read aloud by the Scottish authorities who will try 
them at a deserted U.S. airbase. Suspected former intelligence 
agents Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah were 
fingerprinted, photographed and gave DNA samples one day after 
Libya surrendered them for trial. The Libyans will be arraigned 
today on a 1991 indictment accusing them of blowing up Flight 103 
over Lockerbie, Scotland. 

</P>
<P>
	Animal Group Claims Lab Damage  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- An animal rights group claimed responsibility  
for ransacking 12 University of Minnesota labs, taking dozens of 
research animals and causing an estimated $1 million in damage. A 
spokesman for the Animal Liberation Front said the group smashed 
computers, tipped over lab equipment and wrecked microscopes early 
yesterday to protest the use of animals in scientific research. The 
group said that 27 pigeons, 48 mice, 36 rats and five salamanders 
were taken out of the labs. 

</P>
<P>
	News Corp. To Buy Liberty Media  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- News Corp. plans to expand its cable television  
reach, buying ``substantially all'' of Liberty Media's portion of a 
joint venture in a $1.43 million stock swap. The Fox/Liberty 
Network is half-owned by Liberty and half-owned by News Corp. 
subsidiary Fox Entertainment Group. Under the deal, News Corp. will 
gain control of regional sports network Fox Sports Net, which 
reaches more than 62 million households across the United States, 
entertainment network FX, which reaches more than 39 million 
households, and other related businesses. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL Buys Online Calendar Provider  
</P>
<P>
	DULLES, Va. (AP) -- America Online has acquired When Inc., which  
provides a Web-based calendar service that allows users to keep 
track of their schedules from any computer connected to the 
Internet. AOL said it would begin a new version of the When.com 
service this summer. The calendar service allows users to keep 
track of appointments, birthdays and upcoming activities. The Wall 
Street Journal today quoted sources as saying it was worth about 
$150 million in stock. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 6 in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices are mixed in early trading today.  
Just before 10 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials are up 5.83 to 
10,013.16. Declines on the New York Stock Exchange led advances 
878-679. The Nasdaq was down 6.41 at 2,553.65. 

</P>
<P>
	Nagano Residents Sue IOC for $7M  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Three residents of Nagano sued the IOC and its  
president Juan Antonio Samaranch today, demanding the return of 
nearly $7 million in taxpayer money used in the campaign to get 
last year's Winter Games. One of the plaintiffs, former assemblyman 
Kaoru Iwata, said the lawsuit is ``the only way to impeach the 
injustice'' since the IOC and Samaranch will not punish nine IOC 
members suspected by the Japanese Olympic Committee of violating 
IOC rules by receiving ``excessive'' entertainment. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

</P>
