<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mariano Palacios Alcocer, who abruptly  
resigned as head of Mexico's ruling Institutional Revolutionary 
Party last month, was named the new labor secretary Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He switches places with Jose Antonio Gonzalez Fernandez, who had  
stepped down from the labor post on March 18 to seek the party's 
presidency, which he won. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez Fernandez, who was said to be President Ernesto  
Zedillo's pick to head the party, easily won election to the post 
after the only other candidate dropped out, alleging the race was 
unfair. 
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo also announced Tuesday that Arturo Warman would resign  
as secretary of agrarian reform to become the president's social 
development coordinator, Notimex said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- The governor of Brazil's third-richest  
state indicated Tuesday that he will not lift the moratorium on 
debt payments to the federal government he declared three months 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Minas Gerais state Gov. Itamar Franco, a former Brazilian  
president, sent world markets tumbling in January by announcing a 
90-day moratorium on $11 billion in debt, claiming the state was 
broke. The move forced the federal government to devalue its 
currency to stop a run on cash reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, Franco's successor as  
president and formerly his finance minister, responded by 
suspending millions of dollars in federal funds for Minas Gerais. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Franco seemed intent to continue the moratorium.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's the federal government that owes Minas Gerais,'' Franco  
was quoted as saying by the Estado news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Gov. Newton Cardoso later said the state will not resume  
payments to the federal government without an inventory of how much 
each side owes the other. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the former  
president who left Mexico in disgrace after the 1994 peso collapse, 
wants to one day return home from self-imposed exile, his son said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has expressed his desire to return to our country when it  
would be prudent and when the conditions for it exist,'' Carlos 
Emiliano Salinas Occelli was quoted in Mexico City newspapers 
Tuesday as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Salinas said his father continues to live in Dublin,  
Ireland, despite rumors he has moved to Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Salinas de Gortari, president from 1988 to 1984, was scandalized  
by the arrest of his older brother, Raul, on charges of corruption 
and of masterminding the 1994 assassination of a political rival. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlos Salinas de Gortari has not been charged with any crime.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- After the secret police detained his  
son, a key opposition leader charged President Hugo Chavez on 
Tuesday with persecuting political opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are living with a government of persecution, of  
intimidation,'' Lewis Perez, secretary general of Democratic 
Action, told reporters. He called on Venezuelans to ``fight against 
the current regime to maintain democracy and liberty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A former army paratrooper who led a failed 1992 coup attempt,  
Chavez became president in February. His detractors fear he will 
rule with an iron fist. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Perez, 24, was detained Monday night by secret police who  
said they were investigating allegations of arms trafficking. He 
was still being held Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesus Urdaneta, head of the secret police, said authorities were  
conducting a normal investigation based on suspicions that Perez 
broke the law. Urdaneta met Tuesday afternoon with Chavez at 
Miraflores presidential palace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
