<DOCNO> APW19990406.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 03:14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge OKs Radiation Suit Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A judge has approved a tentative $5 million  
settlement of a lawsuit charging that cancer patients were 
unknowingly subjected to military-sponsored radiation experiments 
in the 1960s and '70s. 
</P>
<P>
	The families that filed the class-action lawsuit claimed  
high-dose radiation hastened the deaths and increased the suffering 
of patients, in effect making them casualties of the Cold War. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed five years ago, alleged that terminally ill  
cancer patients treated at Cincinnati General Hospital between 1960 
and 1971 were given full-body and partial-body doses of radiation 
so researchers could measure its effects. The facility is now known 
as University Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Defendants, including doctors, the federal government and the  
hospital, argued that they attempted to ease suffering and that 
patients died because they already were terminally ill with various 
forms of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one of the patients survives; she was 10 when she received  
radiation treatment for bone cancer in 1969. Many of the 90 
patients died soon after receiving radiation. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Sandra Beckwith said Monday that she would  
hold a hearing May 4 to make the settlement final, barring any 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the families would get about $50,000 each, said Robert  
Newman, attorney for about 50 plaintiffs. ``I think everybody 
around the table is pleased and happy it is over,'' he said. A 
probate court would determine how to distribute the money. 
Attorneys have asked for $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers acknowledged that the Defense Department paid  
$651,000 for the test results so it could learn about the effects 
of radiation exposure. They maintained that they thought radiation 
-- still used in treating some cancers -- would be beneficial. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed settlement also would require a memorial plaque at  
the University of Cincinnati campus and an apology from the federal 
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 14:55:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Platinum Prices Fall Sharply  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Platinum futures prices fell sharply Tuesday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange amid a perception that South African production 
is rising and would offset a four-month delay in shipments of the 
metal from Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, corn and soybeans retreated, while pork  
futures advanced a second day. 
</P>
<P>
	Platinum tumbled as the U.S. dollar strengthened against South  
Africa's rand. Since platinum is sold for dollars, there is an 
incentive to a producer with a weaker local currency to step up 
sales when the dollar is rising. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders reasoned that the weaker rand was likely to encourage  
greater selling from the world's largest platinum producer, putting 
additional supplies on a market where there currently appears to be 
no shortage. 
</P>
<P>
	While Russian delays in shipments of palladium have caused some  
market tightness, particularly from automotive and electronics 
manufacturers in Japan, delays in platinum shipments have not 
resulted in shortages. That's because South Africa produces about 
70 percent of the world's platinum supply, while Russia accounts 
for about 75 percent of the world's palladium supply and only about 
20 percent of the platinum supply. 
</P>
<P>
	South African miners also have boosted production recently amid  
good demand from jewelers and automobile companies that use the 
metal for catalytic converters that control pollution emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Platinum for July delivery fell $5.90, or by 1.6 percent, to  
$356.20 a troy ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans fell sharply on the Chicago Board of Trade amid reports  
three American pork producers in North and South Carolina planned 
to import cheaper Brazilian soybean meal as animal feed in coming 
months. Analysts derided the reports as economically unfeasible, 
but the widespread talk shook the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans have been pressured for the past few weeks amid fears a  
bumper Brazilian crop, offered at prices more attractive to 
importers, would take business away from American exporters. And 
with U.S. farmers this spring planting record acreage to soybeans, 
investors fear the outlook will get worse before it gets better. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures fell on a belief that recent rains and mild  
temperatures across Midwestern planting regions had aided early 
planting and increased the likelihood of a bumper crop. The U.S. 
Agriculture Department a day earlier said spring planting was 
slightly ahead of normal. 
</P>
<P>
	May corn fell 2 1/2 cents to $2.16 1/4 a bushel; May soybeans fell 4 1/4  
cents to $4.77 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures moved sharply higher in near-term contract months  
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange amid continued concern about 
supplies going into the summer grilling season. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices jumped for the second day amid expectations the Clinton  
administration soon will begin buying meat and livestock for 
donation to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has pledged 50,000 tons of pork to aid  
cash-strapped Russia in a move that also was meant to help 
producers slash large surpluses that grew over the winter. But the 
purchase now is likely to come at a time when supplies are 
tightest. 
</P>
<P>
	June lean hogs rose 0.80 cent to 54.90 cents a pound; July pork  
bellies rose 1.02 cents to 53.32 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:53:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Garnishees McLain's Pension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The government has garnisheed the pension of  
former Detroit Tigers' pitcher Denny McLain to give to a pension 
fund he was convicted of embezzling from. 
</P>
<P>
	``Denny McLain used his status as a local baseball celebrity to  
illegally obtain money from the Peet Packing Co. retirement income 
plan for his own purposes. It seems only right that McLain's 
pension money from his time as a major league baseball player be 
returned to the victims of his greed,'' U.S. Attorney Saul A. Green 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	McLain and Roger Smigiel, former co-owners of Chesaning's Peet  
Packing Co., were convicted in 1996 of stealing more than $2.5 
million from the company's pension fund and then laundering the 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	McLain and Smigiel bought Peet Packing in January 1994 and  
quickly took the money from the company's $12 million pension fund, 
according to trial testimony. The Chesaning company went bankrupt 
in June 1995, and more than 200 workers lost their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Green said that during the hearing to have McLain's pension  
garnisheed, his office discovered the McLain's wife, Sharon, had 
obtained a divorce by default. Under terms of the settlement, 
essentially all the assets went to Ms. McLain and all the debts to 
McLain, Green said. 
</P>
<P>
	Green said that on March 31, U.S. District Judge Patrick Duggan  
ordered all of McLain's pension be awarded to the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. 6th Circuit Court of Appeals last week upheld  
embezzlement charges against McLain and Smigiel. 
</P>
<P>
	McLain, the major leagues' last 30-game winner, also faces trial  
on federal charges that he took part in a scheme involving 
fraudulent phone cards. Prosecutors allege John A. ``Junior'' 
Gotti, son of the imprisoned boss of the Gambino crime family, also 
took part in the fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	McLain, 54, pitched for the Detroit Tigers from 1963 to 1970,  
winning 31 games as the Tigers won the World Series title in 1968. 
His last major league season was 1972, when he was 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:53:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Banks Reject Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The boards of French banks Societe Generale and  
Paribas voted today to reject a $37 billion hostile takeover bid by 
Banque Nationale de Paris, reiterating their confidence in plans 
for their own merger. 
</P>
<P>
	The dual rejections confirmed the banks' opposition to BNP's  
proposal, leaving the battle's outcome to shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale and Paribas were completing a $17.2 billion  
friendly merger when BNP made its bid for both banks on March 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale issued a statement Tuesday saying the premium  
offered by BNP would ``either be very small, or even negative,'' 
making it unattractive for its shareholders. In addition, it said 
that BNP's plan for a three-way merger would be ``neither as great, 
nor as certain'' as the benefits of a Societe Generale-Paribas 
link-up. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-way merger proposed by BNP would create a $1 trillion,  
world-leading banking group. 
</P>
<P>
	The struggle comes as European banks have been joining forces to  
better compete in a market transformed by the region's new common 
currency, the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale and Paribas have repeatedly pledged to fight  
the takeover attempt by BNP. In particular, Societe Generale said 
the significant overlap between its own and BNP's retail banking 
operations would automatically result in a drop in revenues if the 
three banks were to merge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Richardson To Stay at DePaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Quentin Richardson says the NBA can wait.  
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, Conference USA's player of the year as a freshman,  
is returning to DePaul for at least one more season. 
</P>
<P>
	His teammates are relieved, his coach is pleased, the family  
that was mostly responsible for his decision is at peace, and 
Richardson is now a happy 18-year-old who can still some day make a 
big payday in the pros. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was basically a decision on whether I needed to be able to  
take care of my family,'' a smiling Richardson said at a news 
conference Monday. ``I asked them were we hurting that bad? My 
father, my sister and my step mom all said, `No, they would be 
fine, it could wait.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson's father, Lee, has worked as a motorman with the  
Chicago Transit Authority for 32 years. At age 56 he wasn't ready 
to retire and he wanted his son to work on his education. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have always told him I wanted him to stay in school,'' Lee  
Richardson said. ``He has always told me that he wanted me to 
retire, but I told him `Hey, I'll be all right.' If he left it up 
to me, I'd want him to do all four. All four years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DePaul coach Pat Kennedy and Richardson's sister, Rochelle,  
talked with several NBA general managers and scouts, seeking input 
to gauge where Richardson might be taken if he declared for the 
draft this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson was projected as a middle to late first-round pick  
where he could probably get a salary of about $900,000. Most 
advised staying in school to work on his game and improve his draft 
positioning. That could, in turn, bring a larger contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to give him the chance to sit down and weigh out  
whether he was really prepared to do this. We wanted him to be at 
the top of his game when he does it,'' Rochelle Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a financial hardship. We just wanted to do what is  
best for him, as well as academically and as a business decision. 
It was not a good idea to let him get out and get locked into a 
contract and not get the (playing) time that would be advantageous 
to his future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson's decision will certainly help DePaul as it tries to  
rebuild a national reputation. His return should mean more 
victories, more fans in the stands and more publicity that will aid 
recruiting. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy had a rooting interest in Richardson returning, but made  
sure he obtained all the information and then let his young star 
make the decision. He wasn't told of Richardson's decision until 
right before it was announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's maybe even bigger than when he said he was first coming  
here,'' said Kennedy, who landed Richardson as a recruit right 
after it appeared he was headed to Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, at 6-foot-5, played mostly small forward last season  
and will need to move his game to the perimeter as an off-guard, 
where he would probably play in the NBA. He averaged 18.9 points 
and 10.5 rebounds, using his jumping quickness, long arms and 
uncanny sense of timing to scrap on the boards with bigger players. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, chosen the nation's top freshman last year by the  
U.S. Basketball Writers Association, The Sporting News and 
Basketball News, will acquire an insurance policy against injury 
this season, his sister said. 
</P>
<P>
	The most disappointing aspect of Richardson's first season at  
DePaul was the Blue Demons' failure to make the NCAA tournament. 
Led by fellow freshmen and Chicago prep stars Bobby Simmons and 
Lance Williams, DePaul had to settle for the NIT, where a 
first-round win over Northwestern was the school's first victory in 
the postseason since 1990. The Blue Demons (18-13) were eliminated 
in the second round by eventual NIT champ California. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, who attended the news conference, was glad to have his  
friend and teammate back for another season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was playing with me, telling me he was coming back and then  
telling me he was going. Now we have a chance to have a great 
team,'' Williams said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:21:04 </DATE_TIME>
