<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 43.84 at 9,963.49 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as an earnings  
warning from Gillette put the brakes on Monday's rally. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average  
was down 43.84 at 9,963.49. The index shifted between positive and 
negative territory for much of the session, rising as much as 23 
points in choppy trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed.  
</P>
<P>
	The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was the brightest  
spot in the market for much of the session before giving up most of 
its gains in the last hour of trading. Sun Microsystems rose 10 
9/16 to 140 9/16 after the company told investors of new efforts to 
improve its compatibility with Microsoft Corp.'s Windows NT 
operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Some traders attributed today's market dip to investors hoping  
to lock in profits from Monday's big jump. The Dow rose 174.82 
Monday to close at 10,007.33, a new record that marked the index's 
second finish above 10,000. The Nasdaq and S&AMP;P 500 indexes also set 
new records, sustained by a rally in Internet stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the impetus to sell came from Gillette, which said  
first-quarter profits will probably not meet Wall Street analysts' 
expectations. Gillette fell 7 13/16 today to 49 15/16. The 
company's announcement sobered traders who had bid stocks higher 
Monday on expectations of strong first-quarter results. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,789 down, 1,193 up and 594 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 785.88 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
694.42 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 2.31 to 612.32, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.71 to 763.27. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.21 to 401.08.  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 22:23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Judy, Hubby May Compete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Imagine their arguments at the dining room  
table. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Judy Sheindlin may soon face some competition from her  
husband. George Sheindlin, like his wife a retired New York City 
judge, is talking to producers of ``People's Court'' about taking 
over as arbiter, an executive with the syndicated TV show's 
distributors who asked not to be identified said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Left in the cold could be current ``People's Court'' jurist  
Edward Koch, who appointed both Sheindlins to the bench when he was 
New York City mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Judge Judy'' has dominated the newly hot court show genre. Its  
ratings are up 76 percent over last season, and the no-nonsense 
former judge is a star. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the ratings for ``People's Court'' haven't changed  
over the past year and two new TV judges, Joe Brown and Mills Lane, 
have passed Koch in average audience size, said Marc Berman, a 
television analyst for the media buying firm Seltel. 
</P>
<P>
	The audience for ``Judge Judy'' is two and a half times that of  
``People's Court,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Signing up Mr. Judge Judy could entice curious viewers who  
wonder what sort of man would live with her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's a bad thing, because the show needs some  
attention,'' Berman said. ``I don't think he will beat Judy in the 
long run, but it will bring people in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People's Court'' has discussed having Sheindlin appear in at  
least half of the shows during the TV season that begins in 
September, said the executive from Warner Bros. Television, the 
show's distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Judy sent word through a spokeswoman that she didn't want  
to talk about potentially competing with her husband. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:25:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Record Low Support for Casual Sex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wendy Shalit's new book is raising eyebrows  
for the shocking message it promotes: sexual modesty. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 23-year-old writer, who lashes out against random  
college hookups and sexual encounters, may not be a generational 
anomaly. A comprehensive survey of college freshmen -- taken 
annually since 1966 -- finds record low support for casual sex among 
the 1998 entering class. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not the only area where young adults are taking decidedly  
different turns on issues than previous generations of college 
students. On law and order, abortion and even their goals in life, 
the differences are sometimes wide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their parents are the ones who sort of believed in this  
liberation through promiscuity and experience,'' said Shalit, whose 
book, ``A Return to Modesty: Discovering the Lost Virtue,'' came 
out in January. But some kids today are ``embracing the codes of 
conduct that their own parents rejected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not a surprise to some college students, who agree that young  
adults are looking for a return to religious or more traditional 
moral values after the legacy left by the decadent 1980s and the 
baby boomers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have members who are more conservative than their  
parents,'' says Chris Gillott, chairman of Pennsylvania State 
University's Young Americans for Freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillott says some of his peers go home and ``come out of the  
conservative closet'' to their families, igniting heated 
discussions on topics from Social Security to affirmative action. 
</P>
<P>
	A few examples:  
</P>
<P>
	--Only 40 percent of freshmen agree that it's OK for two people  
who like each other to have sex, even if they have only known each 
other a short while. That's down from 42 percent in 1997, and an 
all-time high of 52 percent in 1987, according to the study by the 
Higher Education Research Institute at the University of 
California, Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	--In 1970, 56 percent of the freshmen surveyed showed strong  
opposition to capital punishment. By 1998, less than a quarter of 
them believed the death penalty should be abolished. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 73 percent of freshmen said there is too much concern for  
criminals -- an almost 50 percent increase since the early 1970s 
when only about half of those surveyed felt that way. 
</P>
<P>
	--Only half of this year's freshmen backed efforts to keep  
abortion legal -- a record low figure after six years on the 
decline. Support for laws protecting abortion peaked in 1990 at 65 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have pro-choice students on our campus who still say they  
would never have an abortion,'' says Ryan Gruber, a senior at the 
University of Wisconsin, Madison, who used to head the school's 
college Republicans. ``Even if they don't want to push their 
message on others, there is less tolerance on a personal level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even views on the grand scheme of things can shift considerably  
in a few generations. Nearly three-quarters of the Class of 2002 
consider being well-off financially among their highest objectives. 
</P>
<P>
	Their parents had different goals when they were freshmen: in  
the late 1960s, more than 80 percent wanted to develop ``a 
meaningful philosophy of life.'' Today, only 40 percent of incoming 
college students find that objective compelling. 
</P>
<P>
	A record low 26 percent of freshmen believe that ``keeping up to  
date with political affairs'' is a very important or essential life 
goal. In 1966, interest in politics was at its height, with a 
record 58 percent of freshmen considering important in their lives. 
</P>
<P>
	But some say these results don't necessarily signify apathy  
among today's students. Instead, activism and civic-mindedness may 
turn up in different forms, like volunteering and community 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``These activities are political in the sense that they are  
trying to change the system we have,'' says Kendra Fox-Davis, a 
1998 UCLA college graduate who now is vice president of the U.S. 
Student Association in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	She added that while students today may not be as likely to  
demonstrate or march in protest like their parents, young adults 
are active on a host of issues from decreasing tuition to raising 
attention to sweatshop labor conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 freshmen norms are based on the responses of 275,811  
students at 469 of the nation's two and four year colleges and 
universities. UCLA's research institute has conducted the survey 
annually since 1966. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
