<DOCNO> APW19990406.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 08:15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Toughens Yugoslavia Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is intensifying its  
campaign to force Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to end his 
assault in Kosovo and permit hundreds of thousands of refugees to 
go home again. But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said today 
that American ground troops would not be sent into the Balkans 
conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe a sustained air campaign can accomplish the  
objectives we have laid out,'' Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if President Clinton was contemplating sending ground  
troops to the Serbian province, Albright said ``the president has 
no plans or intention for ground forces'' as part of a combat force 
in Kosovo. The administration, however, has committed troops for a 
NATO peacekeeping force, if a peace is reached. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is offering Kosovo refugees temporary  
shelter, as it toughens terms for a settlement to the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``A commitment to cease killing and a Kosovo denied its freedom  
and devoid of its people is not acceptable,'' Clinton said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at Brookings Institution, Albright said: ``We are going  
to continue in this intensive air campaign and we will do so until 
all the Serb forces are out'' of Kosovo, hundreds of thousands of 
ethnic Albanian refugees are returned to their homes and Milosevic 
consents to a peace plan that would station a NATO peacekeeping 
force in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration demands that the ethnic Albanians be allowed  
to return goes beyond NATO's original goal of keeping more from 
being forced out of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Today at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, U.S. Army Gen.  
Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, held an 
unannounced meeting with his counterparts from several allied 
countries to discuss the air campaign, Pentagon officials said. The 
officials would not discuss details of the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, strike aircraft from the carrier USS Theodore  
Roosevelt, which arrived in the Adriatic Sea on Monday, began 
flying missions against Yugoslavia, Navy spokesman Cmdr. Brian 
Cullen said. 
</P>
<P>
	In her remarks, Albright said the NATO summit to be held here  
later in the month would prepare the alliance to ``field forces 
designed and equipped for 21 century missions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to have forces, not just among a few countries but  
throughout NATO that are versatile, flexible and mobile,'' she 
said. ``Our benchmark is clear. We must be as good in dealing with 
new threats as we are in dealing with old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strongly hinting that Milosevic would be held accountable for  
war crimes, Albright said Monday: ``There can be no question that 
war crimes and crimes against humanity are being committed in 
Kosovo. Nor can there be doubt that the orders to carry out these 
acts are coming from the top.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With an estimated 800 people an hour fleeing the Serbian  
province, which is part of Yugoslavia, the State Department now 
estimates close to 400,000 more ethnic Albanians have been routed, 
often by Serb troops -- or even Serb neighbors -- since the NATO 
attack began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton called for private donations to Kosovar refugees and  
offered haven for up to 20,000 at the outset. Pentagon officials 
said a refugee camp likely would be set up at the U.S. base at 
Guantanamo, Cuba, which the United States considers U.S. territory 
and has been used to care for Haitian and Cuban refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Other NATO countries are offering to take in up to 80,000 more.  
</P>
<P>
	Moved by Milosevic's campaign from the original goal of simply  
stopping ethnic repression in Kosovo, the Clinton administration 
insists the Yugoslav leader will not be permitted to succeed; that 
the resettlement is only temporary and the refugees will go home 
again. Officials also deny the sustained NATO bombardment was 
having the unintended result of helping Milosevic achieve his goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Appealing directly to Americans to help the victims of  
Milosevic's ``expulsion policy,'' Clinton announced a toll-free 
number, 1-800-USAID-RELIEF, that people can call to donate money to 
nongovernmental relief efforts for ethnic Albanians expelled from 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing all we can, we need more help,'' Clinton said. He  
said $150 million in U.S. government funds has been committed to 
humanitarian relief in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Clinton had some of his harshest words yet for  
Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know we are up against a dictator who has shown time and  
again that he would rather rule over rubble than not rule at all, 
someone who recognizes no limits on his behavior except those 
imposed by others,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Pentagon, spokesman Kenneth Bacon echoed U.S. resistance  
to any hollow peace offering by the Yugoslav leader without a safe 
return of the refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Milosevic may think he's finished'' at that point, Bacon said  
of any unilateral cease-fire by Milosevic. ``We will not be 
finished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Previewing a planned bolstering of NATO's air power, Defense  
Secretary William Cohen said Apache attack helicopters would target 
Serb military and police forces that are now ``open and 
vulnerable'' in Kosovo. The helicopters probably will not be ready 
for action for more than a week, however, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
