<DOCNO> APW19990406.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 04:32:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Rally / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A late surge in telecommunications shares sent  
Japan's main stock index to its highest close in more than eight 
months today. The U.S. dollar retreated against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 144.93  
points, or 0.89 percent, to end the day at 16,479.71 -- its highest 
close since July 21. On Monday, the average finished up 44.59 
points, or 0.27 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.06 yen in late trading, down 0.30 yen from  
late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
121.83 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo stock exchange, shares recovered from morning  
losses triggered by profit-taking, as buying of telecoms issues by 
foreign investors in the last half-hour of trading boosted the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was heavy buying in the information technology sector''  
such as Sony and NTT, said Yoshio Watanabe, a manager at the 
futures section of Toyo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors that the ruling Liberal Democratic Party might be  
considering an $83 billion supplementary budget this fiscal year 
also fueled the last-minute rally. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 15.44 points, or 1.18 percent, to 1,322.61. 
The TOPIX closed up 3.00 points, or 0.23 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 568.10 million shares changed hands on the First  
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 558.74 million on 
Monday. Advancing issues outnumbered declines 725 to 474, while 129 
issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar tumbled as Japanese exporters,  
hedging against future weakness in the dollar, sold the U.S. 
currency to repatriate funds quickly and avoid losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite today's dip, the dollar is expected to be supported by  
the continuing turmoil in Yugoslavia, where NATO forces have 
intensified their bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. currency is often seen as a haven for investors during  
times of international crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.75 yen and 121.82 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.19 yen, down  
from 130.61 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.795 percent from Monday's finish of 1.740 percent, 
driving its price down to 100.04 yen from 100.51 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 12:15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Dept. Hires Consultant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department hired a Minneapolis law  
firm Tuesday as a consultant for its impending lawsuit against the 
tobacco industry. The firm helped Minnesota reach a $6.6 billion 
settlement with the industry last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The firm of Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi agreed to advise and  
assist Justice Department lawyers through June 30 at the 
substantially reduced rate of $75 per hour plus travel costs and 
expenses, according to Acting Assistant Attorney General David W. 
Ogden, who heads the department's tobacco litigation task force. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton announced in this year's State of the Union  
speech that the government had decided to sue the industry to 
recover money paid by federal health-insurance programs for 
treatment of tobacco-related illnesses. The Justice Department has 
requested $20 million from Congress in the fiscal year beginning 
next Oct. 1 to pay for 40 government lawyers to work on the case 
and for $5 million for expert witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract with the Minneapolis law firm runs through June 30  
and sets a maximum payment of $81,760 through that date. The 
government said it could be extended if both parties agree. 
</P>
<P>
	The department emphasized that contract specifies only  
consulting services and does not contemplate any contingent fee 
payment to the law firm based on potential payments the industry 
might either agree or be ordered to make. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least for the foreseeable future, the litigation team  
itself will consist exclusively of Justice Department attorneys,'' 
Ogden said. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for the law firm was not immediately able to say  
how many lawyers the firm intends to devote to advising the 
government and what the firm's normal hourly rate for such business 
would be. Large firms often charge business clients several hundred 
dollars an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi represented the state of  
Minnesota and Blue Cross-Blue Shield of Minnesota in their lawsuit 
against the tobacco industry. As a result of the lawsuit and near 
the end of the trial, the tobacco industry agreed May 8, 1998, to 
pay $6.6 billion to Minnesota's citizens and to submit to cigarette 
marketing and advertising curbs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi is widely recognized for its  
success in the Minnesota litigation against the tobacco industry 
and for its expertise in this area of litigation,'' Ogden said. 
``They have devoted thousands of hours to uncovering and learning 
the facts relating to tobacco litigation. Their extraordinary 
experience in this area will be very valuable to the department's 
tobacco litigation team as we prepare a plan to recover federal 
health care expenditures from the tobacco industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Department officials said they were particularly interested in  
tapping the law firm's knowledge of the 200,000 pages of industry 
documents that were disclosed during the discovery process of the 
Minnesota lawsuit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 08:15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Toughens Yugoslavia Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
