<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UN Peace Conference Set for May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- With the war-ridden century nearing an  
end, more than 1,000 international organizations, a dozen 
governments and the U.N. General Assembly are backing a global 
conference in May to create a more peaceful 21st century. 
</P>
<P>
	Over 3,000 participants are expected at the meeting in the  
Netherlands which will be addressed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi 
Annan, Queen Noor of Jordan, South Africa's first lady Graca Machel 
and four Nobel Peace Prize winners, organizers said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time, representatives of peace, women's,  
environmental, disarmament and human rights movements will work 
with governments toward a common goal: achieving a culture of peace 
for the 21st century,'' said U.S. peace activist Cora Weiss. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference, from May 11-15, is called The Hague Appeal for  
Peace and will be held at the site of the first Hague appeal 
convened by the czar of Russia 100 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hague Appeal was supposed to be the last U.N. world  
conference of the 20th century -- following those on the 
environment, human rights, social development, population and 
women, said Bill Pace, the appeal's secretary-general. But by the 
mid-1990s, he said, it was clear that conference fatigue coupled 
with an international financial crisis was setting in. 
</P>
<P>
	So a group of international organizations working on a global  
peace initiative decided to organize a conference, with the hope 
that governments and the United Nations would support it, Pace 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference will look at implementation of the 1997 land-mine  
treaty, progress of the International Criminal Court, new proposals 
to peacefully resolve conflicts, the elimination of child soldiers 
and promotion of an international curriculum for schools based on 
the study of peace -- not war, Pace said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
