<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MLS Bans Enhancement Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Major League Soccer banned anabolic steroids and  
human growth hormone today and expects to begin testing players by 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Doug Logan said the league added six categories to  
its list of banned substances, including erythropoietin (EPO), an 
endurance-boosting hormone that increases the blood's ability to 
carry oxygen. 
</P>
<P>
	EPO is a favorite of some cyclists and was at the center of the  
Tour de France drug scandal last year. 
</P>
<P>
	However, scientifically reliable tests have not been perfected  
for some substances, such as EPO, but are expected to be available 
by next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because we cannot test for them, doesn't mean shouldn't  
be making statement that these substances should be banned,'' Logan 
said during a conference call. ``They violate the ethics of 
competitive sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MLS already tests every league and team employee, including  
players, once a year by urinalysis for 10 kinds of illegal drugs, 
including cocaine, marijuana, amphetamines and barbiturates. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's policy change added steroids, stimulants (other than  
caffeine or medications approved by the league), EPO, human growth 
hormone, chorionic gonadotrophin (another human growth hormone), 
and diuretics (used to mask drugs). 
</P>
<P>
	MLS operations manager William Ordower said the 3-year-old  
league has been considering adding such substances for a few years. 
However, the league decided to go forward after a recommendation of 
Dr. Ian Macdonald, who also advises the International Olympic 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making the announcement now to give our players a full  
season to change their habits if any did rely on it,'' Ordower 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 16:12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Can Rent Kennedy Summer Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HYANNIS PORT, Mass. (AP) -- For $100,000, Democratic Party donors  
will be able to spend a Camelot weekend at the storied Kennedy 
family compound in Hyannis Port where Jack, Bobby and Teddy used to 
play touch football. 
</P>
<P>
	For decades, Democrats have happily given money to visit Kennedy  
homes and help out the latest Kennedy running for office. 
</P>
<P>
	But the $100,000-a-head retreat on Cape Cod, scheduled for  
September, marks the first time the home will be used for a major, 
national campaign contribution drive. Guests will have to find a 
hotel room somewhere down the road to sleep in, however. 
</P>
<P>
	It's part of a fund-raising drive led by Rep. Patrick Kennedy,  
D-R.I., to retake the House. Kennedy, 31, the youngest son of Sen. 
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., is head of the Democratic Congressional 
Campaign Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sort of irresistible, if you can afford it, to get a peek  
into how the royal family lives and plays,'' said Dan Payne, a 
Boston political consultant. ``For some people, an affiliation with 
the Kennedys is sort of a life goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Kennedy was appointed to head the Democratic  
Congressional Campaign Committee in the fall after throwing a 
clambake at the Hyannis Port compound. The event was believed to 
have raised at least $250,000. 
</P>
<P>
	During this election cycle, the committee hopes to raise $50  
million by offering retreats in posh places to wealthy donors and 
dinners with top Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics said the idea demonstrates the need to change the  
nation's campaign finance system. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we have a system that's democracy for rent, I certainly  
can't be surprised when I see the Hyannis Port compound for rent, 
too,'' said Meredith McGehee, spokeswoman for the clean-government 
organization Common Cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Erik Smith, a spokesman for the Democratic Congressional  
Committee, said Democrats want to reform campaign finance laws but 
cannot do so without a majority in Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hardaway Scoring More in New Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Penny Hardaway resisted the temptation to tell everybody he was  
right all along. There was nothing wrong with his offensive game 
that a change in position wouldn't solve. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-time All-Star, sensitive to criticism that he hasn't  
been scoring enough, offers the Orlando Magic's Eastern 
Conference-leading record as evidence he's been doing a lot of good 
things this season. 
</P>
<P>
	But with leading scorer Nick Anderson sidelined by a hamstring  
injury the past week, Hardaway was averaging 26 points per game -- 
10 above his season average -- going into Tuesday night's game 
against the Knicks in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason, he and coach Chuck Daly agreed, is that with  
Anderson out the team needs Hardaway to fill a role that he's 
probably been better suited for all along. 
</P>
<P>
	A point guard for most of his NBA career, Hardaway's scoring  
picks up dramatically when he's not expected to set up the offense 
and create opportunities for teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's played his best basketball since I've been here,'' Daly  
said after Hardaway keyed a late run Monday night that carried the 
Magic to a 106-99 victory over the Boston Celtics. ``He plays 
better off the ball. He's happier there, and that's what he wants 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Hardaway insists he doesn't have a problem playing the  
point, he wants people to understand that his statistics will 
suffer. If it's gaudy numbers they want, then give him the ball 
coming off screens and in other situations where he can get more 
open shots. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a role he was prepared to accept before injuries limited  
him to 19 games last season. He returned to point guard this year 
because of the re-emergence of Anderson, who's been the Magic's 
most consistent scorer since February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the point, I tried to put my ego to the side and go out  
there and get everybody involved and get a victory. But nobody sees 
it that way,'' Hardaway said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want me to go out and score 30, score 25, like they've  
seen me in the past. But I'm not the same, and we don't have the 
same team. We have more guys who can really score. If you get 
everybody involved, you win almost every game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway's primary responsibility on offense for three seasons  
was to get the ball to Shaquille O'Neal. When Shaq left for the Los 
Angeles Lakers in 1996, the Magic became more dependent on their 
playmaker's scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	But injuries have slowed the two-time all-NBA selection much of  
the past two seasons and, at times, he's seemed reluctant to assert 
himself on offense. Even his teammates would like to see Hardaway 
be more aggressive. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to understand this is an unselfish guy,'' said  
Darrell Armstrong, who has been starting as point guard with 
Anderson injured. ``When Shaq was here, he gave shots up. He didn't 
really care about posting up. All he cared about was winning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just in his nature to be unselfish. When he doesn't  
score, he does a lot of things to help this team. He rebounds, he 
gets assists, plays defense. He does it all. It's not all about 
scoring. You can score a lot of points and play a bad game 
sometimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway couldn't have said it better himself.  
</P>
<P>
	So, what happens when Anderson returns? Does Hardaway make back  
to the point? Or how about Anderson moving to small forward? 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't speak for the coach,'' said Hardaway.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not our job,'' he said. ``It's the coaches job. And  
whatever he says, that's the way it's going to be.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
