<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Bodies Found in Missouri Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Police today arrested a man suspected of  
killing at least one of the five men whose decomposing bodies were 
found in his rented house. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies, which all appeared to be male, had been in the house  
for some time, said police Capt. Jerry Gallagher. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're all decomposed pretty badly,'' Gallagher said Monday.  
``It's not pretty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they did not know when the killings occurred and  
would not say how the victims died. Gallagher said the air 
conditioning was running when police arrived Monday, making it 
harder to determine how long the bodies had been decomposing. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Beach, 56, was arrested this morning at a hotel parking lot  
in the city's Westport district, several blocks away from the 
house. 
</P>
<P>
	Beach was charged with first-degree murder in the death of  
Kenneth Gulley, 45, of Independence. Arraignment was likely on 
Wednesday, police spokesman Russ Dykstra said. Police wouldn't 
comment on a motive. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Gulley, police identified two other victims as  
Mark Nelson, 28, of Kansas City, and Christopher Conrad, 27, of 
Overland Park, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were seeking relatives of a fourth victim to confirm his  
identity. Dykstra said identification of the last body was hampered 
by its decomposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the bodies were found on the main floor and two in the  
basement of the one-story home. 
</P>
<P>
	One neighbor said the house had been occupied for about 14 years  
by two men, a father and stepson, both limousine drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Rich, 25, said he heard gunshots ``sometime last week''  
from his house across the street and had not seen anyone at the 
home for the past few days. He didn't report the shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a real laid-back, nice neighborhood. I'm not sure if I  
want to stay here now,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
