<DOCNO> APW19990406.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:42:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Refugee Issues Not New to Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As President Clinton steps up the U.S.  
response to the humanitarian crisis in Kosovo, his own history with 
the touchy issue of political refugees is likely to be a factor in 
his decision making. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has blamed his re-election loss in the 1980 Arkansas  
governor's race in part on riots among Cuban exiles who ended up at 
a federal facility in Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	As president in 1994, he had 14,000 Haitian refugees housed at  
the U.S. military base in Guantanamo Bay, Cuba -- a location that 
limited domestic concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	But he caused consternation in Florida that same year by his  
handling of a mass exodus of Cuban refugees touched off by Cuba's 
Fidel Castro. 
</P>
<P>
	Castro, like Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is doing now  
by forcibly removing ethnic Albanians from Kosovo province, had 
found a way to make citizens he didn't like someone else's problem 
-- particularly a U.S. president. 
</P>
<P>
	The 20,000 Kosovo refugees that the United States has agreed to  
shelter temporarily likely will be sent to Guantanamo too, although 
Clinton administration officials delayed a final decision Monday 
while they sought assurances that European countries were fully 
engaged in the relief effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials still were grappling with the logistics  
of transporting and sheltering 20,000 people half a world away on 
Monday. While they have been quick to lend a hand to people struck 
by natural disasters -- soldiers and millions in aid were dispatched 
to Central America after Hurricane Mitch struck last year -- the 
current crisis poses unique challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is different because you don't know what the end date  
is,'' said a White House official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity. ``But you want to make sure people are surviving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were concerns now, as in times past, about how to  
adequately provide for the refugees while they are in the care of 
the United States. But concern for the plight of the Kosovar 
Albanians was outweighing other considerations. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials decided to accept the refugees to alleviate the  
bottleneck of people flowing from Kosovo to Albania, Macedonia and 
the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro -- an estimated 400,000 people, 
mostly ethnic Albanians -- since the U.S.-led NATO bombing of 
Yugoslavia began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said U.S. policymakers  
expected that the Kosovo refugees eventually would be repatriated. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe these refugees want to return to their homes,''  
Rubin said. ``This is a temporary arrangement designed to deal with 
an emergency problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government sent thousands of Cuban refugees to Fort  
Chaffee, Ark., in 1980 in the wake of the Mariel boatlift. Clinton 
got assurances from the Carter administration that no more would be 
sent after a riot left dozens injured, but a month later the 
administration sent refugees harbored in four other states on to 
Fort Chaffee. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's opponent, Republican Frank White, used public  
sentiment over the riots against Clinton, accusing him of failing 
to be tough enough with Carter to move the refugees. Clinton told 
USA Today in 1987 that the incident ``did play some role'' in his 
defeat. He subsequently regained the governors' office. 
</P>
<P>
	When thousands of Haitians began fleeing the island in rickety  
boats in 1994, Clinton ordered the Coast Guard to transport them to 
the Marine facility at Guantanamo until political stability was 
restored in Haiti. While many Haitians ultimately were allowed to 
come to the mainland, thousands had to be returned to Haiti 
forcibly. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton on Monday appealed directly to the American public for  
cash donations to the relief effort and announced ``Operation 
Sustain Hope,'' an interagency initiative for the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton announced a toll-free 1-800 telephone number that people  
can call to donate money for ethnic Albanians expelled from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The president asked for donations to nongovernmental groups in  
the area trying to stanch the humanitarian crisis. He directed 
potential donors to a toll-free number: 1-800-USAID-RELIEF. 
Officials said more lines would be installed in the coming days to 
cope with a flood of calls that jammed circuits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
