<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 12:05:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belle Hits Ringing Blast for O's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- He's much larger than life, standing far above  
the expressway traffic with a huge black bat in his hands and a 
grin across his face. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why is Albert smiling?'' the billboard reads. ``Because it's  
364 to left center.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albert Belle, the Baltimore Orioles' poster boy for the 1999  
season, didn't plant his first homer in those beckoning Camden 
Yards seats in left center. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Belle marked his first formal day with the Orioles by  
launching an opposite-field drive over the 25-foot scoreboard in 
right field. 
</P>
<P>
	It was hardly the most distant shot of his career, but the home  
run was immense in importance. The three-run homer, which gave the 
Orioles the lead for good Monday in a 10-7 victory over Tampa Bay, 
set off a celebration by the sellout crowd that caused the 
ordinarily sullen slugger to take an impromptu curtain call. 
</P>
<P>
	He also managed to produce a genuine smile or two.  
</P>
<P>
	That's exactly what the Orioles were hoping for when they signed  
Belle to a five-year, $65 million contract in December. Team 
officials knew the risk of thrusting him into a town that likes its 
heroes wholesome (i.e. Johnny Unitas and Cal Ripken), but the 
Orioles also figured the fans would love the guy if he hit the 
cover off the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	At least for one day, it was smiles all around.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody on the team benefits with Albert in the lineup,''  
said Brady Anderson, who also homered. ``When you have a proven RBI 
and home run hitter at cleanup, it affects everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three players in front of Belle -- Anderson, Mike Bordick and  
Will Clark -- all did their part by getting on base. Belle then 
showed why he's had at least 100 RBIs in each of the last seven 
seasons, going deep with two runners on and later adding an RBI 
single. 
</P>
<P>
	With Belle leading the way, the Orioles proved they could win  
when Mike Mussina has an off day and when their bullpen sputters. 
Baltimore was resilient without Cal Ripken and relentless against 
everyone the Devil Rays shoved onto the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, baseball's Iron Man, was lifted for a pinch hitter in  
the third inning because of a stiff lower back. If he hadn't 
willingly ended his record consecutive games streak at 2,632 last 
year, the injury would have been front-page news. 
</P>
<P>
	It's still worth noting, however, because he was treated in a  
hospital Monday and might have to go on the disabled list for the 
first time in his 18-year career. The third baseman is questionable 
for Wednesday night against the Devil Rays at Camden Yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's day to day,'' Orioles spokesman John Maroon said Tuesday.  
``Our training staff will monitor the situation and base their 
decision on how he feels today and tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken was plagued by lower back pain during the 1997 season and  
once was in such agony he considered ending his streak by sitting 
out a game in July. But his back loosened up during warmups and he 
finished the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken's replacement Monday, Willis Otanez, went 0-for-3. But  
the Orioles produced 13 hits and won on a day when the ace of the 
staff gave up four runs in five innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the whole season is done, you look back and say there are  
a couple I should have won and I didn't and there are a couple I 
should have lost and I didn't. This probably was one of the 
latter,'' Mussina said. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson contributed heavily with a 3-for-4 performance. After  
opening last season in a 4-for-63 funk, he's now one hit from 
matching his total through May 11 of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 04:55:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Tech Assistant Takes Purdue Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) -- Kristy Sims-Curry didn't need much  
convincing to become the women's basketball coach at Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	As an assistant at Louisiana Tech, she saw the Boilermakers  
three times in the past two seasons, including this year's NCAA 
women's semifinals. The day after Purdue beat the Lady Techsters, 
and the day before the Boilermakers beat Duke for the championship, 
Sims-Curry was offered the job being vacated by Carolyn Peck. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure it's a little bit scary,'' the new coach said Monday.  
``It's my first head coaching job. But I tell you what, the 
position we were in at Louisiana Tech, each and every year was a 
little scary at times, because we expected to be the best and 
expected to be at the top. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where I expect to be here,'' she said at her first news  
conference at Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	Peck announced even before last season began that she would  
become the coach and general manager of the WNBA's new Orlando 
franchise. Under their lame-duck coach, the Boilermakers were 
ranked No. 1 in the nation, won their final 32 games and finished 
34-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Sims-Curry, 32, accepted the offer ``because they expect to be  
among the best, and I couldn't have left Louisiana Tech for anyone 
that didn't want to be the best,'' she said. ``So it's a little bit 
scary, but we'll deal with it and we'll go forward. Hey, you work 
hard and good things happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A former high school coach in Louisiana, Sims-Curry also was an  
assistant at Texas A&AMP;M, Tulane and Stephen F. Austin. Her husband, 
Kelly Curry, also an assistant coach with the Lady Techsters, will 
join her staff as a Boilermakers assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really am proud and very honored to have the opportunity to  
be the new coach at Purdue,'' Sims-Curry said. ``As an assistant, 
we all dream and work for an opportunity like this. ... The work 
ethic and commitment this program stands for, we will work each and 
every day to continue that. I could not be any more excited and 
thrilled to death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the big changes, however, will be the departure of the  
senior backcourt of Stephanie White-McCarty, a first-team 
All-American, and Ukari Figgs, this year's Final Four most valuable 
player. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having seen this team and knowing quite a bit about them ... I  
feel like I do have a little bit of feel for our personnel and 
where we are and where we want to be,'' Sims-Curry said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that you've got to begin with your defensive effort.  
A lot of times, your philosophy will come with what type of 
personnel you have. I don't see that much change in the system. 
Certainly, it's worked well, and we'll continue to build on that 
and add a few things and go from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sims-Curry is the fourth Purdue coach in five seasons. Lin Dunn  
was fired in 1996; Nell Fortner, another Louisiana Tech assistant 
who replaced Dunn, left after one season to lead the U.S. Women's 
National Team; and Peck was the coach for two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue athletic director Morgan Burke called Sims-Curry ``a  
person who will nurture and build on the strengths in our program. 
... We have some very talented returning players, but clearly we're 
going to lose two All-Americans, and we're mindful we have our work 
cut out for us to continue to move this program forward. We think 
the person who can do that is Kristy Sims-Curry.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
