</P>
<P>
	Economic Indicators Rise Again  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While the numbers weren't as strong as the past  
two years, a key indicator of future economic growth suggests the 
country will continue to thrive at least through the summer. The 
Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose for the fifth-straight 
month in February, the Conference Board reported today. Rising 
consumer expectations and a drop in first-time claims for jobless 
benefits were among factors pushing the index up 0.2 percent in 
February, in line with economists' expectations. The index is 
designed to forecast economic activity six to nine months in 
advance. 

</P>
<P>
	Program Calculates Mutual Fund Fees  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new computer program developed by federal  
regulators allows mutual fund investors to calculate the costs of 
funds and compare different funds. Many investors don't realize, 
for example, that a 1 percent annual fee will reduce the final 
account balance in a mutual fund by 18 percent on an investment 
held for 20 years. The Securities and Exchange Commission has been 
pushing the mutual fund industry for improved disclosure of fund 
fees and investment risks. The computer program unveiled today, 
called the mutual fund cost calculator, ``takes some of the mystery 
out of mutual funds by enabling investors to evaluate and compare 
costs,'' SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt said. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Sets March Sales Record  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. took advantage of Americans' love  
affair with trucks to post its best March ever. The No. 2 automaker 
reported today that its U.S. sales were up 14 percent in March over 
the same month a year ago, based on the daily sales rate. Ford 
broke a long list of company records, led by its strongest monthly 
sales of light trucks ever. March sales of F-series pickups, the 
nation's top-selling vehicle for 17 years, were the highest for any 
car or truck in any month since June 1978. Ford's car sales, 
excluding its Jaguar unit, were up nearly 6 percent while its light 
truck sales increased 19 percent to set a record for any month. SUV 
sales were up 11 percent while total pickup sales were up 28 
percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Air Bags Do Well in Test  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Side air bags on Ford Motor Co.'s 1999 models  
greatly reduce the likelihood of serious head injury to the driver 
in crash tests, the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety said 
today. The institute, which is financed by insurers, crashed two 
1999 model Lincoln Town Cars by hurtling them sideways into a pole 
that smashed into the driver's door. Side air bags are standard 
equipment on the 1999 Lincoln Continental and Town Car. Ford has 
started offering them with head protection as options in front 
seats of some of its less expensive vehicles: 1999 Ford Explorer 
and Mercury Mountaineer sport utility vehicles, Ford Windstar 
minivans and the Jaguar XJ8 and X200. Side air bags with head 
protection also are on BMWs, Saabs, Volvos and some Mercedes 
models. 

</P>
<P>
	Auto Workers Charged in Drug Sting  
</P>
<P>
	WARREN, Mich. (AP) -- Drug charges have been brought against 11  
DaimlerChrysler AG workers following a 16-month undercover 
investigation at their auto plant. A forklift operator, William 
Sturkin, was charged with possession with intent to deliver cocaine 
and heroin at the Dodge City truck assembly plant, where he has 
worked for more than 20 years. Police arrested 10 others last week 
on lesser charges. Authorities launched the probe in late 1997 when 
workers complained to management about drug dealing at the plant. 

</P>
<P>
	Hope Seen in Japan's Auto Market  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO -- Automakers have been hit harder by Japan's recession  
than just about any other industry. Domestic sales have fallen 23 
consecutive months, plunging by about 20 percent. But analysts see 
demand roaring back once the recession eases up. And, while dealers 
fight for survival on the front lines, Japanese and foreign 
automakers are jockeying for position to cash in when the market 
finally comes around. American carmakers, which have always 
struggled in Japan, are investing in their sales networks, a major 
weakness, hoping to make significant inroads before the locals can 
turn the corner. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Hire Law Firm for Tobacco Suit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department hired a Minneapolis law  
firm today as a consultant for its impending lawsuit against the 
tobacco industry. The firm helped Minnesota reach a $6.6 billion 
settlement with the industry last year. Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; 
Ciresi agreed to advise and assist Justice Department lawyers 
through June 30 at the substantially reduced rate of $75 per hour 
plus travel costs and expenses, the department said. President 
Clinton has said the government would sue the industry to recover 
money paid by federal health-insurance programs for treatment of 
tobacco-related illnesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Prodigy Offers New Spanish Service  
</P>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Prodigy Communications Corp. will  
offer a Spanish-language Internet access service to U.S. customers, 
the company announced today. The service offers the same features 
available through Prodigy Internet, but also provides both customer 
service and technical support for Spanish-speaking customers. The 
service will be supported with Spanish-language advertising, news 
and links to other Hispanic Web sites and services. Visitors can 
also search the Internet with Spanish language search engines. 

</P>
