<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Mixed at Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks turned mixed Wednesday morning amid  
concerns over the recent fast pace of market gains. The dollar 
slipped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average gained 20.10 points, or 0.12 percent,  
to 16,499.81 at the end of the morning session, marking its highest 
intraday level so far this year. On Tuesday, the average closed up 
144.93 points, or 0.89 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.81 yen at late morning, down 0.25 yen from  
late Tuesday in Tokyo but above its level of 120.62 yen in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices started slightly lower on  
profit-taking as market players worried that Japan's still weak 
economic fundamentals did not warrant the Nikkei's rise of 4 
percent since the end of last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``With no clear signs of the economy getting better, why should  
it go higher?'' asked Louis Tseng, managing director at LHT 
Investment Management. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts also said investors may have been exercising caution  
ahead of the settlement of monthly options contracts Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 5.44 points, or 0.41 percent, to 1,317.17. 
The TOPIX closed up 15.44 points, or 1.18 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 43.84  
points, or 0.4 percent, to 9,963.49 at Tuesday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar's weakness against the yen came  
after the euro strengthened against the U.S. currency as Yugoslavia 
announced a unilateral cease-fire in its battle against Kosovo 
rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav government called the cease-fire a ``gesture of  
goodwill'' in advance of Sunday's Orthodox Easter holiday. The 
action, however, was rejected by Western leaders, who said the NATO 
bombings of Yugoslavia would continue. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, often regarded as a safe haven in times of  
international unrest, had been rising against the euro since the 
bombings began on March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo trading, bought $1.0823, up from its late Tuesday rate  
in Tokyo of $1.0715. The euro also bought 130.82 yen, up from 
130.19 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.805  
percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.795 percent, driving its price 
down to 99.95 yen from 100.04 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
