<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Rejects Yugoslav Truce Offer  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Calling it a sham, Western leaders  
rejected Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's proposed Orthodox 
Easter cease-fire against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Neither the 
cease-fire declaration nor statements from Yugoslav officials said 
anything about holding fire against NATO forces, which mounted 
their most intensive strikes of the two-week-old air campaign and 
promised heavier firepower to come. The allies demand that 
Milosevic withdraw military and paramilitary troops from Kosovo and 
accept an international military force to police a settlement that 
grants autonomy to the Serb province. A Kosovo rebel spokesman also 
rejected the cease-fire. 

</P>
<P>
	US To House Kosovo Refugees in Cuba  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration announced the  
United States would take in up to 20,000 ethnic Albanian refugees 
from Kosovo and house them temporarily at the U.S. naval base at 
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba. Brian Atwood, administrator of the U.S. 
Agency for International Development, said he expected the first 
refugees to be flown to Guantanamo by the week's end. The Kosovar 
Albanians will be given ``temporary protective status'' for up to 
18 months, he said, adding that he expected conditions in Kosovo 
would allow them to return to their homeland before then. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Premier Begins U.S. Visit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite tense relations between Beijing and  
Washington, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji today opened a nine-day U.S. 
visit in Los Angeles. China has called for a halt to the NATO 
airstrikes in Yugoslavia and it resents a U.S. initiative to 
provide a missile defense shield for Japan and Taiwan. In the 
United States, criticism of China's human rights record is 
widespread and there is concern over alleged nuclear espionage. 
Even so, Zhu still hopes to close a deal to allow Beijing to join 
the World Trade Organization when he meets with President Clinton 
on Thursday. Zhu will also visit Denver, Chicago, New York and 
Boston. 

</P>
<P>
	Side Air Bags Do Well in Test  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Side air bags on Ford Motor Co.'s 1999 models  
greatly reduce the likelihood of serious head injury to the driver 
in crash tests, a safety research institute said. The Insurance 
Institute for Highway Safety crashed a 1999 Lincoln Town Car, 
hurtling it sideways into an upright pole that smashed into the 
driver's side door. The side air bag cushioned the dummy's head 
from the force of the crash, making it ``survivable despite the 
(crash's) severity,'' said institute president Brian O'Neill. 

</P>
<P>
	Young Face Greater Smoking Perils  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new study finds the younger a person starts  
smoking, the more damage is done. The research, which appears in 
tomorrow's Journal of the National Cancer Institute, shows that 
smoking in the teen-age years causes permanent genetic changes in 
the lungs and forever increases the risk of lung cancer. About 3 
million teen-agers now smoke, according to government estimates. 

</P>
<P>
	Division Over Internet Learning  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hundreds of universities are launching courses  
or degree programs online, but a pair of new reports question 
whether a seat in front of a computer is as good as a seat in a 
college classroom. The College Board warns that Internet courses 
could hinder the progress of poor and minority students who arrive 
at college with less exposure to computers than white or 
more-affluent students. And a report by the Institute for Higher 
Education Policy says colleges still lack enough knowledge about 
Internet-based learning to justify its rapid growth. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 43.84 at 9,963.49  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An earnings warning from Gillette Corp. sent  
Wall Street stock prices lower today. The Dow industrials fell 
43.84 to close at 9,963.49. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 
1,789-1,193. The Nasdaq was 3.11 higher at 2,563.17, a new record. 

</P>
<P>
	Kissinger, Ueberroth on IOC Panel  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and  
former Los Angeles Olympics chief Peter Ueberroth have been picked 
for a panel to restructure the IOC in the wake of the Salt Lake 
bribery scandal, sources said today. The IOC 2000 commission will 
make recommendations on selection of Olympic host cities, election 
of IOC members, the structure of the IOC and executive board and 
further roles for Olympic athletes. 

</P>
<P>
	Baseball Salaries Up 19 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The biggest escalation in seven years pushed  
baseball's average salary above $1.7 million on opening day, 
according to a study by The Associated Press. Baltimore outfielder 
Albert Belle was the highest-paid player for the third straight 
season, earning $11,949,794. The New York Yankees opened with 
baseball's highest payroll ever, $85.1 million -- an average of 
$3.04 million per player. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  

</P>
