<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslav Leader Declares Cease-Fire  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan  
Milosevic declared a unilateral cease-fire Tuesday in his campaign 
to crush rebels in Kosovo, saying he wanted to honor the Orthodox 
Easter holiday this weekend. Western leaders called the move a sham 
and pledged to press ahead with airstrikes. Moments after the 
cease-fire took effect at 8 p.m. (2 p.m. EDT), air-raid sirens 
wailed in Belgrade, heralding new NATO attacks. President Clinton 
and NATO insisted that half-measures would not end the NATO air 
campaign that began March 24, and British Prime Minister Tony 
Blair's office said Milosevic's announced truce ``doesn't go nearly 
far enough.'' 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Troops in Bosnia Fired On  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- A NATO helicopter flying on  
a routine mission apparently came under fire over Bosnian Serb 
territory, NATO officials said Tuesday, the latest in a recent 
series of attacks on alliance-led forces in Bosnia. The crew of a 
Black Hawk helicopter observed a flash on the ground 10 miles 
southwest of the northern Bosnian city of Doboj on Monday. Within 
seconds they saw an object fly in front of them, forcing them to 
take ``evasive action.'' The helicopter landed safely. NATO-led 
forces are investigating the incident and received assurances from 
the Bosnian Serb Army and local police that they will cooperate. 

</P>
<P>
	Missouri Votes on Concealed Guns  
</P>
<P>
	JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Missouri voters decided Tuesday in a  
close contest whether to lift a concealed-weapons ban dating to the 
days of Jesse James. With 67 percent of the vote counted, a slight 
majority of voters favored Proposition B, which would lift the ban. 
The secretary of state's office said the partial tally had 418,634 
voting for the proposition and 413,296 voting against. The vote 
marked the first time a state has put the question of concealed 
weapons to the voters. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Premier Begins U.S. Visit  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji began a visit to  
the United States Tuesday by acknowledging American concerns about 
human rights violations in China. The premier, speaking through a 
translator, said Gov. Gray Davis raised the issue of human rights 
during a meeting but they did not have time for adequate 
discussion. ``It would have taken all morning,'' Zhu said. Zhu's 
arrival was met with small but vocal demonstrations by about 50 
people advocating a free Tibet and an independent Taiwan. His trip 
marked the first to the United States by a Chinese premier in 15 
years. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Awards $26.5M to Smoker  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A judge slashed a tobacco lawsuit award in  
half, reducing from $51.5 million to $26.5 million the amount 
awarded to a former three-pack-a-day smoker with lung cancer. Judge 
John Munter said the punitive award in Patricia Henley's case was 
excessive. The judge said an award of $25 million is enough to 
punish Philip Morris for misleading the public about the dangers of 
smoking and for marketing cigarettes to teen-agers. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawsuit Claims MCI Discriminates  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- MCI WorldCom Inc. discriminates against  
customers by preventing them from making international calls from 
predominantly ethnic minority neighborhoods designated as ``high 
fraud'' areas, according to a lawsuit. ``This is redlining at its 
worst,'' said co-counsel Raymond Boucher, who filed the lawsuit 
Tuesday in Los Angeles Superior Court on behalf of Darren Haylock. 
Haylock attempted to make a call last week from South Central Los 
Angeles to Belize but MCI refused to let the call go through, the 
lawsuit states. An operator told Haylock that South Central was 
considered a ``high fraud'' area and blocked the call. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Mixed at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks turned mixed Wednesday morning amid  
concerns over the recent fast pace of market gains. The Nikkei 
gained 20.10 points to 16,499.81 at the end of the morning session, 
marking its highest intraday level so far this year. In New York on 
Tuesday, the Dow industrials fell 43.84 to close at 9,963.49. 

</P>
<P>
	Sabres Edge Islanders 4-3  
</P>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP)-- Jason Woolley had a goal and an assist to  
lead Buffalo to a 4-3 victory over the New York Islanders on 
Tuesday night, moving the Sabres to within one point of fifth place 
in the Eastern Conference playoff race. 

</P>
<P>
	Williams Loses in Bausch &AMP; Lomb  
</P>
<P>
	AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. (AP) -- Third-seeded Venus Williams had a  
10-match winning streak snapped Tuesday in the second round of the 
Bausch &AMP; Lomb Championships. It was a 6-4, 7-6 (8-6) loss to Sonya 
Jeyaseelan, a 140th-ranked qualifier -- the lowest-ranked player 
Williams has lost to since turning pro 4 1/2 years ago. The upset also 
halted the momentum the Williams family picked up two weeks ago, 
when Venus beat Serena in the all-sister final of The Lipton 
Championships. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  


