<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Sentenced in Valentine Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	XENIA, Ohio (AP) -- A man who killed a couple at a Valentine's  
Day dance was sentenced Tuesday to the death penalty he begged for 
at his trial. 
</P>
<P>
	James Taylor, who served as his own lawyer, was sentenced by  
Judge Thomas Rose, who accepted the jury's recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor, 68, was convicted of killing Ronald Rihm, 51, and Rihm's  
wife, Carolyn, 57, in 1998. Prosecutors said Taylor had gone to the 
dance to kill his wife, who had left him and moved in with the 
Rihms. She was not shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor said that he intended to kill himself in front of his  
wife but that his gun went off accidentally when Rihm bumped his 
arm. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Rihms were his friends, and he asked for the death  
penalty, saying he felt sorry for them. 
</P>
<P>
	But at Tuesday's sentencing, Taylor proclaimed his innocence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
