<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Company Urges Employees to Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A small New Jersey financial services  
company has come up with a unique way to inspire company spirit and 
improve employee fitness -- corporate marathoning. 
</P>
<P>
	J.G. Wentworth, which has offices in Philadelphia and Fort Lee,  
N.J., offered any employee who finished a four-month training 
program an all-expenses-paid trip to the Los Angeles Marathon. 
Forty-six workers started the program, or about 20 percent of the 
250-person staff; 29 completed the training, got the free trip and 
ran in the March 14 marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	Even non-runners got into the spirit by rooting on the  
marathoners and hosting pasta dinners and a welcome-home party. 
</P>
<P>
	Though 5 a.m. training runs and workers limping around the  
office with sore knees may not seem like morale boosters, company 
officials said the marathon wellness program has improved company 
loyalty, led employees to work longer hours and created a more 
relaxed workplace. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people are healthier, they work better and they enjoy  
their lives more,'' executive vice president Michael Goodman said. 
``Because of this, we're a better company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The marathon program was so successful, J.G. Wentworth is doing  
it again. The company is giving away free trips to the London 
Marathon in April 2000 for employees who earn points by running a 
series of training races. If 50 people qualify for the marathon and 
the company reaches certain sales targets, the entire staff will 
get a free trip to England. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never ran a day in my life. But I started the day after I  
got the e-mail,'' said Tom Hoffman, who ran Los Angeles and now is 
training for London. ``I wanted the free trip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company has tried other employee incentive programs,  
including offering trips for white-water rafting or to Washington, 
D.C., based on certain company goals. But the marathon-wellness 
program was the most successful. 
</P>
<P>
	``People want to come into work,'' said vice president Randi  
Sellari, who ran the marathon despite painful tendinitis in both 
knees. ``They have company loyalty, where they didn't have it 
before. People are talking about the company; they are motivated. I 
see people staying later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Training was the hardest part for most of the J.G. Wentworth  
employees, who often work 10- or 12-hour days. Employees met 
several times a week at 5 a.m. for runs either in Central Park in 
New York or along the Schuylkill River in Philadelphia. On the 
weekends, they would meet for two- to three-hour runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing how quickly you become friends with people that  
you run with almost every day, especially when it's 20 degrees 
outside and its six o'clock in the morning,'' said Al Nickelberry, 
director of sales and a 20-year marathoner who helped set up the 
company's training regiment. 
</P>
<P>
	Nickelberry and Goodman have become unlikely training partners.  
Nickelberry has run since he could walk, completing about two 
marathons a year for more than a decade. Goodman never liked 
running and never thought of doing a marathon. But the pair, who 
both live in the New York suburbs, still meet twice a week for 
pre-dawn runs in Central Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``Running is something that once you get over that hump  
everybody in the company can do, and everybody finds their level 
and finds partners to run with,'' Goodman said. ``You find people 
that you wouldn't normally relate to, and you relate to them about 
running.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
