<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hope Seen in Japan's Auto Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Flanked by local rivals such as Honda and Toyota on  
a gritty road lined with dealerships, Ford dealer Yoshiaki Kikuchi 
has the unenviable task of hawking American cars to Japanese 
consumers who aren't exactly running to make big purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers have been hit harder by Japan's recession than just  
about any other industry. Domestic sales have fallen 23 consecutive 
months, plunging by about 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just hanging on,'' said Kikuchi, ``doing our best to  
stay in business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts see demand roaring back once the recession eases  
up. And, while dealers fight for survival on the front lines, 
Japanese and foreign automakers are jockeying for position to cash 
in when the market finally comes around. 
</P>
<P>
	American carmakers, which have always struggled in Japan, are  
investing in their sales networks, a major weakness, hoping to make 
significant inroads before the locals can turn the corner. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor has been pouring money into distribution channels and  
is about to enter Japan's cutthroat small-car market for the first 
time with its Ka model -- a big hit in Europe that is expected to 
appeal to Japanese tastes. 
</P>
<P>
	German-American automaker DaimlerChrysler AG, meanwhile, has  
broken ties with Japanese partners to sell some of its models 
independently. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the aggressive strategy is sound.  
</P>
<P>
	``They've established a stronger network, so they'll be able to  
ultimately benefit when the market gets stronger,'' said Peter 
Boardman, an industry analyst with Warburg Dillon Reed. 
</P>
<P>
	But Japanese manufacturers are also toughening up with  
production cutbacks and cash infusions from foreign partners. 
Analysts expect them to emerge from the recession more formidable 
than ever, having finally been forced to confront structural 
problems and increase efficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Renault of France agreed to invest $5.4 billion in  
Nissan Motor, taking a 37 percent stake in the debt-burdened 
automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	And Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's biggest automaker, has slashed  
production at its main plant in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you see the market correct and stabilize, I think we're  
going to see the Japanese come back stronger than they were 
before,'' said Steve Usher, an auto analyst with Jardine Fleming. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say Japan's automakers have fared remarkably well amid  
the sharp downturn in domestic sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty incredible,'' Usher said. ``There's not an  
American or European carmaker that could have sustained that kind 
of pressure in their core market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A weak yen has helped them weather the difficulties by making  
Japanese exports less expensive in other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	But exports, which account for nearly half of the automakers'  
sales, might not continue to prop up the industry if the yen posts 
a sharp recovery or demand drops off in key markets such as the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say that despite falling revenue, Japanese automakers  
are in a strong position because they retain a technological edge 
over their foreign rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	They are said to hold a big lead in the development of  
environment-friendly vehicles, which are expected to become an 
important part of the market in years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota was the first automaker to market a gasoline-electric  
hybrid car and Honda Motor Co. plans to launch one this year. 
Overseas rivals don't expect to have their versions ready for sale 
before 2001. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
