<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guard Urges Fishing Boat Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A U.S. Coast Guard panel has recommended mandatory  
inspections of fishing boats and licensing of skippers in the wake 
of four sinkings along the East Coast that killed 11 clam 
fishermen. 
</P>
<P>
	Most fishing fatalities -- including the recent deaths -- are  
preventable, said the Fishing Vessel Casualty Task Force. The 
report was to be released today by Coast Guard officials in 
Atlantic City, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The spate of accidents in December and January wasn't unique,  
the report said. A comparison of deaths of the last four years 
showed no significant shift in casualty statistics, the Coast Guard 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Inadequate safety standards, poor compliance with safety  
regulations, and insufficient participation in voluntary safety 
measures too often lead to unsafe conditions, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel recommended several measures -- including operator  
licenses, competency certificates for crew and mandatory vessel 
inspections, all of which would require congressional approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tragic deaths described in this report tell us that the  
time is right to seek breakthrough levels of casualty reduction,'' 
Rear Admiral R.C. North wrote in a memo attached to a report. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, boat inspections are voluntary, and many owners fail  
to maintain their vessels, equipment and basic safety gear, the 
task force said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The level of fishing vessel safety standards is analogous to  
requiring parachutes for an airplane crew, but only marketing 
voluntary measures to encourage a mechanically sound aircraft and a 
competent pilot and crew,'' the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
