<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Judy, Hubby May Compete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It may soon be Judge Judy vs. Mr. Judge Judy in  
the court of public opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald Sheindlin, the husband of ``Judge Judy'' Sheindlin and  
like her a retired New York City judge, is talking to producers of 
the ``People's Court'' about taking over as its arbiter, according 
to an executive with the syndicated TV show's distributors who 
asked not to be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Left in the cold could be current ``People's Court'' jurist  
Edward Koch, who appointed both Sheindlins to the bench when he was 
New York City mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Judge Judy'' has dominated the newly hot court show genre, its  
ratings up 76 percent over last season, and has made the 
no-nonsense former judge a star. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the ratings for ``People's Court'' haven't changed  
over the past year and two new TV judges, Joe Brown and Mills Lane, 
have passed Koch in average audience size, said Marc Berman, a 
television analyst for the media buying firm Seltel. 
</P>
<P>
	The audience for ``Judge Judy'' is two and a half times that of  
``People's Court,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Signing up Judy's husband could entice curious viewers who  
wonder what sort of man would live with her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's a bad thing, because the show needs some  
attention,'' Berman said. ``I don't think he will beat Judy in the 
long run, but it will bring people in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's unclear what Gerald Sheindlin's workload would be;  
``People's Court'' has discussed having him appear in at least half 
of the shows during the TV season that begins in September, said 
the executive from Warner Bros. Television, the show's 
distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Judy sent word through a spokeswoman that she didn't want  
to talk about potentially competing with her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	An executive at ``Judge Judy'' seemed to be spoiling for a  
fight, despite asking not to be identified. ``We can't wait,'' the 
executive said. 
</P>
<P>
	Koch has presided over ``People's Court'' since the show was  
revived in September 1997. ``People's Court'' with Judge Joseph 
Wapner was as much a cultural touchstone in the 1980s as ``Judge 
Judy'' is today. 
</P>
<P>
	The 74-year-old former mayor, who was hospitalized briefly for  
low blood pressure last month, referred calls to producers at 
``People's Court.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
