<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Company Recalls Salmon Dip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A New Jersey company is recalling all  
varieties of Perona Farms smoked salmon dip because it may be 
contaminated with listeria, a type of serious, sometimes 
lifethreatening, bacteria. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers who have purchased 8-ounce containers of Perona Farms  
smoked salmon dip -- including Moroccan, scampi and pastrami 
varieties -- should not eat the dip, but return it to the place of 
purchase for a refund. 
</P>
<P>
	Healthy people may suffer only such symptoms as severe headache,  
nausea, abdominal pain and diarrhea from listeria. But the germ can 
cause serious, even fatal, infections in young children, the 
elderly or people with weak immune systems, and can cause 
miscarriages in pregnant women. 
</P>
<P>
	Food inspectors in New York found listeria in one batch of  
smoked salmon dip, but Perona Farms of Andover, N.J., said Tuesday 
it is recalling all batches and varieties of the dip. No illnesses 
have been reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The dip was sold in stores in Washington, D.C., and 12 states:  
New York, New Jersey, Massachusetts, Vermont, Connecticut, 
Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, 
Kentucky and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers may contact the company at 1-800-750-6190.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
