<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Criticizes U.S. Trade Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's farm minister said Tuesday that the  
possible invocation of a section of a controversial U.S. trade law 
could damage ties between Washington and Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoichi Nakagawa, who heads the Ministry of Agriculture,  
Forestry and Fisheries, said the punitive Super 301 provision goes 
against the spirit of the World Trade Organization, according to a 
ministry spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the U.S. is trying to implement it, it is bad for  
U.S.-Japan relations,'' the spokesman, speaking on customary 
condition of anonymity, quoted Nakagawa as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Nakagawa's comments come after the United States released its  
annual report on foreign trade barriers on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said Washington would urge Tokyo to implement further  
deregulation measures in the telecommunications, housing, medical 
services and pharmaceuticals sectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese media reports have interpreted that as an indication  
the Clinton administration is threatening to invoke Super 301 if no 
progress is made on insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Kaoru Yosano, Japan's trade minister, criticized the  
report, saying it was ``not necessarily based on international 
rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. and Japanese officials are scheduled to hold working-level  
talks on Japan's insurance market next week in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
