<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former SEC Lawyer Gets Jail Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A former lawyer with the Securities and Exchange  
Commission was sentenced today to a year in prison for bribing a 
broker to promote the stock of a company he represented. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert D. Schulman, 56, of New York City was sentenced by U.S.  
District Judge John F. Keenan in Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	Schulman was convicted July 30 of conspiracy to commit wire  
fraud and interstate commercial bribery for participating in a 
scheme to make secret payments to stock brokers to entice them to 
sell shares of Grayhound Electronics Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	He formerly served as a staff lawyer in the Enforcement Division  
of the SEC's Northeast Regional Office from 1968 to 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Schulman was snared in an undercover FBI investigation in which  
agents posed as corrupt brokers willing to accept bribes to promote 
stocks to their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Schulman told an FBI agent posing as a  
dishonest stockbroker that he was a lawyer for Grayhound 
Electronics and several of its European shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	He allegedly promised to make secret payments of Grayhound stock  
to the broker in exchange for the broker's agreement to sell more 
than a million shares of Grayhound to his customers so that the 
stock price would rise from 38 cents a share to $1 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	After the phony broker bought 50,000 shares of Grayhound  
supposedly on behalf of a customer, Schulman had 15,000 shares of 
Grayhound deposited into a secret brokerage account for the 
broker's benefit, prosecutors said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
