<DOCNO> APW19990406.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 11:25:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Air Bags Do Well in Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Side air bags on Ford Motor Co.'s 1999 models  
greatly reduce the likelihood of serious head injury to the driver 
in crash tests, a safety research institute said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, which is financed by  
insurers, crashed two 1999 model Lincoln Town Cars by hurtling them 
sideways into an upright pole that smashed into the driver's side 
door. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first test, the car had no side air bag and the head  
injuries sustained by the dummy representing the driver were severe 
enough to cause death in an actual collision, institute president 
Brian O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second test, the side air bag cushioned the dummy's head  
from the force of the crash, making it ``survivable despite the 
(crash's) severity,'' O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Side air bags are standard equipment on the 1999 Lincoln  
Continental and Town Car. Ford has started offering them with head 
protection as options in front seats of some of its more popular 
and less expensive vehicles: 1999 Ford Explorer and Mercury 
Mountaineer sport utility vehicles, Ford Windstar minivans and the 
Jaguar XJ8 and X200. 
</P>
<P>
	Side air bags with head protection also are on BMWs, Saabs,  
Volvos and some Mercedes models. 
</P>
<P>
	Some automakers offer side air bags that protect the chest area  
rather than the head. Ford's side air bags are designed to do both, 
deploying from the side of the seat and inflating upward and 
forward, said Ford spokeswoman Jennifer Flake. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers such as BMW and Volvo also are designing side air  
bags to try to prevent passengers from being ejected out a window 
during rollover crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	In the institute test, cars are crashed sideways at 18 mph into  
a vertical pole, pushing the pole well into the driver's side, past 
the steering wheel rim. 
</P>
<P>
	The test is comparable to one manufacturers can use to pass  
recent federal head protection requirements. The Transportation 
Department estimates that if all cars had side air bags with head 
protection, about 600 deaths could be prevented in crashes each 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Slightly less than a third of all fatal motor vehicle crashes  
are side-impact crashes, and most of the deaths they cause involve 
head injuries, according to a government database of fatal 
accidents from 1993-1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The institute also said side air bags could help with the  
mismatch among vehicles when larger vehicles such as SUVs or 
pickups crash into the sides of cars. Studies show those accidents 
mostly kill the passengers in the smaller vehicles, the cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``These kinds of air bags are an important step forward in  
making cars crash compatible,'' O'Neill said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 02:13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Reporter Reveals Chiquita Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A reporter facing sentencing next month for  
illegally obtaining voice mail from Chiquita has named a former 
attorney for the banana company as a confidential source for his 
stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Gallagher also testified Monday that attorneys for The  
Cincinnati Enquirer did not tell him that accessing Chiquita's 
voice mail might be illegal until after he had tapped the system. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was relayed to me that it might be illegal,'' Gallagher  
said. ``By then, I had accessed (the system) 15 to 20 times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher, 42, was the lead reporter for the Enquirer's series  
in May 1998 that questioned Chiquita's business practices in 
Central America. The newspaper later renounced the series, fired 
Gallagher, apologized to Chiquita Brands International on the front 
page and paid the Cincinnati-based company more than $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, Gallagher pleaded guilty to illegally intercepting  
communications and obtaining unauthorized access to Chiquita's 
computer systems. 
</P>
<P>
	He never testified about how he obtained the voice mail  
messages, but agreed to cooperate with prosecutors. On Monday, he 
was called to testify by attorneys representing George Ventura, a 
Salt Lake City lawyer who formerly worked for Chiquita. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura goes on trial April 19 on charges that he helped steal  
the voice mail messages. Attorneys were in court to argue about 
evidence to be allowed in that trial, and whether charges of 
illegal interception of communication should be dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning from Ventura's attorney Marc Mezibov,  
Gallagher said Ventura was one of about six people he promised 
confidentiality in return for their help on the Chiquita series. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher, 40, could be sentenced to 2 1/2 years in prison, but his  
plea bargain notes that there is no mandatory prison term. His 
sentencing was delayed until May 13, after he testifies at 
Ventura's trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Enquirer local news editor David Wells, who oversaw reporters'  
work on the Chiquita articles, said editors and lawyers acted 
quickly when Gallagher told them he had accessed the system. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as his editors knew about the access, he was told  
never to do it again,'' Wells said after the hearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
