<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heavy snow fell in parts of the West today, while rain and  
thunderstorms stretched from the Great Lakes to the Gulf Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The heaviest snowfall came in California's Sierra Nevada, with  
up to 2 feet of snow fell overnight at higher elevations around 
Lake Tahoe on the California-Nevada state line. 
</P>
<P>
	That snow fell on top of nearly 2 feet that accumulated in the  
mountains during the Easter weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have any pull, will you tell it to stop?'' said Judy  
Miller, a service manager at the Donner Park Unocal on Interstate 
80 in Truckee, Calif. ``It's too late in the season to be getting 
so much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At lower elevations, 3 to 4 inches of snow fell overnight in  
Nevada's Reno and Carson City area. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 8 inches of snow was forecast elsewhere in the mountains  
of Northern California and lesser amounts in Montana and Idaho. 
Wind gusting to 50 mph was possible in the Southwest, where 19 
inches of snow fell at higher elevations of northern Arizona on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the East, rain and thunderstorms stretched from Wisconsin and  
Michigan across the Ohio and Tennessee valleys to southern sections 
of Louisiana and Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow fell on Minnesota, with as much as 7 inches possible today  
in parts of the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The rain was moving eastward, and was forecast to extend through  
the Appalachians into the Southeast by tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, tornadoes struck the middle of the nation.  
</P>
<P>
	In Wichita, Kan., a tornado near an elementary school ripped  
apart three portable classrooms as children took cover in a nearby 
basement. Wind topping 65 mph caused minor damage elsewhere in the 
city. No injuries were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Several tornadoes in southeastern Nebraska destroyed some farm  
buildings near Shubert, ripped roofs off buildings outside Verdon, 
and damaged buildings and power lines elsewhere around the area. No 
one was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy rain accompanied the Nebraska storms, with nearly 2 1/2  
inches at Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pocahontas, Ark., a tornado destroyed one business and  
damaged several others. One person was reported injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Monday was 94 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The low was 4 at 
Yellowstone National Park, Wyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 30s and 40s in the  
northern Plains, Rockies and Great Lakes; the 50s and 60s in the 
Northeast, Northwest, Plains and West; and the 70s and 80s in the 
Southeast and Southwest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
