<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Chiquita Lawyer on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Lawyers defending a former Chiquita banana  
company attorney accused of stealing voice mail for a newspaper 
investigation argued Tuesday that a reporter's promise of anonymity 
to a source is a legally enforceable commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for George G. Ventura made the argument to try to  
prevent two former reporters for The Cincinnati Enquirer from 
linking Ventura to the illegal intrusion into Chiquita's internal 
voice-mail system. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense is trying to persuade a judge to throw out all 10  
felony charges against Ventura, a former lawyer for Chiquita Brands 
International Inc. who is now in private practice in Salt Lake 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Ann Marie Tracey didn't say when she will decide.  
</P>
<P>
	Ventura has pleaded innocent to unlawful interception of  
communications and unauthorized access to computer systems. He 
could get 12 1/2 years in prison if convicted. His was postponed 
Tuesday to July 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura's lawyers argued that a reporter who promises anonymity  
to a source has effectively entered into a legally binding contract 
that protects the source against being exposed later by the 
reporter, even under pressure of prosecution. They said Ohio's 
shield law, which allows reporters to protect the identities of 
confidential sources, also protects the sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``If one (reporter) decides he is going to become an arm of the  
prosecutor and divulge the identity of a confidential source, then 
he has done journalism a tremendous disservice, because then no 
confidential source is ever going to cooperate with a reporter 
again,'' said Marc Mezibov, a lawyer for Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Breyer, the prosecutor, said he saw no reason to legally  
protect the identity of confidential sources. He said that could 
have the effect of releasing such sources from any accountability 
for their actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters Michael Gallagher and Cameron McWhirter relied on the  
voice mail messages in an Enquirer package of stories last May 
accusing Cincinnati-based Chiquita of improper dealings in Central 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the Enquirer fired Gallagher, apologized on its front  
page to Chiquita and said it was paying Chiquita more than $10 
million to settle any claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher pleaded guilty in September to felony charges and is  
awaiting sentencing that could range from 2 1/2 years in prison to 
probation. The prosecutor said Tuesday he will ask to have 
Gallagher's sentencing delayed until after Ventura's trial. 
</P>
<P>
	McWhirter has not been charged and now works for The Detroit  
News, also owned by Gannett Co. Inc. McWhirter has said he did not 
access Chiquita's system but got codes from a source and gave them 
to Gallagher. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
