<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Buys Online Calendar Provider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DULLES, Va. (AP) -- America Online Inc. has acquired When Inc.,  
which provides a Web-based calendar service that allows users to 
keep track of their schedules from any computer connected to the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online said in a statement Monday that it had completed  
the acquisition of When, based in Redwood City, Calif., for an 
undisclosed amount of its stock. The Wall Street Journal today 
quoted sources familiar with the deal as saying it was worth about 
$150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL said it would begin a new version of the When.com service  
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The calendar service allows users to keep track of appointments,  
birthdays and upcoming activities. Subscribers can also select 
events that interest them, such as the release of certain CDs or 
books, and receive reminders when they are available. 
</P>
<P>
	The information entered in the personal calendar remains  
private, but the subscriber has the option of volunteering certain 
dates, like birthdays or anniversaries, in exchange for receiving 
selective offers from AOL advertisers. 
</P>
<P>
	When.com's group calendar features allow members of an  
organization or a community to share calendar information. 
</P>
<P>
	``When.com's calendar is the perfect personalization tool to  
help build community and to connect shopping opportunities with a 
person's individual interests and community events,'' America 
Online's president, Robert W. Pittman, said in the statement. 

</P>
</TEXT>
