<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Not Affecting Navy Readiness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- The Steelworkers strike at Newport News  
Shipbuilding, in its second day today, so far has not affected the 
Navy's readiness, Navy officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the yard is the only shipyard that builds  
nuclear-powered aircraft carriers, there are other places the Navy 
could go if necessary should a carrier need repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy has four shipyards, and two can handle ``major  
maintenance service'' for aircraft carriers, said David Caskey, 
spokesman for the Arlington-based Naval Sea Systems Command, which 
oversees construction and maintenance of Navy ships. The shipyards 
are Norfolk Naval Shipyard in Portsmouth and Puget Sound Naval 
Shipyard in Washington state. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether the strike is affecting the Navy's readiness,  
Caskey said, ``Not now.'' He would not speculate on long-term 
effects. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne Ripley, a spokesman for the Navy's Supervisor of  
Shipbuilding office in Newport News, agreed readiness was not 
hampered. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Navy maintains sufficient public and private ship repair  
capacity for all ship types, including aircraft carriers, to ensure 
readiness is maintained during periods of private sector labor 
disputes,'' Ripley said in a written statement in response to 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News Shipbuilding is building the aircraft carrier  
Ronald Reagan, refueling the carrier USS Nimitz, doing some 
maintenance work on the carrier USS Harry S. Truman and working on 
the USS Narwhal, a submarine scheduled to be deactivated. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipyard spokeswoman Jerri Fuller Dickseski said work at the  
yard continued despite the strike. Many salaried employees rose 
through the ranks and have experience performing the hourly 
employees' jobs, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's how we're maintaining productivity,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Local 8888 of the United Steelworkers of America represents  
9,200 hourly workers out of the yard's total 17,400 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Local President Arnold Outlaw said fewer than 500 hourly workers  
crossed the picket line Monday and that a majority of union members 
appeared to honor the strike Tuesday. Ms. Dickseski would not say 
how many hourly employees reported for work. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 1,000 workers walked the picket lines Tuesday, Outlaw  
said. ``We will keep on doing the same thing until the shipyard 
decides they want to bring us a fair package,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	No negotiating sessions have been held since union members voted  
Thursday to reject the shipyard's final offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The union wants an across-the-board hourly pay increase of $3.95  
over three years. The shipyard has offered increases over three 
years that it said would boost the average worker's pay $2.49 an 
hour, with automatic promotions based on experience and skills. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
