<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heston Challenged on Gun Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Mayor Marc Morial is challenging Charlton  
Heston to a debate over gun safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Heston, president of the National Rifle Association, replied  
Tuesday: ``The mayor should take care of the problems of New 
Orleans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morial issued the challenge for a nationally televised debate on  
the eve of the actor's visit to Louisiana. New Orleans is suing 
gunmakers for shooting injuries and deaths; the NRA is backing 
legislation to bar such lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are trying to gag cities by sponsoring legislation that  
makes gunmakers immune to product liability suits,'' Morial said in 
a statement. ``A national debate will help the American people see 
the real issue. The real issue is the fact that guns can be 
designed safer.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 18:32:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charles Keating Enters Guilty Pleas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former Lincoln Savings &AMP; Loan chief Charles  
Keating Jr. pleaded guilty today to four counts of fraud in a deal 
with prosecutors that allows him to go free, bringing a close to a 
case that epitomized the S&AMP;L scandal of the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Mariana Pfaelzer, after taking a  
90-minute recess to review conditions of the deal, accepted the 
plea. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-running case involved investors' loss of $200 million  
and the collapse Lincoln Savings, which cost taxpayers $3.4 
billion. His previous convictions had been thrown out on appeal, 
but prosecutors said they would retry him. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Keating was sentenced to time he has spent in  
jail on previous convictions, less than five years in prison. The 
judge did not impose any fines, restitution or supervision by 
authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also dismissed fraud charges against Keating's son,  
Charles Keating III. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how he felt afterward, Keating said, ``Great.'' Asked what  
lay ahead, he said, ``Life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He declined further comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Keating pleaded guilty to three counts of wire fraud and one  
count of bankruptcy fraud. The latter count involved transfer of 
$975,000 from his American Continental Corp. to himself through 
relatives days before the company filed for bankruptcy protection. 
American Continental was parent of Lincoln Savings. 
</P>
<P>
	The plea followed an announcement by prosecutors in January that  
they planned to retry Keating and his son on charges that he 
defrauded investors who lost $200 million in worthless junk bonds 
issued by American Continental Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating's case returned to U.S. District Court earlier this year  
after an appellate court threw out the Keatings' 1992 federal 
convictions and said they deserved a new trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating, known for extravagant spending during his days as  
chairman of American Continental, was convicted in federal and 
state court on charges stemming from the collapse of Lincoln 
Savings. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors argued in the two trials that Keating looted Lincoln  
Savings of its assets to prop up American Continental. Bond 
purchasers, they said, were not told of the investment's risky 
nature. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating denied the allegations and blamed government regulators  
for Lincoln's collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Sharon McCaslin told Pfaelzer the deal  
was justified because Keating was accepting responsibility for 
fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaslin also said that so much time had passed that some  
witnesses may have difficulty recalling the events that led to 
Lincoln's collapse. Many of the bond purchasers were elderly 
Lincoln customers who claimed they were duped into buying the 
bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal, Keating submitted a financial statement  
verifying that he had no financial resources in the United States 
or overseas that would enable him to pay $1 million in fines called 
for in the four counts involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the plea agreement, Keating faced a maximum sentence of  
20 years in prison followed by three years of supervised release, 
plus the fines and possible restitution to victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating served nearly five years in prison before the federal  
conviction was overturned on grounds some jurors learned of his 
earlier conviction in state court and discussed it in the jury 
room. Despite finding that the jury had based its verdict on the 
courtroom evidence, Pfaelzer ruled that jurors' exposure to outside 
information denied Keating a fair trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating's state conviction was voided as well on grounds that  
the trial judge issued improper instructions to the jury. The state 
of California is appealing that reversal. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating's lawyer Stephen Neal said he thought there was little  
chance the case would be resurrected. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Keating's legal problems are not entirely over. He  
still faces $1.5 billion in civil judgments stemming from lawsuits 
filed by investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating had been sentenced to 10 years in prison on the state  
conviction and received a 12-year concurrent sentence in federal 
court. He was freed in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned to jail for five days in March 1998 after Pfaelzer  
ruled that he violated the terms of his probation by applying for a 
passport. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Keating III also was convicted in the federal trial. He  
was sentenced to eight years in prison, but remained free on bail 
pending appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
