<HEADLINE> Dollar, Gold Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mostly lower today against  
other major currencies in European trading where dealings resumed 
after a four-day Easter weekend. Gold prices fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell to 120.98 Japanese yen from 121.83 yen late  
Monday in New York, and was lower against the euro, which rose to 
$1.0728 from $1.0708. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Monday in New York  
included 1.4874 Swiss francs, down from 1.4895, and 1.5007 Canadian 
dollars, down from 1.5020. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.5992, down from $1.6000.  
</P>
<P>
	At midday in New York, the euro was quoted at $1.0811 but other  
currency quotes were unavailable. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on euro rates in Europe, the dollar was worth 1.8231 German 
marks, down from 1.8265; 6.1144 French francs, down from 6.1275; 
2.0542 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1670, and 1,804.88 Italian lire, 
down from 1,808.32. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $278.60 per troy ounce, down from  
$280.20 on Thursday, the last day of trading before the Easter 
holiday. In Zurich the bid was $278.40, down from $280.00 late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold markets in Hong Kong were closed for the Ching Ming  
holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $4.96 per troy ounce, down from  
$5.03. 
</P>
</TEXT>
