<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL May Reject Sale of Redskins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Two years and one day after the death of Jack  
Kent Cooke, NFL owners appear ready to reject the proposed sale of 
the Washington Redskins, a decision that could leave the franchise 
in limbo for months and perhaps years. 
</P>
<P>
	Questions about Howard Milstein's finances, his contentious  
stewardship of the New York Islanders and a perceived high-handed 
lobbying approach have many owners leaning toward a veto of the 
$800 million bid, the most offered for a U.S. sports franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four of the 31 owners must approve the sale Wednesday at  
a special meeting arranged after Milstein requested a postponement 
last month in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	One league source, speaking on condition of anonymity, told The  
Associated Press the group had no more than seven to 10 votes in 
Phoenix and they are still ``far short'' of the three-fourths 
required. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote could hinge on a recommendation from commissioner Paul  
Tagliabue and the league's financial committee, which will meet 
before the vote. The eight-member committee was split 3-3 with two 
abstentions in Phoenix. Committee chairman New England owner Bob 
Kraft has been one of the bid's few solid supporters, but committee 
members Tom Benson of New Orleans and Pat Bowlen of Denver are 
adamantly opposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the objections by some owners:  
</P>
<P>
	--While Milstein is worth an estimated $500 million, most of it  
is tied up in real estate, making his part of the bid heavily 
leveraged without the ready cash to back it up. His father recently 
agreed to supply $125 million to support the bid, but some league 
officials reportedly consider that money a loan that helps the 
financing arrangement only marginally. 
</P>
<P>
	--Milstein's part-ownership of the NHL's Islanders, which he  
bought with a partner just 14 months ago, has been ugly and 
litigious. Milstein wanted a new arena and threatened to cancel 
games because he felt the old one was unsafe. There are lawsuits 
pending between Milstein and New York's Nassau County. 
</P>
<P>
	--Milstein, according to several sources, solicited politicians  
in the nation's capital to lobby owners on his behalf. Sources say 
several owners considered it an impropriety when they received 
calls from congressmen from other parts of the country asking about 
the Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	--Several owners have expressed a preference for Cooke's son,  
team president John Kent Cooke, to own the team. John Kent Cooke 
was outbid by Milstein and Daniel Snyder in an auction conducted by 
the trustees of his father's estate -- in accordance with his 
father's will after his death on April 6, 1997 -- but sources say 
some owners are eager to make the point that they alone can choose 
who joins their exclusive club. 
</P>
<P>
	All of which begs the question: If the owners say no, what  
happens next? 
</P>
<P>
	No one is saying for sure -- ``We'll cross that bridge if we have  
to,'' league spokesman Greg Aiello said -- but the league probably 
will tell the trustees to hold another auction and come back with 
another bid in a few months. 
</P>
<P>
	The favorite to win a second round of bidding would be Snyder, a  
Washington-area communications executive who has the money in the 
bank and who has come through the NFL process unscathed. Snyder 
could team with a losing bidder from the first round, such as 
Phoenix developer Sam Grossman, to mount a formidable bid. 
</P>
<P>
	But all that becomes moot if Milstein loses and decides to sue,  
halting the sale process with a course of action that could take 
years to play out. Milstein was asked by the owners in Phoenix if 
he would sue. His initial response was that he had not thought 
about it, but he later said he would not. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless the sale is approved, John Kent Cooke will continue to  
run the team, retaining coach Norv Turner and general manager 
Charley Casserly. 
</P>
<P>
	Several free agents said they were wary of signing with the  
Redskins because of the uncertainty, and the players under contract 
want the matter resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those things that has gone on too long,'' center  
Cory Raymer said Tuesday. ``And it's become a pain in the butt.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
