<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Charged for DNC Contribution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A businessman was charged Tuesday with giving  
the Democratic National Committee $150,000 drawn from a South 
Korean corporation -- a violation of federal election laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert S. Lee, 49, was the 16th person charged in a Justice  
Department investigation of campaign financing. He has agreed to a 
plea agreement that will be filed Wednesday, Assistant U.S. 
Attorney Daniel J. O'Brien said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien wouldn't discuss details of the plea. DNC spokesman Rick  
Hess said the DNC had thought the funds were from U.S. sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee was charged with misdemeanor aiding and abetting an illegal  
campaign contribution from foreign sources, a violation of the 
Federal Election Campaign Act. The charge carries up to a year in 
prison and a fine of more than $25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee is accused of giving the DNC a $150,000 check drawn on a  
California development firm's bank account that was entirely funded 
by a firm in Seoul, South Korea. The check was allegedly handed 
over to the DNC in May 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone message left for Lee's attorney was not returned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
