<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lukas Journalism Prizes Are Awarded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Books on the abolition of slavery, the  
plundering of the Congo, and the lives of World War II veterans 
from New Jersey were named winners Monday of the first J. Anthony 
Lukas prize for nonfiction writing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lukas Prize Project honors work that exemplifies the  
writings of its namesake, a former correspondent for The New York 
Times who died in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry Meyer's ``All on Fire: William Lloyd Garrison and the  
Abolition of Slavery'' won The J. Anthony Lukas Book Prize. He 
receives $10,000 for his recounting of the religious, political and 
literary forces that came together to defeat slavery. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam Hochschild will receive $10,000 as the winner of The Mark  
Lynton History Prize for his book, ``King Leopold's Ghost: A Story 
of Greed, Terror, and Heroism in Colonial Africa.'' The book 
details the plundering of the Congo by King Leopold II of Belgium, 
an act that led to the first great human rights movement of the 
20th century. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Coyne is the $45,000 winner of The J. Anthony Lukas  
Work-In-Progress Award for his forthcoming book ``The Best Years of 
Their Lives,'' a look at six men from the same New Jersey town who 
fought in World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas, a winner of two Pulitzer Prizes and the National Book  
Award, tackled generational conflict in his first book ``Don't 
Shoot: We Are Your Children.'' He examined the impact of school 
desegregation in ``Common Ground,'' and discussed class conflict at 
the turn of the century in ``Big Trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The awards are co-administered by the Columbia University  
Graduate School of Journalism and the Nieman Foundation at Harvard 
University. The awards will be presented May 1 at the Conference on 
Nonfiction Writing and Awards Ceremony at Columbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
