<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Economic Indicators Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A key economic barometer rose for a fifth  
straight month in February, signaling that the U.S. economy will 
continue to thrive at least through the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said the Index of Leading Economic  
Indicators rose 0.2 percent in February, in line with economists' 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the 10 indicators that make up the leading index were  
positive, including higher consumer expectations and lower 
first-time claims for unemployment benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the fifth consecutive increase in the leading index  
but it shows less breadth than usual with only four of 10 
components rising in February,'' said Michael Boldin, director of 
business cycle research at the business-financed private research 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	The index is designed to forecast economic activity six to nine  
months in advance. The Conference Board also reported that the 
coincident indicators, which measure current activity, rose 0.3 
percent and the lagging index, which measures the economy's past 
performance, rose 0.2 percent in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Taken together, the board said the three index components show a  
healthy economy and an economic expansion that will continue 
through at least late 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is consistent with the view that the economy is  
continuing to expand,'' said Michael Moran, chief economist at 
Daiwa Securities America. ``The signal that you get from this 
measure is no turning point in the economy is at hand and that is 
good news for investors and good for the economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The figures had little impact on Wall Street, where the Dow  
Jones industrial average was retreating from Monday's record and 
back below 10,000. At late morning, the Dow was down 35.24 at 
9,972.09. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the strength in the index came from decline in initial  
unemployment claims, said Douglas Porter, senior economist at 
Nesbitt Burns Securities of Chicago. That made up for declines in 
manufacturers' new orders. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is consistent with the trend we've seen in the economy,  
``Porter said. ``We're not as strong as 1997 and 1998, but it still 
a solid performance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report said the rise in the coincident indicators point to  
the Gross Domestic Product expanding at an annual rate of 3 percent 
in the first quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The index increased 0.5 percent in January and increased 0.2  
percent in December. During the six months ended in February, the 
leading index rose 1.4 percent and eight of the 10 components 
advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading indicators are calculated from a base of 100, set in  
1992. First calculated in the late 1960s, it is periodically 
fine-tuned and figures from past years are revised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
