<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Indicators Rise Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While the numbers weren't as strong as the past  
two years, a key indicator of future economic growth suggests the 
country will continue to thrive at least through the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose for the fifth  
straight month in February, the Conference Board, reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising consumer expectations and a drop in first-time claims for  
jobless benefits were among factors pushing the index up 0.2 
percent in February, in line with economists' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the fifth consecutive increase in the leading index  
but it shows less breadth than usual with only four of 10 
components rising in February,'' said Michael Boldin, director of 
business cycle research at the business-financed private research 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	A drop in orders from manufacturers held the index down.  
</P>
<P>
	The index is designed to forecast economic activity six to nine  
months in advance. The Conference Board also reported that the 
coincident indicators, which measure current activity, rose 0.3 
percent and the lagging index, which measures the economy's past 
performance, rose 0.2 percent in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Taken together, the board said the three index components show a  
healthy economy and an economic expansion that will continue 
through at least late 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is consistent with the view that the economy is  
continuing to expand,'' said Michael Moran, chief economist at 
Daiwa Securities America. ``The signal that you get from this 
measure is no turning point in the economy is at hand and that is 
good news for investors and good for the economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The figures had little impact on Wall Street, where the Dow  
Jones industrial average retreated from Monday's record and dropped 
back below 10,000. The Dow fell 43.84 to close at 9,963.49, but the 
Nasdaq composite index climbed to a second straight record close. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas Porter, senior economist at Nesbitt Burns Securities of  
Chicago, said the index was reflecting a trend in an economy that 
now is in the ninth year of an expansion. ``We're not as strong as 
1997 and 1998, but its still a solid performance,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said the rise in the coincident index indicates the  
Gross Domestic Product expanded at an annual rate of 3 percent in 
the first quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading index increased 0.5 percent in January and increased  
0.2 percent in December. During the six months ended in February, 
the leading index rose 1.4 percent and eight of the 10 components 
advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading indicators are calculated from a base of 100, set in  
1992. First calculated in the late 1960s, it is periodically 
fine-tuned and figures from past years are revised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
