<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Turn Lower; Dow Down 39.96 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned lower Tuesday as an earnings  
warning from Gillette put the brakes on Monday's rally. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 39.96 at 9,967.37. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed after trading lower through  
much of the morning. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 1.51 at 
1,322.63, and the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was up 
7.73 at 2,567.79. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Dow rose 174.82 points to close at 10,007.33, a  
new record that marked the index's second finish above 10,000. The 
Nasdaq and S&AMP;P 500 indexes also set new records, sustained by a 
rally in Internet stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette, which said first-quarter profits will probably not  
meet Wall Street analysts' expectations, fell 6 13/16 today to 50 
15/16. The company's announcement sobered traders who had bid 
stocks higher Monday on expectations of strong first-quarter 
results. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette's news also hurt other consumer products companies.  
Procter &AMP; Gamble, a component of the Dow, fell 1 1/2 to 99 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM rose today as the company unveiled a new version of its Web  
server, which allows companies to provide faster service on the 
Internet. IBM was up 1 3/16 at 185 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! was providing the Nasdaq Stock Market a boost today as  
traders sent its shares higher in advance of its earning report, 
due Wednesday. Many analysts believe the Web search engine company 
will surpass a First Call consensus estimate of 8 cents per share. 
Its shares were up 12 1/8 at 231 1/4 after rising 39 3/16 on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers today by an 11-to-8  
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 341.5 
million shares, slightly ahead of Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was off 1.98 at 612.65, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 3.64 at 717.60. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
