<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Makes Rocket's Debut a Washout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Roger Clemens kicked the mound in disgust  
with his right foot. Tony Phillips' homer had just destroyed his 
aura of invincibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Two innings later, Clemens headed to the dugout to watch his new  
team lose a soggy season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens was nearly unhittable for the first 4 2-3 innings of his  
debut with the New York Yankees on Monday night against the Oakland 
Athletics, despite a 47-minute rain delay between the second and 
third innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to extend the 15-game winning streak with which he closed  
last season for the Toronto Blue Jays, Clemens had allowed only a 
drag bunt single by Jason McDonald in the third inning and had 
struck out seven of the 17 batters he faced. 
</P>
<P>
	But, after walking Miguel Tejada on a full count with two outs  
in the fifth, Clemens gave up Phillips' game-tying shot to right 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a little quick on my slide step,'' Clemens said. ``He's  
got that zone down where he's very dangerous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Derek Jeter's 410-foot homer to center field in the top of the  
seventh put the Yankees ahead 3-2 and gave Clemens another chance 
for the win, but again the five-time Cy Young Award winner could 
not hold the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	With one out in the bottom of the seventh, Clemens walked  
Phillips and was taken out of the game after throwing 107 pitches. 
The bullpen then blew Clemens' chance for a win, as well as the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Giambi's run-scoring groundout off Mike Stanton tied the  
game 3-3 and Matt Stairs followed with an RBI single off loser 
Stanton. John Jaha then doubled off Jeff Nelson to drive in 
Oakland's fifth run. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tony got us going,'' Giambi said. ``(Clemens) was dealing and  
it was tough, but Tony kind of broke the string. That kind of put a 
light at the end of the tunnel for us when it was kind of getting 
dim.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game finally ended at 12:27 a.m. PDT after a second rain  
delay of 1 hour, 21 minutes that prevented the Yankees from batting 
in the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, traded to the Yankees in February by the Blue Jays,  
struck out eight and walked five while allowing four hits in his 
debut for New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very excited to take the mound,'' he said. ``I'm pretty  
jacked up for every start. But taking the field with these guys is 
very special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens remained two short of the AL record of 17 consecutive  
wins shared by Dave McNally of the Baltimore Orioles in 1968-69 and 
Johnny Allen of the Cleveland Indians in 1936-37. The major league 
record is 24 by Carl Hubbell of the New York Giants in 1936-37. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen anybody so high to win a ball game as Clemens  
was in the dugout for the first inning,'' said Yankees interim 
manager Don Zimmer, a Red Sox coach during part of Clemens' 13-year 
tenure in Boston. ``He was like a wild lion. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the game started, he looked like he was pitching for a  
World Series win. He's some competitor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees left the bases loaded in the first two innings  
against Oakland starter Gil Heredia, a late opening day replacement 
for injured Kenny Rogers, scoring just one run. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we get a base hit in the first or second inning with the  
bases loaded, I think that's enough for Clemens,'' Zimmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Clemens started 5-6 with a 3.50 ERA, but did not lose  
again after May 29. He went 15-0 with a 2.29 ERA the rest of the 
season, winning his second straight Cy Young Award while leading 
the AL in wins, ERA and strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he was disappointed about walking five batters, Clemens  
said he was relatively satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	``Considering the conditions out there, I felt good,'' he said.  
``I felt strong. I felt I was able to channel my emotions. I was 
happy with that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
