<DOCNO> APW19990406.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:35:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Richardson To Stay at DePaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Quentin Richardson says the NBA can wait.  
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, Conference USA's player of the year as a freshman,  
is returning to DePaul for at least one more season. 
</P>
<P>
	His teammates are relieved, his coach is pleased, the family  
that was mostly responsible for his decision is at peace, and 
Richardson is now a happy 18-year-old who can still some day make a 
big payday in the pros. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was basically a decision on whether I needed to be able to  
take care of my family,'' a smiling Richardson said at a news 
conference Monday. ``I asked them were we hurting that bad? My 
father, my sister and my step mom all said, `No, they would be 
fine, it could wait.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson's father, Lee, has worked as a motorman with the  
Chicago Transit Authority for 32 years. At age 56 he wasn't ready 
to retire and he wanted his son to work on his education. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have always told him I wanted him to stay in school,'' Lee  
Richardson said. ``He has always told me that he wanted me to 
retire, but I told him `Hey, I'll be all right.' If he left it up 
to me, I'd want him to do all four. All four years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DePaul coach Pat Kennedy and Richardson's sister, Rochelle,  
talked with several NBA general managers and scouts, seeking input 
to gauge where Richardson might be taken if he declared for the 
draft this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson was projected as a middle to late first-round pick  
where he could probably get a salary of about $900,000. Most 
advised staying in school to work on his game and improve his draft 
positioning. That could, in turn, bring a larger contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to give him the chance to sit down and weigh out  
whether he was really prepared to do this. We wanted him to be at 
the top of his game when he does it,'' Rochelle Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a financial hardship. We just wanted to do what is  
best for him, as well as academically and as a business decision. 
It was not a good idea to let him get out and get locked into a 
contract and not get the (playing) time that would be advantageous 
to his future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson's decision will certainly help DePaul as it tries to  
rebuild a national reputation. His return should mean more 
victories, more fans in the stands and more publicity that will aid 
recruiting. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy had a rooting interest in Richardson returning, but made  
sure he obtained all the information and then let his young star 
make the decision. He wasn't told of Richardson's decision until 
right before it was announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's maybe even bigger than when he said he was first coming  
here,'' said Kennedy, who landed Richardson as a recruit right 
after it appeared he was headed to Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, at 6-foot-5, played mostly small forward last season  
and will need to move his game to the perimeter as an off-guard, 
where he would probably play in the NBA. He averaged 18.9 points 
and 10.5 rebounds, using his jumping quickness, long arms and 
uncanny sense of timing to scrap on the boards with bigger players. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, chosen the nation's top freshman last year by the  
U.S. Basketball Writers Association, The Sporting News and 
Basketball News, will acquire an insurance policy against injury 
this season, his sister said. 
</P>
<P>
	The most disappointing aspect of Richardson's first season at  
DePaul was the Blue Demons' failure to make the NCAA tournament. 
Led by fellow freshmen and Chicago prep stars Bobby Simmons and 
Lance Williams, DePaul had to settle for the NIT, where a 
first-round win over Northwestern was the school's first victory in 
the postseason since 1990. The Blue Demons (18-13) were eliminated 
in the second round by eventual NIT champ California. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, who attended the news conference, was glad to have his  
friend and teammate back for another season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was playing with me, telling me he was coming back and then  
telling me he was going. Now we have a chance to have a great 
team,'' Williams said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 05:35:11 </DATE_TIME>
