<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Switched-Baby Mom May Sue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENA VISTA, Va. (AP) -- Paula Johnson, the mother of one of the  
3-year-old girls switched at birth, will sue for custody of her 
biological daughter and also wants to keep the other girl, whom she 
is raising, her lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paula is going to assert her constitutional right to raise her  
own child,'' attorney John Blakely said. ``We are going to file a 
petition to obtain full custody as soon as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Johnson also will appeal a judge's approval Monday of the $2  
million settlement between the state and the families who are 
raising her biological daughter, Rebecca Chittum, the attorney 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the agreement provides money for the grandparents who  
share custody of Rebecca. Blakely told Circuit Judge Thomas Wood 
the settlement was insufficient and that at least $1 million should 
go solely to the child. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no reason to divert any of this money away from this  
child to the grandparents,'' Blakely said. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would come from the state, which runs the University  
of Virginia Medical Center, where Rebecca Chittum and Callie Conley 
were switched in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Johnson took the real Rebecca home, believing she was her  
daughter Callie Conley, and the girl has been known as Callie 
Conley ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the real Callie went home with Kevin Chittum and  
Whitney Rogers, and has been known as Rebecca Chittum ever since. 
The couple died in a car crash last July 4, around the time the 
switch was discovered. Rebecca is being raised by the parents of 
Chittum and Ms. Rogers. 
</P>
<P>
	Blakely said Ms. Johnson plans to maintain custody of Callie.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is no constitutionally protected right of grandparents  
to have custody of grandchildren,'' he said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the switch was never determined.  
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Blakely had set the stage for a challenge to  
Rebecca's custodial grandparents, but said Ms. Johnson had made no 
firm decision on whether to seek custody of her biological 
daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The natural mother has a God-given right to raise her child  
and is the natural custodian of her own child,'' Blakely told Wood. 
``They have no blood relationship to Rebecca.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute over how much money the two children and their  
families deserve for the mix-up has ruined an informal custody and 
visitation agreement. Visitations have ended, and feelings between 
the two families have soured. 
</P>
<P>
	``If your child were in the care of someone else,'' Blakely told  
the newspaper, ``and you saw some of the money that you think 
should be going to your child going to people to whom it doesn't 
belong, you'd be upset and wonder whether or not something should 
be done about the placement of that child.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
