<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 06:55:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Claims Drop in Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Claims for unemployment benefits in Spain  
fell to 10.78 percent of the workforce in March from 10.94 percent 
in February, the Labor Ministry reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of March around 1.76 million people were registered  
to receive benefits, down from 1.78 million at the end of February, 
the ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	March's jobless rate was the lowest since December 1981, the  
government said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry's rate is one of two used to measure unemployment  
in Spain. Analysts, however, tend to watch the National Statistics 
Institute's quarterly unemployment survey more closely because it 
covers everyone who is out of work, not just those eligible for 
unemployment benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the institute, the unemployment rate stood at 18.17  
percent in the fourth quarter of 1998, down from 18.55 percent in 
the third quarter. Spain has the highest unemployment rate in the 
European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
