<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, American Stock 
Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Gillette, fell 7 3/4 to 50    	
</P>
<P>
	The consumer products company said it expects to earn 24 cents a  
share in the first quarter, missing Wall Street's targets by a 
penny. Gillette said weakness in its Braun electric shaver business 
and in Latin America hurt results. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and 
Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co. lower their ratings of the stock. 

</P>
<P>
 *National Propane Partners LP, rose 4 1/2 to 11 5/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Propane Corp. will acquire National Propane in a cash  
tender offer valued at $12 a common unit, or $80.4 million. 

</P>
<P>
 *Core Laboratories, fell 5 1/16 to 12 9/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Core Laboratories said weakness in oilfield activities will push  
1999 earnings significantly below last year's level. The company, 
which handles reservoir management, said weak demand for some of 
its services will continue into the second half of 1999. 

</P>
<P>
 *Media Arts Group Inc., rose 3/8 to 10 5/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The maker of gifts, collectibles and decorative accessories has  
formed a new unit to research Internet business opportunities. 
Media Arts also said it will open 115 new independently owned 
stores. 

</P>
<P>
                               *AMEX    	

</P>
<P>
 *Allou Health Care &AMP; Beauty, rose 2 3/16 to 13 1/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Internet Stock News, a Web-based investment newsletter, added  
Allou to a group of stocks dubbed ``Ones to Watch in 1999.'' Allou 
runs The Fragrance Counter and CosmeticsCounter.com, electronic 
commerce sites that sell perfume and makeup. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *MCI WorldCom Inc., fell 2 15/16 to 89 9/16  
</P>
<P>
 *Nextel Communications, fell 7/16 to 39 3/16 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported that MCI WorldCom, the nation's  
second-biggest long-distance phone company, is in preliminary talks 
about acquiring wireless phone service provider Nextel. 

</P>
<P>
 *Yahoo! Inc., fell 4 1/4 to 214 7/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! shareholders finally sold off some stock after watching  
its shares rise 39 3/16 Monday. Yahoo! continued to rise this 
morning in advance of its first-quarter earnings report, expected 
Wednesday after the market closes. Analysts have called for the 
popular Web site operator to earn 8 cents a share, but many believe 
Yahoo! will top that estimate. 

</P>
<P>
 *TCI Music, rose 21 3/16 to 29 9/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Media offered to swap its Internet and interactive TV  
assets for TCI's series B stock and a $50 million loan. The deal 
calls for TCI to acquire Liberty's equity stakes in online 
companies like Priceline.com Inc., iVillage Inc., SportsLine USA 
Inc. and Drugstore.com. 

</P>
<P>
 *Heuristic Development Group, rose 2 11/16 to 4 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	Heuristic will acquire Virtual Communities Inc., a creator of  
Web sites including Virtual Jerusalem and Virtual HolyLand. 
Heuristic was looking for a way to refocus its business after its 
main product, a computerized system that created exercise programs, 
failed to impress test customers. 

</P>
<P>
 *Novel Denim, fell 2 13/16 to 6 15/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The supplier of denim and chino clothing said it expects  
earnings in its recently ended fourth quarter to miss analysts' 
expectations. Novel Denim said it expects to earn 28 cents to 32 
cents a share; analysts surveyed by First Call had estimated 
earnings of 43 cents a share. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
