<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:45:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How the Earnings Test Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	President Clinton and Republicans in Congress are contemplating  
eliminating Social Security penalties for people ages 65 to 69 who 
earn income from work. How the penalty, known as the earnings test, 
currently works: 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	For people ages 65 and over:  
</P>
<P>
	Retirement benefits are reduced by $1 for every $3 of income  
earned from work above $15,500 a year in 1999. Investment income is 
not counted. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a senior citizen entitled to the current average  
Social Security benefit -- $9,360 a year -- who earned $20,000 a year 
from work would lose $1,500 in Social Security benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The $15,500 earnings limit that triggers the penalty is  
scheduled to rise to $17,000 in 2000, to $25,000 in 2001 and to 
$30,000 in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	In order to get compensation -- called delayed retirement credits  
-- for the lost benefits, a person must forego their entire Social 
Security check during each month worked. Once he or she stops 
earning above the limit -- or reaches age 70, when the penalty no 
longer applies -- Social Security checks are increased, to take 
account of each month worked, at a current rate of 5.5 percent per 
year worked. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the average Social Security benefit now is $780 a  
month. Senior citizens who forfeit those checks entirely starting 
at age 65 in 1999 until age 70 in 2004 would, upon their 70th 
birthdays, draw benefits of about $995 a month -- a 5.5 percent 
increase for each of the five years of lost checks -- for the rest 
of their lives. 
</P>
<P>
	The delayed retirement credit is scheduled to rise incrementally  
until it reaches 8 percent a year for workers born in 1943 and 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	For people ages 62 to 64 who take Social Security's early  
retirement option: 
</P>
<P>
	Benefits are reduced by $1 for every $2 earned above $9,600 a  
year in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Even partial loss of benefits entitles a person to compensation  
later. But it is not available until the person's 65th birthday, 
even if work stops sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	Most proposals to eliminate the earnings test penalty do not  
include this age group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:36:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bombed Yugoslav Town a Grisly Scene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Search teams dug through a row of  
bombed-out apartment buildings Tuesday, pushing aside twisted 
steel, chunks of concrete and splintered wood in hopes of finding 
survivors of a NATO airstrike that obliterated the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The overnight attack killed 12 people in Aleksinac, a mining  
town of 17,000 people, the official Tanjug news agency reported. 
Dozens of others were wounded in the raid, Serbian television said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the worst single report of civilian casualties since NATO  
airstrikes began March 24. The town is located 100 miles south of 
Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Two corpses, pools of blood and parts of dismembered bodies lay  
Tuesday among crumbled heaps of corrugated steel and seared brick. 
Bewildered residents picked through debris to recover belongings. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoke curled from a home along a residential street that caught  
fire during the raid. Bricks, boards and roof tiles were strewn 
about, some thrown up to 200 yards by the blast. 
</P>
<P>
	At the entrance of the local hospital, Dr. Bratislav  
Miladinovic, appeared dazed and in shock. He was on duty at the 
time of the strike, and only later learned that it killed his 
sister and father. His wife and child were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, Belgium, NATO said the strike had been aimed at a  
nearby military post housing an artillery brigade, and that it was 
investigating. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO Air Commodore David Wilby of Britain said it was possible  
that one of the weapons ``fell short'' due to a guidance system 
fault, incoming fire or another cause and that ``any unintended 
damage'' was ``very much regretted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian Prime Minister Mirko Marjanovic, who visited the site  
Tuesday, accused NATO of ``genocide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Since there are no military targets nearby, the objective of  
the criminal aggressors is evident -- to kill Serb civilians,'' 
Marjanovic said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0290 </DOCNO>
