<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Sets March Sales Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- With record-breaking demand for its pickups and  
sport utility vehicles, Ford Motor Co. took advantage of Americans' 
love affair with trucks to post its best March ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 2 automaker reported Tuesday that its U.S. sales were up  
14 percent in March over the same month a year ago, based on the 
daily sales rate. Ford broke a long list of company records, led by 
its strongest monthly sales of light trucks ever. 
</P>
<P>
	March sales of F-series pickups, the nation's top-selling  
vehicle for 17 years, were the highest for any car or truck in any 
month since June 1978. Ford sold 85,686 of the full-size pickups 
last month, more than many models achieve over an entire year. The 
June '78 record was 90,370 F-series trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's car sales, excluding its Jaguar unit, were up nearly 6  
percent while its light truck sales increased 19 percent to set a 
record for any month. SUV sales were up 11 percent while total 
pickup sales were up 28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The news was especially good for Ford because pickups and SUVs  
carry the highest profit margins. Much of the big increase in 
F-series sales was due to robust demand for the new F-250 and F-350 
Super Duty trucks built at Ford's Louisville, Ky., truck plant, 
which has been running full-tilt with three shifts. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're crying all the way to the bank,'' said analyst David  
Healy of Burnham Securities Inc. ``The models that are the most 
profitable for them have the biggest year-over-year increase in 
sales.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford announced Tuesday that it was increasing its second-quarter  
production by 20,000 trucks and 10,000 cars to meet the strong 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Explorer and Expedition SUVs also set March sales records,  
while the new Mercury Cougar and the Escort ZX2 coupes had their 
best sales months yet. Ford's minivan sales were up 23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Ford closed  
down 6 1/4 cents to $58.25 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's report comes after last week's largely upbeat sales  
figures from DaimlerChrysler AG and most major foreign automakers. 
General Motors Corp., the No. 1 automaker, is expected to report 
slightly higher March sales on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Rewey, Ford vice president of marketing and sales, said a  
stable economy marked by high consumer confidence, income growth, 
low inflation and interest rates was behind the robust demand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both Wall Street and Main Street respond favorably to  
consistency and stability,'' Rewey said. ``We believe that stable 
fiscal and monetary policy have played a key role in the duration 
of this expansion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Healy said he does not see any drop in the high demand in the  
short term. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see anything in the picture that's going to slow this  
down unless gasoline prices keep going up 30 cents a gallon every 
week,'' he said. ``At this point, the gasoline thing is just a 
minor irritant to people who want to buy an Expedition or an 
Excursion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jaguar's sales were down 17 percent last month.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
