<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 23:41:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woods, Duvall To Make Masters Show?  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- It took two years to do it, but the people  
who run the Masters finally made the changes to Augusta National to 
try and stop Tiger Woods from running away with too many green 
jackets. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe they needn't have bothered. The way David Duval is  
playing, he'll see to it himself. 
</P>
<P>
	In the time it took to lengthen a few holes, plant some new  
trees and deepen the rough along Augusta's generous fairways, a new 
force wearing wraparound sunglasses emerged to shake up the golf 
world's balance of power. 
</P>
<P>
	And as the 63rd Masters prepares to unfold Thursday, Duval finds  
himself slipping more and more comfortably into the favorite's role 
many assumed Woods would easily hold for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I'm ready to play and I go out and play well and think  
clearly, I'll have a chance to win,'' Duval said. 
</P>
<P>
	Just two years have passed since Woods routed the field by 12  
shots to win his first Masters only a few months after he was old 
enough to drink legally. No less an expert than Jack Nicklaus 
predicted Woods might win 10 green jackets. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Duval had yet to win a PGA tournament. His  
reputation was growing, but mainly for a propensity to finish 
second a lot. While Woods was trying on his new green jacket in 
1997, Duval was long gone after missing the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Oh, how things have changed.  
</P>
<P>
	Duval started winning shortly after, and it seems like he can't  
stop. Seven wins came in little more than a year, and he's added 
four more this year, including the last two. 
</P>
<P>
	``His golf game, it's incredible,'' Fred Couples said. ``He's  
winning and it looks very easy. I just haven't seen anyone do 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The wins were enough to knock Woods from atop the world  
rankings, and spark the beginnings of a rivalry that golf fans can 
only hope will be tested with a head-to-head showdown on a spring 
Sunday in Augusta. 
</P>
<P>
	While Duval comes in having won two straight, Woods also has  
been playing well and is rested after taking off the BellSouth 
Classic last week in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's playing better, no doubt about it,'' Woods said of Duval.  
``But I like my chances, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So does defending champion Mark O'Meara, who thinks Duval's hot  
streak might be just the thing to rejuvenate the competitive juices 
of his neighbor and frequent playing partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``He (Woods) wants to be the man. David wants to be the man.  
That's good for golf,'' O'Meara said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval and Woods top a crowded field of 96 golfers who will  
follow the honorary group of Gene Sarazen, Byron Nelson and Sam 
Snead off the first tee Thursday. It's the biggest Masters field in 
33 years and will play in threesomes for the first time since 1962 
because of its size. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not the only thing different in a tournament where  
tradition weighs heavy and change comes slowly and often 
unannounced. 
</P>
<P>
	A new back tee on the par-5 second will make it difficult for  
most golfers to reach in two, and another on 17 will bring into 
play the pine tree on the left side of the fairway that President 
Eisenhower made famous by saying it should be cut down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously they've made changes, and the scores will be  
higher,'' said Couples, who lost last year when O'Meara made a 
20-footer for birdie on the last hole. ``There's no way they're 
going to be lower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Meara, who served sushi and fajitas as host of the the  
champion's dinner Tuesday night, seems almost forgotten in the 
hoopla surrounding Duval's dominant play. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval was in the clubhouse last year tied with Couples at 8  
under when O'Meara snuffed any chances of a playoff by making 
birdies on the last two holes to win by a shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter what happens this week or in the future, I was able  
to step up to the plate and win at least one,'' O'Meara said. ``The 
game doesn't owe me anything, and I know that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Meara, who added a British Open title to give him two majors  
in one year after playing 18 years without any, was the PGA Tour's 
player of the year last year in a close race with Duval. This year, 
it hasn't been close. 
</P>
<P>
	``What David has done in the last two years in professional golf  
is absolutely incredible,'' he said. ``You know, he's been pretty 
low-key about it. But let's face it, in today's era of unbelievably 
talented deep fields, to win the amount of events he's won is 
phenomenal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duval was so low-key Tuesday he didn't bother to play for a  
second straight day. Instead, he hit a few balls and worked on his 
chipping. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, he talked about how he elevated his game to another level  
when he quit worrying about bad shots or where balls would end up. 
That is especially important at Augusta, where the bounces and 
kicks can be unnerving. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you have to learn to be very conservative here, very  
patient, and accept that you're going to hit some good shots that 
are going to end up 50 feet away,'' Duval said. ``You're going to 
get some kicks off of some hills that you're not going to 
particularly like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if the kicks mostly go right and Duval finds himself in  
position to win his first major at the age of 27? 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'm prepared for it,'' he said. ``I think last year's  
event here certainly helped in that fashion.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
