<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kosovo Refugees Get Temporary Homes  
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO is taking pressure off neighboring  
Balkan states by flying tens of thousands Kosovo Albanian refugees 
to temporary homes. More than 1,000 exhausted refugees stumbled off 
planes in Turkey and Norway. Some refugees will be flown as far as 
Australia. The flights began from Macedonia late yesterday and 
continued today. A daylong airlift to Turkey was carrying 3,500 
refugees on 10 flights, Macedonian's vice premier said. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Sites Targeted by NATO  
</P>
<P>
	ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Allied warplanes blasted fuel  
depots, oil refineries, roads and bridges in the most intensive 
night of air raids across Yugoslavia. The refugee airlift has 
begun, meanwhile, for the first of at least 110,000 ethnic 
Albanians who have fled Yugoslav forces in Kosovo for Albania, 
Macedonia and Montenegro. More than 400,000 ethnic Albanians have 
left the embattled Serbian province since the NATO air campaign 
began nearly two weeks ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockerbie Suspects in Dutch Court  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- Two Libyan suspects in the 1988  
Pan Am jet bombing listened today while the names of all 270 
victims were read aloud by the Scottish authorities who will try 
them at a deserted U.S. airbase. Suspected former intelligence 
agents Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah were 
fingerprinted, photographed and gave DNA samples one day after 
Libya surrendered them for trial. The Libyans will be arraigned 
today on a 1991 indictment accusing them of blowing up Flight 103 
over Lockerbie, Scotland. 

</P>
<P>
	3 Well-Preserved Inca Mummies Found  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Archeologists have discovered three  
well-preserved Inca mummies high in the Andes Mountains, the 
National Geographic Society said today. The three, relics of an 
Inca sacrificial ritual, were found beneath 5 feet of rock and 
earth on a burial platform atop Argentina's Mount Llullaillaco. The 
bodies of two girls and a boy may have been frozen since being 
placed there some 500 years ago. An archeologist said tests on the 
mummies showed all internal organs intact and blood appeared to 
still be present in the heart and lungs, as if the three had died 
only recently. 

</P>
<P>
	News Corp. To Buy Liberty Media  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- News Corp. plans to expand its cable television  
reach, buying ``substantially all'' of Liberty Media's portion of a 
joint venture in a $1.43 billion stock swap. The Fox/Liberty 
Network is half-owned by Liberty and half-owned by News Corp. 
subsidiary Fox Entertainment Group. Under the deal, News Corp. will 
gain control of regional sports network Fox Sports Net, which 
reaches more than 62 million households across the United States, 
entertainment network FX, which reaches more than 39 million 
households, and other related businesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Prodigy Offers New Spanish Service  
</P>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Prodigy will offer a Spanish-language  
Internet access service to Spanish-speaking households in the 
United States. The service offers the same features available 
through Prodigy Internet, but also provides both customer service 
and technical support for Spanish-speaking customers. The service 
will be supported with Spanish-language advertising, news and links 
to other Hispanic Web sites and services. Visitors can also search 
the Internet with Spanish language search engines. 

</P>
<P>
	Leading Economic Indicators Rise  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A key economic barometer rose for a fifth  
straight month in February, signaling that the U.S. economy will 
continue to thrive at least through the summer. The Conference's 
Board said the Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose 0.2 
percent in February, in line with economists' expectations. Four of 
the 10 indicators that make up the leading index rose, including 
consumer expectations. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Dip Lower; Dow Down 62.99  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks dipped lower in early trading today as an  
earnings warning from Gillette helped put the brakes on yesterday's 
rally. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were down 62.99 
at 9,944.34. Declines on the New York Stock Exchange led advances 
1,417-1,055. The Nasdaq was up 0.19 to 2,560.25. 

</P>
<P>
	Greek Soccer Team Goes to Belgrade  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- In a show of solidarity with Yugoslavs  
facing daily airstrikes, a top Greek soccer team intends to play an 
exhibition game in Belgrade tomorrow. ``We've won many titles on 
the field, this will be a humanitarian title,'' said Dimitris 
Melissanidis, the president of AEK Athens. AEK Athens is scheduled 
to leave Greece today for its game against Partizan in the 
Yugoslavian capital. The Serbs welcomed the initiative but they 
reportedly failed to give the Greek team any safety guarantees. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

</P>
</TEXT>
