<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Declares Cease-Fire  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav leadership today  
declared a unilateral cease-fire in their battle against rebels in 
Kosovo to mark Orthodox Easter, hours after the most intensive 
night of NATO air raids across Yugoslavia. Western officials said 
the bombings would continue. It was unclear if the cease-fire would 
continue past the holiday Sunday, but NATO and U.S. officials had 
been expecting a cease-fire offering. Defense Secretary William 
Cohen said the Serb cease-fire idea is ``not only completely 
unacceptable but it's absurd.'' 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Base in Cuba To House Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As NATO airstrikes continued pummeling  
Yugoslavia today, the United States said its naval base at 
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, would be a ``safe haven'' for up to 20,000 
Kosovar refugees in the coming days. The refuge would be only 
temporary, said White House press secretary Joe Lockhart. ``We 
fully intend the Kosovars will ultimately return to their homes.'' 
The NATO campaign against Yugoslavia continued with ``a productive 
and aggressive'' round of bombing, Lockhart said. 

</P>
<P>
	Airstrikes Complicate China Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's visit to the  
United States comes at a time of tense relations between Beijing 
and Washington, including a dispute over the bombing of Yugoslavia. 
China has called for an immediate halt to the NATO airstrikes. Zhu, 
whose six-city, nine-day visit began today in Los Angeles, still 
hopes to close a deal with the Clinton administration to allow 
Beijing to join the World Trade Organization, which regulates 
international trade, after 13 years of trying. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Wants Hate-Law Expansion  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Decrying ``the persistence of old, even  
primitive hatreds,'' President Clinton today asked Congress to 
expand federal hate crime laws to include offenses based on sexual 
orientation. The president also directed the departments of 
Education and Justice to collect and periodically publish data on 
hate crimes at colleges, including crime statistics as well as 
surveys on students' racial attitudes. Clinton said Americans 
should resist destructive, biased attitudes because they imperil 
the country's future. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockerbie Suspects Arraigned  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- Two Libyan suspects in the 1988  
Pan Am jet bombing were arraigned by Scottish authorities at a 
deserted U.S. airbase today. Suspected former intelligence agents 
Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah were 
fingerprinted, photographed and gave DNA samples one day after 
Libya surrendered them for trial. The two men were then arraigned 
on charges contained in a 1991 U.S.-British indictment accusing 
them of planting the bomb that ripped apart Flight 103 over 
Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21, 1988. The attack killed 270 
people. 

</P>
<P>
	News Corp. To Buy Liberty Media  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rupert Murdoch is expanding his reach in cable  
television in the United States, buying out most of partner John 
Malone's interest in a joint venture for $1.4 billion. Murdoch's 
News Corp. will take over substantially all of the operations of 
the Fox/Liberty Network. News Corp. will gain control of regional 
sports network Fox Sports Net, which reaches more than 62 million 
U.S. households, the entertainment network FX, which reaches more 
than 39 million homes, and other related businesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Dylan, Simon To Tour Together  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's nirvana for 1960s folk fans -- Bob Dylan and  
Paul Simon are hitting the road together for a summer tour. It's 
the first time they have shared a concert bill. Each man will play 
a 75-minute set and, for most of the tour's 32 dates, they also 
plan a few duets. The tour starts June 6 in Colorado Springs, 
Colo., and ends at Jones Beach on New York's Long Island on July 
31. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 17.76 at 9,989.57  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks are mixed in late-day trading as an  
earnings warning from Gillette put the brakes on yesterday's rally. 
Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were down 17.76 at 
9,989.57. Declines on the New York Stock Exchange led advances 
1,716-1,201. The Nasdaq was up 16.25 to 2,576.31. 

</P>
<P>
	WNBA Nears Contract Deadline  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Another labor dispute could delay the start of  
another basketball season. The WNBA has given its players until 
Saturday to reach a contract agreement with the league. At the 
center of the disagreement is salaries, just as it was when the NBA 
locked out its players for six months, including nearly half the 
season. The players' union wants a minimum salary of $45,000 for 
the three-month summer season. The WNBA is proposing $20,000, 
according to the union. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

</P>
