<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> News Corp. To Buy Liberty Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Australian media mogul Rupert Murdoch is  
expanding his reach in cable television in the United States, 
buying out most of partner John Malone's interest in a joint 
venture for $1.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	News Corp., the media conglomerate controlled by Murdoch, will  
take over substantially all of the operations of the Fox/Liberty 
Network, which was founded three years ago as a venture between 
News Corp.'s Fox Entertainment Group and Malone's Liberty Media 
Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, announced late Monday evening, News Corp. will  
gain control of regional sports network Fox Sports Net, which 
reaches more than 62 million households across the United States, 
the entertainment network FX, which reaches more than 39 million 
households, and other related businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty will receive about 51.8 million U.S.-listed shares of  
News Corp., worth about $1.43 billion based on Monday's closing 
stock prices. In early trading today, News Corp.'s shares slipped 
31 1/4 cents to $33.50 on the New York Stock Exchange while Liberty 
Media shares rose $1.50 or 2.7 percent to $57.37 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation about the deal has been swirling for several days  
after published reports by several newspapers pushed News Corp.'s 
New York-listed shares to a 52-week high. 
</P>
<P>
	``In acquiring Liberty's interest in these properties, News  
Corporation has firmly established itself as the leader in original 
cable programming and distribution,'' Murdoch said. ``This deal 
will enable us to leverage more fully the Fox brand across our 
cable and broadcast properties while giving us added flexibility 
over our sports and entertainment channels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the deal, News Corp. will also take over the  
joint venture's 40 percent interest in Rainbow Programming, a unit 
of Cablevision that controls the New York Knicks basketball team, 
the New York Rangers hockey team and part of Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty will retain its 50 percent interest in International  
Sports Programming Partners, the international sports programming 
venture it has partnered with Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	News Corp. is one of the world's largest media companies with  
operations in the United States, Canada, the United Kingdom, 
Australia, Latin America and the Pacific Basin. It had revenue in 
1998 of $14 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Media is a subsidiary of AT&AMP;T Corp. and is one of  
nation's largest providers of cable television programming. Malone 
is the former head of Tele-Communications Inc., the cable giant 
acquired by AT&AMP;T. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
