<DOCNO> APW19990406.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:32:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charles Keating Enters Guilty Pleas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former Lincoln Savings &AMP; Loan CEO Charles  
Keating Jr., a central figure in the S&AMP;L scandal in the 1980s, has 
pleaded guilty to four counts of fraud in exchange for a plea 
agreement that allows him to go free. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-running case involved investors' loss of $200 million  
and the collapse of Lincoln Savings, which cost taxpayers $3.4 
billion. His previous convictions had been thrown out on appeal, 
but prosecutors said they would retry him. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Mariana Pfaelzer accepted the plea  
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Keating was sentenced to time he has spent in  
jail on previous convictions, totaling a bit less than five years 
in prison. The judge did not impose any fines, restitution or 
supervision by authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also dismissed fraud charges against Keating's son,  
Charles Keating III. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how he felt afterward, Keating said, ``Great.'' Asked what  
lay ahead, he said, ``Life.'' He declined further comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating pleaded guilty to three counts of wire fraud and one  
count of bankruptcy fraud. The latter count involved transfer of 
$975,000 from his American Continental Corp. to himself through 
relatives days before the company filed for bankruptcy protection. 
American Continental was parent of Lincoln Savings. 
</P>
<P>
	The plea followed an announcement by prosecutors in January that  
they planned to retry Keating and his son on charges that he 
defrauded investors who lost $200 million in worthless junk bonds 
issued by American Continental Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating's case returned to U.S. District Court earlier this year  
after an appellate court threw out the Keatings' 1992 federal 
convictions and said they deserved a new trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating, known for extravagant spending during his days as  
chairman of American Continental, was convicted in federal and 
state court on charges stemming from the collapse of Lincoln 
Savings. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors argued in the two trials that Keating looted Lincoln  
Savings of its assets to prop up American Continental. Bond 
purchasers, they said, were not told of the investment's risky 
nature. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating denied the allegations and blamed government regulators  
for Lincoln's collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Sharon McCaslin told Pfaelzer the deal  
was justified because Keating was accepting responsibility for 
fraud. McCaslin also said that so much time had passed that some 
witnesses may have difficulty recalling the events that led to 
Lincoln's collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the plea agreement, Keating faced a maximum sentence of  
20 years in prison followed by three years of supervised release, 
plus the fines and possible restitution to victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating served nearly five years in prison before the federal  
conviction was overturned on grounds some jurors learned of his 
earlier conviction in state court and discussed it in the jury 
room. Despite finding that the jury had based its verdict on the 
courtroom evidence, Pfaelzer ruled that jurors' exposure to outside 
information denied Keating a fair trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating's state conviction was voided as well on grounds that  
the trial judge issued improper instructions to the jury. The state 
of California is appealing that reversal. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating lawyer Stephen Neal said he thought there was little  
chance the case would be resurrected. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Keating's legal problems are not entirely over. He  
still faces $1.5 billion in civil judgments stemming from lawsuits 
filed by investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Keating III also was convicted in the federal trial. He  
was sentenced to eight years in prison, but remained free on bail 
pending appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990406.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 11:15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Majoli Eyes Bausch &AMP; Lomb Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. (AP) -- The stress fracture in her foot has  
healed, leading Iva Majoli to believe the health of her tennis game 
will follow suit soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Majoli, the 1997 French Open champion, earned just her fourth  
victory of the year Monday, defeating Sandra Nacuk 7-5, 6-3 in the 
opening round of the Bausch &AMP; Lomb Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel I'm getting closer and closer to the top players,''  
said Majoli, the 16th seed in this tournament and 32nd-ranked 
player in the world. ``1998 is over. I can start 1999 fresh. It's 
like a new beginning. I'm looking forward to my next matches and 
I'm working real hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No. 10 seed Chanda Rubin, No. 11 Magui Serna, No. 14 Virginia  
Ruano-Pascual and No. 15 Nathalie Dechy all won their first-round 
matches. They were the only seeds in action on a light opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	The stars -- Venus Williams, Lindsay Davenport and Monica Seles --  
were to take the court today in the $520,000 tournament, the last 
stop in the United States before most players head to Europe and 
the heart of the clay court season. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninth-seeded Anna Kournikova defeated Evgenia Koulikovskaya 6-1,  
7-5 in one of the early matches. Koulikovskaya was a late entry, 
earning her spot after Andrea Glass dropped out with a hip injury. 
Also in morning action, 13th seed Lisa Raymond defeated Larisa 
Neiland 3-6, 6-1, 6-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Majoli had today off in the final stop in the United States  
before most of the women head to Europe and the heart of the clay 
court season. 
</P>
<P>
	That's normally the season Majoli likes most and she hopes to  
use it to re-enter her name among the world's elite. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look at some of the girls and I think to myself, I can get  
in front of these girls,'' said Majoli, who missed the end of 1998 
and a good portion of this year with the stress fracture. ``I want 
to get back. I feel I can be up there for the next few years. The 
young players are coming, but I've got a good, aggressive game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On a much lengthier comeback trail is Jennifer Capriati, who  
defeated Sylvia Plischke 7-5, 6-3 for just her fourth victory of 
the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Capriati entered the tournament ranked 81st in the world and  
will take another month off after this week to work with her new 
coach, Harold Solomon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm beginning to believe I can win again,'' Capriati said.  
``My tennis is good enough that I can still beat some of these 
players. I think Harold Solomon, in a short time, has helped me to 
believe that, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capriati persevered through a sloppy first set that took exactly  
an hour to complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Plischke, ranked 39th in the world, strained her thigh muscle  
early in the second set and Capriati hurried to a 5-0 lead. 
Capriati lost the next three games, but broke Plischke's serve for 
the eighth time in the match to close it out. 
</P>
<P>
	``All this was part of it being the first match on clay'' this  
year, Capriati said. ``It's about making adjustments, getting used 
to the bad bounces and stuff. Every game was close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another player slowly moving up the rankings is Tara Snyder of  
Wichita, Kan. She took center court early in the day and beat 
Larissa Schaerer of Paraguay 6-2, 6-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder, ranked 36th, will play seventh-seeded Conchita Martinez  
tonight. She'll take the confidence she gained in a second-round 
victory here last year against last year's seventh seed, Irina 
Spirlea, on the way to a quarterfinal appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to keep working on the physical aspect, especially  
with my legs, trying to build a good base underneath me,'' Snyder 
said. ``That's one thing that sets Venus, Serena and Davenport 
apart. They're so strong and they can pound away at it on the 
baseline.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
